{"title_page": "Romani people in the Czech Republic", "text_new": "{{refimprove|date=October 2013}}\n{{Romani people}}\n[[Romani people]] ({{lang-cs|Romov\u00e9}}, commonly known as '''Gypsies''' {{lang-cs|Cik\u00e1ni}}) are an ethnic minority in the [[Czech Republic]], currently Roma making up 2\u20133% of the population. Originally migrants from North Western India sometime between the 6th and 11th centuries, they have long had a presence in the region. Since the creation of [[First Czechoslovak Republic|Czechoslovakia]] in 1918, the Romani population have experienced considerable hardship, having been a main target of [[Porajmos|Nazi extermination programs]] during [[World War II]], and the subject of forced relocation and other radical social policies during the [[Czechoslovak Socialist Republic|Communist era]]. In the successor state, the Czech Republic, challenges remain for the Romani population with respect to education and poverty, and there are frequent tensions with the ethnically Czech majority population over issues including crime and integration.\n\n==Demographics==\nAccording to the 2011 census, the Romani population was 13,150,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://zpravy.ihned.cz/c1-54211050-k-romske-narodnosti-se-verejne-hlasi-13-150-lidi-mene-nez-k-rytirum-jedi-ze-star-wars|title=K romsk\u00e9 n\u00e1rodnosti se ve\u0159ejn\u011b hl\u00e1s\u00ed 13 150 lid\u00ed. M\u00e9n\u011b ne\u017e k Ryt\u00ed\u0159\u016fm jedi ze Star Wars|trans-title=13,150 people publicly declare themselves to have Romani Nationality, less than Jedi Knights from Star Wars|date=15 December 2011|work=Hospod\u00e1\u0159sk\u00e9 Noviny|language=Czech|accessdate=3 June 2018}}</ref> 0.2% of the total number reporting some nationality. Of these, 5,199 responded by listing only Romani nationality; the remaining 7,951 listed their Romani nationality in combination with another nationality, for example, Romani and Czech, Romani and Moravian and so on. In the 2001 Census, 11,746 people reported their nationality as Romani \u2013 0.1% of those claiming some nationality. \n\nHowever, 40,370 respondents to the 2011 census reported [[Romani language]] as their language.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://vdb.czso.cz/vdbvo2/faces/cs/index.jsf?page=statistiky#katalog=30261|url-status=dead|title=Z\u00e1kladn\u00ed v\u00fdsledky|date=29 May 2012|archivedate=29 May 2012}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n=== Origin ===\nThe Romani people originate from [[North India|Northern India]],{{sfn|Hancock|2002 |p= [https://books.google.com/?id=MG0ahVw-kdwC&lpg=PP1&pg=PR20  xx] | ps =: \u2018While a nine century removal from India has diluted Indian biological connection to the extent that for some Romanian groups, it may be hardly representative today, Sarren (1976:72) concluded that we still remain together, genetically, Asian rather than European\u2019}}<ref name=\"IsabelMendizabal\">{{cite journal| doi = 10.1016/j.cub.2012.10.039|first=Isabel|last=Mendizabal|title=Reconstructing the Population History of European Romani from Genome-wide Data|journal=Current Biology|date=6 December 2012|volume=22| issue = 24|pages=2342\u20132349|pmid=23219723}}</ref><ref name=\"Comas\">{{cite news|author=Sindya N. Bhanoo|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2012/12/11/science/genomic-study-traces-roma-to-northern-india.html?_r=0|title=Genomic Study Traces Roma to South India|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|date=11 December 2012}}</ref><ref>''Current Biology''.</ref><ref name=\"google1\">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=AS61CgAAQBAJ&pg=PA50&dq=Roma+Rajastan+Penjab#v=snippet&q=Roma%20Rajasthan%20Punjab&f=false |title=Flamenco on the Global Stage: Historical, Critical and Theoretical Perspectives |author1=K. Meira Goldberg |author2=Ninotchka Devorah Bennahum |author3=Michelle Heffner Hayes |page=50 |accessdate=2016-05-21|isbn=9780786494705 |date=2015-09-28 }}</ref><ref name=\"google2\">{{cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/roughguidetoworl00simo |url-access=registration |quote=Roma Rajastan Penjab. |title=World Music: Africa, Europe and the Middle East |publisher=Rough Guides |author1=Simon Broughton |author2=Mark Ellingham |author3=Richard Trillo |page=[https://archive.org/details/roughguidetoworl00simo/page/147 147] |accessdate=2016-05-21|isbn=9781858286358 |year=1999 }}</ref> most likely from the northwestern Indian states [[Rajasthan]]<ref name=\"google1\"/><ref name=\"google2\"/> and [[Punjab, India|Punjab]].<ref name=\"google1\"/> Linguistic evidence indicates that the roots of Romani language lie in India; the language shares grammatical characteristics with Indian languages, as well as a large part of the basic lexicon, such as body parts or daily routines.<ref name=\"mluvnice\">{{Citation | last1 = \u0160ebkov\u00e1 | first1 = Hana | last2 = \u017dlnayov\u00e1 | first2 = Edita | year = 1998 | url = http://rss.archives.ceu.hu/archive/00001112/01/118.pdf | title = N\u00e1stin mluvnice slovensk\u00e9 rom\u0161tiny (pro pedagogick\u00e9 \u00fa\u010dely) | place = \u00dast\u00ed nad Labem | publisher = Pedagogick\u00e1 fakulta Univerzity J. E. Purkyn\u011b v \u00dast\u00ed nad Labem | page = 4 | isbn = 978-80-7044-205-0 | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20160304024041/http://rss.archives.ceu.hu/archive/00001112/01/118.pdf | archivedate = 2016-03-04 }}</ref> More specifically, Romani shares its basic lexicon with [[Hindi]] and [[Punjabi language|Punjabi]]. It shares many phonetic features with [[Marwari (language)|Marwari]], while its grammar is closest to [[Bengali language|Bengali]].<ref name=\"hub1995\">{{cite journal|first=Milena|last=H\u00fcbschmannov\u00e1|title=Roma\u0148i \u010dhib \u2013 rom\u0161tina: N\u011bkolik z\u00e1kladn\u00edch informac\u00ed o romsk\u00e9m jazyku|journal=Bulletin Muzea Romsk\u00e9 Kultury|issue=4/1995|year= 1995 |publisher= Muzeum romsk\u00e9 kultury|place=Brno|quote=Zat\u00edmco romsk\u00e1 lexika je bli\u017e\u0161\u00ed hind\u0161tin\u011b, marv\u00e1r\u0161tin\u011b, pand\u017e\u00e1b\u0161tin\u011b atd., v gramatick\u00e9 sf\u00e9\u0159e nach\u00e1z\u00edme mnoho shod s v\u00fdchodoindick\u00fdm jazykem, s beng\u00e1l\u0161tinou.}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Z\u00e1kaz vstupu potuln\u00fdch cik\u00e1n\u016f a tul\u00e1k\u016f.jpg|thumb|Sign banning entry of itinerant Gypsies and rovers, 1920s]]\nThe results of a genetic study in 2012 suggest that the Romani originated in North Western India and migrated as a group.<ref name=\"IsabelMendizabal\"/><ref name=\"Comas\"/><ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.livescience.com/40652-facts-about-roma-romani-gypsies.html|title=5 Intriguing Facts About the Roma|work=Live Science}}</ref> The study indicates that the ancestors of present scheduled tribes and scheduled caste populations of [[North India]], traditionally referred to collectively as the [[\u1e0coma]], are the likely ancestors of modern European Roma.<ref>{{Citation | last1 = Rai | first1 = N | last2 = Chaubey | first2 = G | last3 = Tamang | first3 = R | last4 = Pathak | first4 = AK | last5 = Singh | first5 = VK  | year = 2012 | title = The Phylogeography of Y-Chromosome Haplogroup H1a1a-M82 Reveals the Likely Indian Origin of the European Romani Populations | journal = PLoS ONE | volume = 7 | number = 11 | page = e48477 | doi = 10.1371/journal.pone.0048477 | pmid=23209554 | pmc=3509117}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2016, during the International Roma Conference, the [[Minister of External Affairs (India)|Indian Minister of External Affairs]] stated that the people of the Roma community were children of India. The conference ended with a recommendation to the [[Government of India]] to recognize the Roma community spread across 30 countries as a part of the [[Indian diaspora]].<ref name=\"diaspora\">{{cite web|title=Can Romas be part of Indian diaspora?|publisher=khaleejtimes.com|url=http://www.khaleejtimes.com/international/india/can-romas-be-part-of-indian-diaspora|date=29 February 2016|accessdate=4 March 2016}}</ref>\n\n=== World War II ===\n{{See also|Porajmos}}\nDuring the [[Nazi occupation of Czechoslovakia]] in [[World War II]], Romani were exterminated by [[Nazi Germany|Nazi]] mobile killing units and in camps such as [[Lety concentration camp|Lety]], [[Hodonin concentration camp|Hodon\u00edn]] and [[Auschwitz]]. 90% of native Romani were killed during the war; the Romani in modern-day Czech Republic are mostly post-war immigrants from Slovakia or Hungary and their descendants.\n\n=== Communist era ===\n{{main|Romani people in Czechoslovakia}}\nDuring the communist years unsuccessful attempts to change the nomadic living style of Romani were undertaken by the government. Many Romani people were rehoused in ''[[panel\u00e1k]]'' housing estates, which subsequently fell into acute disrepair, such as the [[Ch\u00e1nov housing estate]] near [[Most (Most District)|Most]].<ref>[http://www.sweb.cz/whitewoman/chanov/english.htm Chanov - urban settlement without trees and flowers]</ref> After 1989, some Romani women accused the state of \"forced sterilizations\" arguing that they were not properly informed of what \"sterilization\" meant.<ref>[http://www.psychologia.sk/empatia/11.htm Radim Uzel: Jak to bylo s n\u00e1silnou sterilizac\u00ed u Rom\u016f v \u010ceskoslovensku?]</ref> According to Czech ombudsman [[Otakar Motejl]], \"at least 50 Romani women were unlawfully sterilized\".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://aktualne.centrum.cz/clanek.phtml?id=40065|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110522081313/http://aktualne.centrum.cz/clanek.phtml?id=40065|url-status=dead|archive-date=22 May 2011|title=Otakar Motejl: Nez\u00e1konn\u011b bylo sterilizov\u00e1no nejm\u00e9n\u011b 50 \u017een|trans-title=Otakar Motejl: At Least 50 Women Were Unlawfully Sterilized|language=Czech|date=29 December 2005|accessdate=3 June 2018|website=Aktu\u00e1ln\u011b.cz}}</ref> The Czech representative at the United Nations protested against the accusations, claiming that they were \"false\" and that Romani women \"exaggerate in all cases\".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://aktualne.centrum.cz/domaci/spolecnost/clanek.phtml?id=218615|title=\u010cesko \u0159eklo v OSN, \u017ee Romky p\u0159eh\u00e1n\u011bj\u00ed|trans-title=Czech Republic says in UN that Roma women exaggerate|website=Aktu\u00e1ln\u011b.cz|language=Czech|date=18 August 2006|accessdate=3 June 2018}}</ref> A hospital in Vitkovice, Ostrava, apologised to a Romani woman who was sterilised after her second [[Caesarean section|caesarean]], but a request for a compensation of 1 million Czech crowns was rejected by the court.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://aktualne.centrum.cz/domaci/spolecnost/clanek.phtml?id=333188|title=Soud:Za sterilizaci jen omluva,pen\u00edze ne|trans-title=Court: Apology for sterilization, no money|language=Czech|website=Aktu\u00e1ln\u011b.cz|date=17 January 2007|accessdate=3 June 2018}}</ref>\n\n== Emigration ==\nMany Romani left the country after the independence of the Czech Republic, saying that they felt unsafe due to a surge in right-wing activity. Countries such as Ireland, the UK, Norway and Sweden took in large numbers, but most Romani returned home after a few years. Immigration rates to Great Britain dropped suddenly after financial support for refugees started to be paid out in the form of food tickets in summer 2000 (due to the [[Immigration and Asylum Act 1999]]).<ref>*{{cite web |title=Roma And Emigration |url=http://www.varianty.cz/cdrom/podkapitoly/b02romove.pdf |work=Postoj politik\u016f k emigraci Rom\u016f (The Attitude Of Politicians To The Romani Emigration) |page=219 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070226080107/http://www.varianty.cz/cdrom/podkapitoly/b02romove.pdf |archivedate=2007-02-26 }}</ref> The following year, British customs officers began to check the passengers flying to the UK from Prague airport and routinely rejected those of Romani origin.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/czech/interview/seifter.htm|title=Interview with Pavel Seifter, Czech Ambassador to the UK|website=BBC|language=Czech|date=1 August 2001|accessdate=3 June 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|date=3 November 2004|url=http://www.britske-listy.cz/2004/11/3/art20418.html|archive-url=https://archive.is/20130210042328/http://www.britske-listy.cz/2004/11/3/art20418.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=10 February 2013|language=Czech|title=Pozdn\u00ed d\u016fkaz u britsk\u00fdch soud\u016f: Brit\u0161t\u00ed imigra\u010dn\u00ed \u00fa\u0159edn\u00edci v Ruzyni Romy skute\u010dn\u011b rasisticky diskriminovali|trans-title=Late proof in British courts: British immigration officers really did racially discriminated against Roma at Ruzyn\u011b airport|accessdate=3 June 2018|website=Britsk\u00e9 listy}}</ref> In October 1997, after receiving over 1,000 requests for asylum from Czech Roma within a single year, Canada reinstated a visa regime for Czech citizens.<ref>{{cite news|date=10 October 1997|title=Canada limits Czech visitors|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-srv/inatl/longterm/canada/stories/gypsies101097.htm|first=Howard|last=Schneider|accessdate=3 June 2018|work=The Washington Post}}</ref>\n\n==Anti-ziganism==\n{{see also|Antiziganism#Czech_Republic|l1=Antiziganism in the Czech Republic}}\n[[File:\u010cesk\u00e9 Bud\u011bjovice 29-6-2013 24.JPG|thumb|Violent anti-Roma protests in [[\u010cesk\u00e9 Bud\u011bjovice]] in 2013]]\nThe Romanis are at the centre of the agenda of far-right groups in the Czech Republic, which spread [[Anti-Romanyism|anti-ziganism]]. One highly publicized case was the [[V\u00edtkov arson attack of 2009]], in which four right-wing extremists seriously injured a three-year-old Romani girl. The public responded by donating money as well as presents to the family, who were able to buy a new house from the donations, while the perpetrators were sentenced to 18 and 22 years in prison.\n\nIn January 2010, Amnesty International launched a report titled ''Injustice Renamed: Discrimination in Education of Roma persists in the Czech Republic''.<ref>[https://www.amnesty.org/en/documents/eur71/003/2009/en/ ''Injustice Renamed: Discrimination in Education of Roma persists in the Czech Republic''] Amnesty International report, January 2010</ref> According to the [[BBC]], Amnesty argued that while cosmetic changes had been introduced by the authorities, little genuine improvement in addressing discrimination against Romani children had occurred.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/europe/8456882.stm|title=Amnesty says Czech schools still fail Roma Gypsies|date=13 January 2010|publisher=BBC News|accessdate=14 January 2010| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20100114052029/http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/europe/8456882.stm| archivedate= 14 January 2010 | url-status= live}}</ref>\n\nAccording to a 2010 opinion poll, 68% of Czechs have antipathy towards Romani.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://zpravy.idnes.cz/stem-dve-tretiny-cechu-nemaji-rady-romy-fc1-/domaci.asp?c=A070504_141136_domaci_mr|work=idnes.cz|date=4 May 2007|language=Czech|title=STEM: Dv\u011b t\u0159etiny \u010cech\u016f nemaj\u00ed r\u00e1dy Romy|trans-title=STEM: Two-thirds of Czechs dislike Roma|accessdate=3 June 2018}}</ref> The survey also found that 82% Czechs oppose any form of a \"special care of Roma rights\", 83% of Czechs consider Romani asocial, and 45% of Czechs would support the expulsion of Romani people from the Czech Republic.<ref>{{cite news|first=Jiri|last=St'astny |url=http://zpravy.idnes.cz/cesi-propadaji-anticikanismu-kazdy-druhy-tu-romy-nechce-zjistil-pruzkum-1qx-/domaci.asp?c=A101209_161615_domaci_js |title=\u010ce\u0161i propadaj\u00ed anticik\u00e1nismu, ka\u017ed\u00fd druh\u00fd tu Romy nechce, zjistil pr\u016fzkum|language=Czech|website=idnes.cz |date=9 December 2010 |accessdate=3 June 2018}}</ref>\n\nA 2011 poll, which followed a number of brutal attacks by Romani perpetrators against white victims, reported that 44% of Czechs are afraid of Roma people.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tyden.cz/rubriky/domaci/romsky-bloger-nekteri-romove-se-chovaji-jako-blazni_216270.html|title=Romsky bloger nekteri romove se chovaji jako blazni|language=Czech|accessdate=1 November 2011}}</ref> The majority of Czechs (90%) do not want Romani people as neighbours,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://translate.google.com/translate?u=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.romea.cz%2Findex.php%3Fid%3Dservis%2Fz2005_0318&hl=cs&ie=UTF8&sl=cs&tl=en|title=Czech don't want Roma as neighbours|language=Czech|accessdate=15 April 2007}}</ref> viewing them as thieves and social parasites. Despite a long waiting list for adoptive parents, Romani children from orphanages are almost never adopted by Czech couples.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.radio.cz/en/article/88089 |title=What is keeping children in orphanages when so many people want to adopt?|date=7 February 2007|website=Radio Prague|accessdate=17 May 2012}}</ref> After the [[Velvet Revolution]] in 1989 jobs traditionally employing Romanis either disappeared or were taken over by immigrant workers.{{citation needed|date=June 2013}}\n\nThe 2019 [[Pew Research Center|Pew Research poll]] found that 66% of Czechs held unfavorable views of Roma.<ref>{{cite news |title=European Public Opinion Three Decades After the Fall of Communism \u2014 6. Minority groups |url=https://www.pewresearch.org/global/2019/10/14/minority-groups/ |work=Pew Research Center |date=14 October 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Crime==\nCrime statistics from the early 1990s reported that the crime rate among the Romani population in Czechoslovakia was highly disproportionate, especially regarding burglaries. According to \u0158\u00ed\u010dan (1998), about 20\u201330% of the Romani population earn their livelihood in illegal ways, such as procuring prostitution, trafficking and other property crimes.<ref name=\"rican\">{{cite book |last= \u0158\u00ed\u010dan |first= Pavel |title= S Romy \u017e\u00edt budeme \u2013 jde o to jak: d\u011bjiny, sou\u010dasn\u00e1 situace, ko\u0159eny probl\u00e9m\u016f, nad\u011bje spole\u010dn\u00e9 budoucnosti |publisher= Port\u00e1l |location= Praha |year= 1998 |isbn= 978-80-7178-250-6 |pages=58\u201363 |url=https://books.google.com/?id=qtgmAAAAMAAJ&q=pavel+%C5%99%C3%AD%C4%8Dan+s+romy+%C5%BE%C3%ADt+budeme&dq=pavel+%C5%99%C3%AD%C4%8Dan+s+romy+%C5%BE%C3%ADt+budeme}}</ref> Romani make up more than 60% of the Czech prison population and about 50% of repeat offenders, and are thus more than 20 times over-represented in Czech prisons than their population share would suggest.<ref name=\"rican\"/>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Romani people in Czechoslovakia]]\n*[[D.H. and Others v. the Czech Republic]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Roma people in the Czech Republic}}\n* [http://www.czso.cz/sldb2011/eng/redakce.nsf/i/preliminary_results_of_the_2011_population_and_housing_census czso.cz]\n* [http://romove.radio.cz/en/ Roma in the Czech Republic] ([[Czech Radio]])\n* {{cite web |title=Romany communities: ways of living in relation to criminality (in the known of the Czech Republic and Slovakia) |url=http://www.epolis.cz/download/pdf/materials_31_1.pdf |first=Roman|last=Kri\u0161tof}}\n\n{{Ethnic and national minoritites in the Czech Republic}}\n{{Romani diaspora}}\n\n[[Category:Romani in the Czech Republic| ]]\n[[Category:Romani-related controversies]]\n", "text_old": "{{refimprove|date=October 2013}}\n{{Romani people}}\n[[Romani people]] ({{lang-cs|Romov\u00e9}}, commonly known as '''Gypsies''' {{lang-cs|Cik\u00e1ni}}) are an ethnic minority in the [[Czech Republic]], currently Roma making up 2\u20133% of the population. Originally migrants from North Western India sometime between the 6th and 11th centuries, they have long had a presence in the region. Since the creation of [[First Czechoslovak Republic|Czechoslovakia]] in 1918, the Romani population have experienced considerable hardship, having been a main target of [[Porajmos|Nazi extermination programs]] during [[World War II]], and the subject of forced relocation and other radical social policies during the [[Czechoslovak Socialist Republic|Communist era]]. In the successor state, the Czech Republic, challenges remain for the Romani population with respect to education and poverty, and there are frequent tensions with the ethnically Czech majority population over issues including crime and integration.\n\n==Demographics==\nAccording to the 2011 census, the Romani population was 13,150,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://zpravy.ihned.cz/c1-54211050-k-romske-narodnosti-se-verejne-hlasi-13-150-lidi-mene-nez-k-rytirum-jedi-ze-star-wars|title=K romsk\u00e9 n\u00e1rodnosti se ve\u0159ejn\u011b hl\u00e1s\u00ed 13 150 lid\u00ed. M\u00e9n\u011b ne\u017e k Ryt\u00ed\u0159\u016fm jedi ze Star Wars|trans-title=13,150 people publicly declare themselves to have Romani Nationality, less than Jedi Knights from Star Wars|date=15 December 2011|work=Hospod\u00e1\u0159sk\u00e9 Noviny|language=Czech|accessdate=3 June 2018}}</ref> 0.2% of the total number reporting some nationality. Of these, 5,199 responded by listing only Romani nationality; the remaining 7,951 listed their Romani nationality in combination with another nationality, for example, Romani and Czech, Romani and Moravian and so on. In the 2001 Census, 11,746 people reported their nationality as Romani \u2013 0.1% of those claiming some nationality. \n\nHowever, 40,370 respondents to the 2011 census reported [[Romani language]] as their language.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://vdb.czso.cz/vdbvo2/faces/cs/index.jsf?page=statistiky#katalog=30261|url-status=dead|title=Z\u00e1kladn\u00ed v\u00fdsledky|date=29 May 2012|archivedate=29 May 2012}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n=== Origin ===\nThe Romani people originate from [[North India|Northern India]],{{sfn|Hancock|2002 |p= [https://books.google.com/?id=MG0ahVw-kdwC&lpg=PP1&pg=PR20  xx] | ps =: \u2018While a nine century removal from India has diluted Indian biological connection to the extent that for some Romanian groups, it may be hardly representative today, Sarren (1976:72) concluded that we still remain together, genetically, Asian rather than European\u2019}}<ref name=\"IsabelMendizabal\">{{cite journal| doi = 10.1016/j.cub.2012.10.039|first=Isabel|last=Mendizabal|title=Reconstructing the Population History of European Romani from Genome-wide Data|journal=Current Biology|date=6 December 2012|volume=22| issue = 24|pages=2342\u20132349|pmid=23219723}}</ref><ref name=\"Comas\">{{cite news|author=Sindya N. Bhanoo|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2012/12/11/science/genomic-study-traces-roma-to-northern-india.html?_r=0|title=Genomic Study Traces Roma to South India|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|date=11 December 2012}}</ref><ref>''Current Biology''.</ref><ref name=\"google1\">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=AS61CgAAQBAJ&pg=PA50&dq=Roma+Rajastan+Penjab#v=snippet&q=Roma%20Rajasthan%20Punjab&f=false |title=Flamenco on the Global Stage: Historical, Critical and Theoretical Perspectives |author1=K. Meira Goldberg |author2=Ninotchka Devorah Bennahum |author3=Michelle Heffner Hayes |page=50 |accessdate=2016-05-21|isbn=9780786494705 |date=2015-09-28 }}</ref><ref name=\"google2\">{{cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/roughguidetoworl00simo |url-access=registration |quote=Roma Rajastan Penjab. |title=World Music: Africa, Europe and the Middle East |publisher=Rough Guides |author1=Simon Broughton |author2=Mark Ellingham |author3=Richard Trillo |page=[https://archive.org/details/roughguidetoworl00simo/page/147 147] |accessdate=2016-05-21|isbn=9781858286358 |year=1999 }}</ref> most likely from the northwestern Indian states [[Rajasthan]]<ref name=\"google1\"/><ref name=\"google2\"/> and [[Punjab, India|Punjab]].<ref name=\"google1\"/> Linguistic evidence indicates that the roots of Romani language lie in India; the language shares grammatical characteristics with Indian languages, as well as a large part of the basic lexicon, such as body parts or daily routines.<ref name=\"mluvnice\">{{Citation | last1 = \u0160ebkov\u00e1 | first1 = Hana | last2 = \u017dlnayov\u00e1 | first2 = Edita | year = 1998 | url = http://rss.archives.ceu.hu/archive/00001112/01/118.pdf | title = N\u00e1stin mluvnice slovensk\u00e9 rom\u0161tiny (pro pedagogick\u00e9 \u00fa\u010dely) | place = \u00dast\u00ed nad Labem | publisher = Pedagogick\u00e1 fakulta Univerzity J. E. Purkyn\u011b v \u00dast\u00ed nad Labem | page = 4 | isbn = 978-80-7044-205-0 | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20160304024041/http://rss.archives.ceu.hu/archive/00001112/01/118.pdf | archivedate = 2016-03-04 }}</ref> More specifically, Romani shares its basic lexicon with [[Hindi]] and [[Punjabi language|Punjabi]]. It shares many phonetic features with [[Marwari (language)|Marwari]], while its grammar is closest to [[Bengali language|Bengali]].<ref name=\"hub1995\">{{cite journal|first=Milena|last=H\u00fcbschmannov\u00e1|title=Roma\u0148i \u010dhib \u2013 rom\u0161tina: N\u011bkolik z\u00e1kladn\u00edch informac\u00ed o romsk\u00e9m jazyku|journal=Bulletin Muzea Romsk\u00e9 Kultury|issue=4/1995|year= 1995 |publisher= Muzeum romsk\u00e9 kultury|place=Brno|quote=Zat\u00edmco romsk\u00e1 lexika je bli\u017e\u0161\u00ed hind\u0161tin\u011b, marv\u00e1r\u0161tin\u011b, pand\u017e\u00e1b\u0161tin\u011b atd., v gramatick\u00e9 sf\u00e9\u0159e nach\u00e1z\u00edme mnoho shod s v\u00fdchodoindick\u00fdm jazykem, s beng\u00e1l\u0161tinou.}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Z\u00e1kaz vstupu potuln\u00fdch cik\u00e1n\u016f a tul\u00e1k\u016f.jpg|thumb|Sign banning entry of itinerant Gypsies and rovers, 1920s]]\nThe results of a genetic study in 2012 suggest that the Romani originated in North Western India and migrated as a group.<ref name=\"IsabelMendizabal\"/><ref name=\"Comas\"/><ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.livescience.com/40652-facts-about-roma-romani-gypsies.html|title=5 Intriguing Facts About the Roma|work=Live Science}}</ref> The study indicates that the ancestors of present scheduled tribes and scheduled caste populations of [[North India]], traditionally referred to collectively as the [[\u1e0coma]], are the likely ancestors of modern European Roma.<ref>{{Citation | last1 = Rai | first1 = N | last2 = Chaubey | first2 = G | last3 = Tamang | first3 = R | last4 = Pathak | first4 = AK | last5 = Singh | first5 = VK  | year = 2012 | title = The Phylogeography of Y-Chromosome Haplogroup H1a1a-M82 Reveals the Likely Indian Origin of the European Romani Populations | journal = PLoS ONE | volume = 7 | number = 11 | page = e48477 | doi = 10.1371/journal.pone.0048477 | pmid=23209554 | pmc=3509117}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2016, during the International Roma Conference, the [[Minister of External Affairs (India)|Indian Minister of External Affairs]] stated that the people of the Roma community were children of India. The conference ended with a recommendation to the [[Government of India]] to recognize the Roma community spread across 30 countries as a part of the [[Indian diaspora]].<ref name=\"diaspora\">{{cite web|title=Can Romas be part of Indian diaspora?|publisher=khaleejtimes.com|url=http://www.khaleejtimes.com/international/india/can-romas-be-part-of-indian-diaspora|date=29 February 2016|accessdate=4 March 2016}}</ref>\n\n=== World War II ===\n{{See also|Porajmos}}\nDuring the [[Nazi occupation of Czechoslovakia]] in [[World War II]], Romani were exterminated by [[Nazi Germany|Nazi]] mobile killing units and in camps such as [[Lety concentration camp|Lety]], [[Hodonin concentration camp|Hodon\u00edn]] and [[Auschwitz]]. 90% of native Romani were killed during the war; the Romani in modern-day Czech Republic are mostly post-war immigrants from Slovakia or Hungary and their descendants.\n\n=== Communist era ===\n{{main|Romani people in Czechoslovakia}}\nDuring the communist years unsuccessful attempts to change the nomadic living style of Romani were undertaken by the government. Many Romani people were rehoused in ''[[panel\u00e1k]]'' housing estates, which subsequently fell into acute disrepair, such as the [[Ch\u00e1nov housing estate]] near [[Most (Most District)|Most]].<ref>[http://www.sweb.cz/whitewoman/chanov/english.htm Chanov - urban settlement without trees and flowers]</ref> After 1989, some Romani women accused the state of \"forced sterilizations\" arguing that they were not properly informed of what \"sterilization\" meant.<ref>[http://www.psychologia.sk/empatia/11.htm Radim Uzel: Jak to bylo s n\u00e1silnou sterilizac\u00ed u Rom\u016f v \u010ceskoslovensku?]</ref> According to Czech ombudsman [[Otakar Motejl]], \"at least 50 Romani women were unlawfully sterilized\".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://aktualne.centrum.cz/clanek.phtml?id=40065|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110522081313/http://aktualne.centrum.cz/clanek.phtml?id=40065|url-status=dead|archive-date=22 May 2011|title=Otakar Motejl: Nez\u00e1konn\u011b bylo sterilizov\u00e1no nejm\u00e9n\u011b 50 \u017een|trans-title=Otakar Motejl: At Least 50 Women Were Unlawfully Sterilized|language=Czech|date=29 December 2005|accessdate=3 June 2018|website=Aktu\u00e1ln\u011b.cz}}</ref> The Czech representative at the United Nations protested against the accusations, claiming that they were \"false\" and that Romani women \"exaggerate in all cases\".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://aktualne.centrum.cz/domaci/spolecnost/clanek.phtml?id=218615|title=\u010cesko \u0159eklo v OSN, \u017ee Romky p\u0159eh\u00e1n\u011bj\u00ed|trans-title=Czech Republic says in UN that Roma women exaggerate|website=Aktu\u00e1ln\u011b.cz|language=Czech|date=18 August 2006|accessdate=3 June 2018}}</ref> A hospital in Vitkovice, Ostrava, apologised to a Romani woman who was sterilised after her second [[Caesarean section|caesarean]], but a request for a compensation of 1 million Czech crowns was rejected by the court.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://aktualne.centrum.cz/domaci/spolecnost/clanek.phtml?id=333188|title=Soud:Za sterilizaci jen omluva,pen\u00edze ne|trans-title=Court: Apology for sterilization, no money|language=Czech|website=Aktu\u00e1ln\u011b.cz|date=17 January 2007|accessdate=3 June 2018}}</ref>\n\n== Emigration ==\nMany Romani left the country after the independence of the Czech Republic, saying that they felt unsafe due to a surge in right-wing activity. Countries such as Ireland, the UK, Norway and Sweden took in large numbers, but most Romani returned home after a few years. Immigration rates to Great Britain dropped suddenly after financial support for refugees started to be paid out in the form of food tickets in summer 2000 (due to the [[Immigration and Asylum Act 1999]]).<ref>*{{cite web |title=Roma And Emigration |url=http://www.varianty.cz/cdrom/podkapitoly/b02romove.pdf |work=Postoj politik\u016f k emigraci Rom\u016f (The Attitude Of Politicians To The Romani Emigration) |page=219 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070226080107/http://www.varianty.cz/cdrom/podkapitoly/b02romove.pdf |archivedate=2007-02-26 }}</ref> The following year, British customs officers began to check the passengers flying to the UK from Prague airport and routinely rejected those of Romani origin.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/czech/interview/seifter.htm|title=Interview with Pavel Seifter, Czech Ambassador to the UK|website=BBC|language=Czech|date=1 August 2001|accessdate=3 June 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|date=3 November 2004|url=http://www.britske-listy.cz/2004/11/3/art20418.html|archive-url=https://archive.is/20130210042328/http://www.britske-listy.cz/2004/11/3/art20418.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=10 February 2013|language=Czech|title=Pozdn\u00ed d\u016fkaz u britsk\u00fdch soud\u016f: Brit\u0161t\u00ed imigra\u010dn\u00ed \u00fa\u0159edn\u00edci v Ruzyni Romy skute\u010dn\u011b rasisticky diskriminovali|trans-title=Late proof in British courts: British immigration officers really did racially discriminated against Roma at Ruzyn\u011b airport|accessdate=3 June 2018|website=Britsk\u00e9 listy}}</ref> In October 1997, after receiving over 1,000 requests for asylum from Czech Roma within a single year, Canada reinstated a visa regime for Czech citizens.<ref>{{cite news|date=10 October 1997|title=Canada limits Czech visitors|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-srv/inatl/longterm/canada/stories/gypsies101097.htm|first=Howard|last=Schneider|accessdate=3 June 2018|work=The Washington Post}}</ref>\n\n==Anti-ziganism==\n{{see also|Antiziganism#Czech_Republic|l1=Antiziganism in the Czech Republic}}\n[[File:\u010cesk\u00e9 Bud\u011bjovice 29-6-2013 24.JPG|thumb|Violent anti-Roma protests in [[\u010cesk\u00e9 Bud\u011bjovice]] in 2013]]\nThe Romanis are at the centre of the agenda of far-right groups in the Czech Republic, which spread [[Anti-Romanyism|anti-ziganism]]. One highly publicized case was the [[V\u00edtkov arson attack of 2009]], in which four right-wing extremists seriously injured a three-year-old Romani girl. The public responded by donating money as well as presents to the family, who were able to buy a new house from the donations, while the perpetrators were sentenced to 18 and 22 years in prison.\n\nIn January 2010, Amnesty International launched a report titled ''Injustice Renamed: Discrimination in Education of Roma persists in the Czech Republic''.<ref>[https://www.amnesty.org/en/documents/eur71/003/2009/en/ ''Injustice Renamed: Discrimination in Education of Roma persists in the Czech Republic''] Amnesty International report, January 2010</ref> According to the [[BBC]], Amnesty argued that while cosmetic changes had been introduced by the authorities, little genuine improvement in addressing discrimination against Romani children had occurred.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/europe/8456882.stm|title=Amnesty says Czech schools still fail Roma Gypsies|date=13 January 2010|publisher=BBC News|accessdate=14 January 2010| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20100114052029/http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/europe/8456882.stm| archivedate= 14 January 2010 | url-status= live}}</ref>\n\nAccording to a 2010 opinion poll, 68% of Czechs have antipathy towards Romani.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://zpravy.idnes.cz/stem-dve-tretiny-cechu-nemaji-rady-romy-fc1-/domaci.asp?c=A070504_141136_domaci_mr|work=idnes.cz|date=4 May 2007|language=Czech|title=STEM: Dv\u011b t\u0159etiny \u010cech\u016f nemaj\u00ed r\u00e1dy Romy|trans-title=STEM: Two-thirds of Czechs dislike Roma|accessdate=3 June 2018}}</ref> The survey also found that 82% Czechs oppose any form of a \"special care of Roma rights\", 83% of Czechs consider Romani asocial, and 45% of Czechs would support the expulsion of Romani people from the Czech Republic.<ref>{{cite news|first=Jiri|last=St'astny |url=http://zpravy.idnes.cz/cesi-propadaji-anticikanismu-kazdy-druhy-tu-romy-nechce-zjistil-pruzkum-1qx-/domaci.asp?c=A101209_161615_domaci_js |title=\u010ce\u0161i propadaj\u00ed anticik\u00e1nismu, ka\u017ed\u00fd druh\u00fd tu Romy nechce, zjistil pr\u016fzkum|language=Czech|website=idnes.cz |date=9 December 2010 |accessdate=3 June 2018}}</ref>\n\nA 2011 poll, which followed a number of brutal attacks by Romani perpetrators against white victims, reported that 44% of Czechs are afraid of Roma people.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tyden.cz/rubriky/domaci/romsky-bloger-nekteri-romove-se-chovaji-jako-blazni_216270.html|title=Romsky bloger nekteri romove se chovaji jako blazni|language=Czech|accessdate=1 November 2011}}</ref> The majority of Czechs (90%) do not want Romani people as neighbours,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://translate.google.com/translate?u=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.romea.cz%2Findex.php%3Fid%3Dservis%2Fz2005_0318&hl=cs&ie=UTF8&sl=cs&tl=en|title=Czech don't want Roma as neighbours|language=Czech|accessdate=15 April 2007}}</ref> viewing them as thieves and social parasites. Despite a long waiting list for adoptive parents, Romani children from orphanages are almost never adopted by Czech couples.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.radio.cz/en/article/88089 |title=What is keeping children in orphanages when so many people want to adopt?|date=7 February 2007|website=Radio Prague|accessdate=17 May 2012}}</ref> After the [[Velvet Revolution]] in 1989 jobs traditionally employing Romanis either disappeared or were taken over by immigrant workers.{{citation needed|date=June 2013}}\n\nThe 2019 [[Pew Research Center|Pew Research poll]] poll found that 66% of Czechs held unfavorable views of Roma.<ref>{{cite news |title=European Public Opinion Three Decades After the Fall of Communism \u2014 6. Minority groups |url=https://www.pewresearch.org/global/2019/10/14/minority-groups/ |work=Pew Research Center |date=14 October 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Crime==\nCrime statistics from the early 1990s reported that the crime rate among the Romani population in Czechoslovakia was highly disproportionate, especially regarding burglaries. According to \u0158\u00ed\u010dan (1998), about 20\u201330% of the Romani population earn their livelihood in illegal ways, such as procuring prostitution, trafficking and other property crimes.<ref name=\"rican\">{{cite book |last= \u0158\u00ed\u010dan |first= Pavel |title= S Romy \u017e\u00edt budeme \u2013 jde o to jak: d\u011bjiny, sou\u010dasn\u00e1 situace, ko\u0159eny probl\u00e9m\u016f, nad\u011bje spole\u010dn\u00e9 budoucnosti |publisher= Port\u00e1l |location= Praha |year= 1998 |isbn= 978-80-7178-250-6 |pages=58\u201363 |url=https://books.google.com/?id=qtgmAAAAMAAJ&q=pavel+%C5%99%C3%AD%C4%8Dan+s+romy+%C5%BE%C3%ADt+budeme&dq=pavel+%C5%99%C3%AD%C4%8Dan+s+romy+%C5%BE%C3%ADt+budeme}}</ref> Romani make up more than 60% of the Czech prison population and about 50% of repeat offenders, and are thus more than 20 times over-represented in Czech prisons than their population share would suggest.<ref name=\"rican\"/>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Romani people in Czechoslovakia]]\n*[[D.H. and Others v. the Czech Republic]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Roma people in the Czech Republic}}\n* [http://www.czso.cz/sldb2011/eng/redakce.nsf/i/preliminary_results_of_the_2011_population_and_housing_census czso.cz]\n* [http://romove.radio.cz/en/ Roma in the Czech Republic] ([[Czech Radio]])\n* {{cite web |title=Romany communities: ways of living in relation to criminality (in the known of the Czech Republic and Slovakia) |url=http://www.epolis.cz/download/pdf/materials_31_1.pdf |first=Roman|last=Kri\u0161tof}}\n\n{{Ethnic and national minoritites in the Czech Republic}}\n{{Romani diaspora}}\n\n[[Category:Romani in the Czech Republic| ]]\n[[Category:Romani-related controversies]]\n", "name_user": "John of Reading", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eAnti-ziganism:Typo fixing, replaced:Pew Research pollpoll \u2192Pew Research poll", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Romani_people_in_the_Czech_Republic"}
{"title_page": "2020 coronavirus pandemic in Georgia (country)", "text_new": "{{short description|Details of ongoing viral pandemic in Georgia}}\n{{About|cases within the country Georgia|the U.S. state Georgia|2020 coronavirus pandemic in Georgia (U.S. state)}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{EngvarB|date=March 2020}}\n{{Current disaster|event=pandemic|date=March 2020}}\n{{infobox pandemic\n| name = 2020 coronavirus pandemic in Georgia\n| map1            = COVID-19 Outbreak Cases in Georgia per regional unit (municipality).svg\n| legend1         = Map of the COVID-19 outbreak in Georgia as of 21 March 2020 per municipality.<br>(as of 24 March):<br>Red dots represent medical centers currently treating patients<br> {{legend|#e63c0d|Strict quarantine regime}}{{legend|#ff8080|Confirmed cases reported}}\n| map2            = <!--COVID-19 Outbreak Cases in Italy (Density).svg-->\n| legend2         = <!--Number of confirmed cases by province<br>(as of 24 March): {{legend|#FCEED3|1\u20139 confirmed}}{{legend|#F2A88D|10\u201399 confirmed}}{{legend|#E36654|100\u2013499 confirmed}}{{legend|#E5354B|500\u2013999 confirmed}}{{legend|#87353F|1,000\u20139,999 confirmed}}<!--{{legend|#630606|\u226510,000 confirmed}}-->\n| disease = [[Coronavirus disease 2019|COVID-19]]\n| virus_strain = [[Severe acute respiratory syndrome coronavirus 2|SARS-CoV-2]]\n| location = [[Georgia (country)|Georgia]]\n| first_case = [[Tbilisi]]\n| arrival_date = 26 February 2020 ({{age in years, months and days|2020|02|26}})\n| origin = [[Wuhan]], [[Hubei]], [[China]]\n| confirmed_cases = 170\n| suspected_cases = \n| recovery_cases = 36\n| deaths = 1\n}}\n\nThe [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]] was confirmed to have spread to [[Georgia (country)|Georgia]] when its first case was confirmed in [[Tbilisi]] on 26 February 2020.<ref name=\"georgiatoday.1\" />\n\n== Timeline ==\nAll flights from China and [[Wuhan]] to [[Tbilisi International Airport]] were cancelled until 27 January.{{update inline|date=February 2020}} The Health Ministry announced that all arriving passengers from China would be screened. Georgia also temporarily shut down all flights to Iran.<ref>{{Cite News|url=https://imedinews.ge/ge/saqartvelo/126262/tbilisis-aeroportshi-mgzavrebs-koronaviruszeamotsmeben|title=\u10d7\u10d1\u10d8\u10da\u10d8\u10e1\u10d8\u10e1 \u10d0\u10d4\u10e0\u10dd\u10de\u10dd\u10e0\u10e2\u10e8\u10d8 \u10db\u10d2\u10d6\u10d0\u10d5\u10e0\u10d4\u10d1\u10e1 \"\u10d9\u10dd\u10e0\u10dd\u10dc\u10d0\u10d5\u10d8\u10e0\u10e3\u10e1\u10d6\u10d4\" \u10d0\u10db\u10dd\u10ec\u10db\u10d4\u10d1\u10d4\u10dc|date=25 January 2020|accessdate=26 January 2020|5=|website=imedinews.ge|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200126064402/https://imedinews.ge/ge/saqartvelo/126262/tbilisis-aeroportshi-mgzavrebs-koronaviruszeamotsmeben|archive-date=26 January 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 26 February, Georgia confirmed its first COVID-19 case. A 50-year-old man, who returned to Georgia from Iran, was admitted to Infectious Diseases Hospital in [[Tbilisi]]. He came back to the Georgian border via Azerbaijan by taxi.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://imedinews.ge/ge/saqartvelo/129237/saqartveloshi-koronavirusis-pirveli-shemtkhveva-dadasturda |title=\u10e1\u10d0\u10e5\u10d0\u10e0\u10d7\u10d5\u10d4\u10da\u10dd\u10e8\u10d8 \u10d9\u10dd\u10e0\u10dd\u10dc\u10d0\u10d5\u10d8\u10e0\u10e3\u10e1\u10d8\u10e1 \u10de\u10d8\u10e0\u10d5\u10d4\u10da\u10d8 \u10e8\u10d4\u10db\u10d7\u10ee\u10d5\u10d4\u10d5\u10d0 \u10d3\u10d0\u10d3\u10d0\u10e1\u10e2\u10e3\u10e0\u10d3\u10d0 |access-date=26 February 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200228125933/https://imedinews.ge/ge/saqartvelo/129237/saqartveloshi-koronavirusis-pirveli-shemtkhveva-dadasturda |archive-date=28 February 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"georgiatoday.1\">{{Cite web|url=http://georgiatoday.ge/news/19625/First-Case-of-Coronavirus-Reported-in-Georgia- |title=First Case of Coronavirus Reported in Georgia |access-date=26 February 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200226185051/http://georgiatoday.ge/news/19625/First-Case-of-Coronavirus-Reported-in-Georgia- |archive-date=26 February 2020 |url-status=live |website=georgiatoday.ge}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://civil.ge/archives/340246|title=Georgia Confirms First Case of Coronavirus|date=2020-02-26|website=Civil.ge|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-27|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200227050210/https://civil.ge/archives/340246|archive-date=27 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://agenda.ge/en/news/2020/620|title=Georgia reports second case of coronavirus|website=Agenda.ge|access-date=2020-02-28|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200228181135/https://agenda.ge/en/news/2020/620|archive-date=28 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n{{float_box|{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic data/Georgia medical cases chart}}}}\n\nOn 28 February, Georgia confirmed that a 31-year-old Georgian woman who had travelled to Italy tested positive and was admitted to Infectious Diseases Hospital in Tbilisi.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nAn additional 29 are being kept in isolation in a Tbilisi hospital, with Georgia's Center for Disease control chief, Amiran Gamkrelidze stating there was a \u201chigh probability\u201d that some of them have the virus.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thejakartapost.com/news/2020/02/28/belarus-azerbaijan-report-first-coronavirus-cases.html|title=Belarus, Azerbaijan report first coronavirus cases|last=Post|first=The Jakarta|website=The Jakarta Post|language=en|access-date=2020-02-28|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200228161017/https://www.thejakartapost.com/news/2020/02/28/belarus-azerbaijan-report-first-coronavirus-cases.html|archive-date=28 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 5 March, five people have tested positive for the new coronavirus COVID-19 in Georgia increasing the total number of people infected in the country to nine. Head of the Georgian National Centre for Disease Control Amiran Gamkrelidze made the announcement at the recent news briefing following today. He said, all of the five people belong to the same cluster who travelled together to Italy and returned to Georgia on Sunday.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://agenda.ge/en/news/2020/691|title=Georgia confirms five new cases of coronavirus|website=Agenda.ge|accessdate=6 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 12 March, [[President of Georgia|President]] [[Salome Zourabichvili]], in a televised appearance called for calm and unity.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://imedinews.ge/ge/sazogadoeba/131294/salome-zurabishvili-koronavirustan-dakavshirebit-mimartvas-avrtselebs|title=\u10e1\u10d0\u10da\u10dd\u10db\u10d4 \u10d6\u10e3\u10e0\u10d0\u10d1\u10d8\u10e8\u10d5\u10d8\u10da\u10d8 \u10d9\u10dd\u10e0\u10dd\u10dc\u10d0\u10d5\u10d8\u10e0\u10e3\u10e1\u10d7\u10d0\u10dc \u10d3\u10d0\u10d9\u10d0\u10d5\u10e8\u10d8\u10e0\u10d4\u10d1\u10d8\u10d7 \u10db\u10d8\u10db\u10d0\u10e0\u10d7\u10d5\u10d0\u10e1 \u10d0\u10d5\u10e0\u10ea\u10d4\u10da\u10d4\u10d1\u10e1|website=imedinews.ge|accessdate=14 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nAs of 15 March, 33 cases were confirmed, 637 were held under quarantine and 54 were under hospital supervision.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://stopcov.ge/en/|title=Prevention of Coronavirus Spread in Georgia|access-date=15 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 16 March, the spokesperson of the Government of Georgia Irakli Chikovani announced special measures and recommendations. The government of Georgia banned entrance to Georgia for any foreign nationals for the next two weeks.<ref name=\"on.ge16feb\">[https://on.ge/story/52023 \u10e3\u10ea\u10ee\u10dd \u10e5\u10d5\u10d4\u10e7\u10dc\u10d8\u10e1 \u10db\u10dd\u10e5\u10d0\u10da\u10d0\u10e5\u10d4\u10d4\u10d1\u10d8\u10e1\u10d7\u10d5\u10d8\u10e1 \u10e1\u10d0\u10e5\u10d0\u10e0\u10d7\u10d5\u10d4\u10da\u10dd\u10e8\u10d8 \u10e8\u10d4\u10db\u10dd\u10e1\u10d5\u10da\u10d0 2 \u10d9\u10d5\u10d8\u10e0\u10d8\u10e1 \u10d2\u10d0\u10dc\u10db\u10d0\u10d5\u10da\u10dd\u10d1\u10d0\u10e8\u10d8 \u10d8\u10d9\u10e0\u10eb\u10d0\u10da\u10d4\u10d1\u10d0], on.ge</ref> The Coordination Council recommended all elderly citizens of Georgia to avoid mass gatherings and isolate themselves.<ref>[https://www.interpressnews.ge/ka/article/590140 \u10e1\u10d0\u10d9\u10dd\u10dd\u10e0\u10d3\u10d8\u10dc\u10d0\u10ea\u10d8\u10dd \u10e1\u10d0\u10d1\u10ed\u10dd 70 \u10ec\u10d4\u10da\u10e1 \u10d6\u10d4\u10db\u10dd\u10d7 \u10db\u10dd\u10e5\u10d0\u10da\u10d0\u10e5\u10d4\u10d4\u10d1\u10e1 \u10e0\u10d4\u10d9\u10dd\u10db\u10d4\u10dc\u10d3\u10d0\u10ea\u10d8\u10d0\u10e1 \u10d0\u10eb\u10da\u10d4\u10d5\u10e1, \u10db\u10dd\u10d4\u10e0\u10d8\u10d3\u10dd\u10dc \u10e1\u10d0\u10d6\u10dd\u10d2\u10d0\u10d3\u10dd\u10d4\u10d1\u10e0\u10d8\u10d5\u10d8 \u10d7\u10d0\u10d5\u10e8\u10d4\u10e7\u10e0\u10d8\u10e1 \u10d0\u10d3\u10d2\u10d8\u10da\u10d4\u10d1\u10e1 \u10d3\u10d0 \u201e\u10db\u10d0\u10e5\u10e1\u10d8\u10db\u10d0\u10da\u10e3\u10e0\u10d0\u10d3 \u10e8\u10d4\u10d4\u10ea\u10d0\u10d3\u10dd\u10dc \u10e1\u10d0\u10d9\u10e3\u10d7\u10d0\u10e0\u10d8 \u10d7\u10d0\u10d5\u10d8\u10e1 \u10d8\u10d6\u10dd\u10da\u10d0\u10ea\u10d8\u10d0\u10e1\u201c], ipn.ge</ref> The Government also recommends cafes, restaurants and bars to offer customers the take-away service.<ref>[https://www.interpressnews.ge/ka/article/590139-mtavroba-restornebsa-da-kape-barebs-rekomendaciit-mimartavs-mokalakeebs-ec-gatanis-servisi-shestavazon \u10db\u10d7\u10d0\u10d5\u10e0\u10dd\u10d1\u10d0 \u10e0\u10d4\u10e1\u10e2\u10dd\u10e0\u10dc\u10d4\u10d1\u10e1\u10d0 \u10d3\u10d0 \u10d9\u10d0\u10e4\u10d4-\u10d1\u10d0\u10e0\u10d4\u10d1\u10e1 \u10e0\u10d4\u10d9\u10dd\u10db\u10d4\u10dc\u10d3\u10d0\u10ea\u10d8\u10d8\u10d7 \u10db\u10d8\u10db\u10d0\u10e0\u10d7\u10d0\u10d5\u10e1, \u10db\u10dd\u10e5\u10d0\u10da\u10d0\u10e5\u10d4\u10d4\u10d1\u10e1 \u10d4.\u10ec. \u10d2\u10d0\u10e2\u10d0\u10dc\u10d8\u10e1 \u10e1\u10d4\u10e0\u10d5\u10d8\u10e1\u10d8 \u10e8\u10d4\u10e1\u10d7\u10d0\u10d5\u10d0\u10d6\u10dd\u10dc], ipn.ge</ref>  33 cases of coronavirus were confirmed in Georgia, 637 persons remain in quarantine and 54 persons are under direct medical supervision in hospitals for the 16th of March.<ref>[https://netgazeti.ge/news/434107/ \u10e1\u10d0\u10e5\u10d0\u10e0\u10d7\u10d5\u10d4\u10da\u10dd 2 \u10d9\u10d5\u10d8\u10e0\u10d8\u10d7 \u10e1\u10d0\u10d6\u10e6\u10d5\u10d0\u10e0\u10e1 \u10d9\u10d4\u10e2\u10d0\u10d5\u10e1 \u2013 \u10db\u10d7\u10d0\u10d5\u10e0\u10dd\u10d1\u10d8\u10e1 \u10d2\u10d0\u10d3\u10d0\u10ec\u10e7\u10d5\u10d4\u10e2\u10d8\u10da\u10d4\u10d1\u10d0], netgazeti.ge</ref> The government disseminated a special sms to all phones in Georgia informing population about measures and recommendations.<ref>[https://netgazeti.ge/news/434103/ \u10db\u10d7\u10d0\u10d5\u10e0\u10dd\u10d1\u10d0: \u10d0\u10e3\u10ea\u10d8\u10da\u10d4\u10d1\u10d4\u10da\u10d8 \u10e1\u10d0\u10ed\u10d8\u10e0\u10dd\u10d4\u10d1\u10d8\u10e1 \u10d2\u10d0\u10e0\u10d4\u10e8\u10d4 \u10e1\u10d0\u10ee\u10da\u10d8\u10d3\u10d0\u10dc \u10d0\u10e0 \u10d2\u10d0\u10ee\u10d5\u10d8\u10d3\u10d4\u10d7], netgazeti.ge</ref>\n\n=== Timeline ===\n\n==== Prelude ====\n\n* [[22 January]]: Amiran Gamkrelidze, head of the Georgian National Center for Disease Control, warns Georgian travellers from visiting Wuhan, the point of origin of the COVID-19 outbreak. He claims that there is a \"small, but theoretical\" chance that the virus could reach Georgia.<ref>[https://agenda.ge/en/news/2020/206 Health official: China-born virus has \u2018low but theoretical\u2019 chance of reaching Georgia], Agenda.ge</ref>\n* [[26 January]]: Georgian doctors start examining passengers arriving from China at airports for coronavirus-related symptoms.<ref>[https://agenda.ge/en/news/2020/245 Passengers inbound from China examined at Tbilisi airport], Agenda.ge</ref>\n* [[27 January]]: \n** Georgian news outlet ''Alia'' claims that some medics refuse to check airport arrivals out of a lack of proper safety guarantees. The Ministry of Health denies these allegations.<ref>[https://www.alia.ge/%e1%83%a1%e1%83%90%e1%83%a1%e1%83%ac%e1%83%a0%e1%83%90%e1%83%a4%e1%83%9d%e1%83%a1-%e1%83%94%e1%83%a5%e1%83%98%e1%83%9b%e1%83%98%e1%83%a1-%e1%83%a1%e1%83%99%e1%83%90%e1%83%9c%e1%83%93%e1%83%90%e1%83%9a/?fbclid=IwAR2butPwJoowCoxhyuuvU7Z40rar7O2fizzgNF8YGKBIjF3bhJV60IpuLqM \u10e1\u10d0\u10e1\u10ec\u10e0\u10d0\u10e4\u10dd\u10d3! \u2013 \u10e0\u10d0\u10e2\u10dd\u10db \u10d0\u10db\u10d1\u10dd\u10d1\u10d4\u10dc \u10d4\u10e5\u10d8\u10db\u10d4\u10d1\u10d8 \u10e3\u10d0\u10e0\u10e1 \u10d0\u10d4\u10e0\u10dd\u10de\u10dd\u10e0\u10e2\u10e8\u10d8 \u10d2\u10d0\u10e1\u10d5\u10da\u10d0\u10d6\u10d4?], Alia.ge</ref>\n** The National Center for Disease Control starts monitoring Chinese workers operating on the construction of a highway in Georgia.\n* [[28 January]]: \n** Georgia announces it will be evacuating its citizens from the Hubei Province of China.\n** Georgia bans the import of live animals, including turtles and ornamental fish, from China. Tbilisi claims the ban will remain in effect until the WHO declares China free from the coronavirus.\n* [[29 January]]: \n** Georgia suspends direct flights with China for two months.\n** Two Chinese sailors stationed in Batumi and showing signs of high fever start being monitored by the NCDC.\n* [[30 January]]: [[Prime Minister of Georgia|Prime Minister]] [[Giorgi Gakharia]] alleges that the country's healthcare system is ready to respond to the new coronavirus if it enters Georgia.\n* [[31 January]]: Two Chinese and two Georgian citizens, one of whom recently returned from Wuhan, are monitored by the NCDC after showing high temperatures. Their blood samples are sent to Germany after their test results come back negative for all the viruses that Georgia is capable at the moment of testing for.\n* [[1 February]]: The Georgian Foreign Ministry \"stands with\" China as the outbreak continues to expand and thanks Turkey for offering to evacuate Georgian citizens from Wuhan.\n* [[2 February]]: Turkey and France evacuate 5 Georgian citizens from the Hubei Province of China, initial center of the coronavirus outbreak.\n* [[4 February]]: The Lugar Center of the NCDC starts testing for the coronavirus after receiving reagents from Germany. It previously had to send test samples to Germany or the Netherlands for confirmation.\n* [[10 February]]: United Airports of Georgia reports a 3% year-on-year decrease in airport traffic in January. Media cites the suspension of flights with China as a potential cause.\n* [[20 February]]: A South Korean citizen with high fever tests negative for the coronavirus in Georgia.\n* [[22 February]]: 34 Georgian citizens recently evacuated from China test negative for the coronavirus while in quarantine in Imereti.\n* [[23 February]]: Georgia calls the outbreak of the coronavirus in neighboring Iran a \"serious concern\" and suspends direct flights with the Islamic Republic.\n* [[24 February]]: \n** Georgia warns its citizens visiting Italy, in particular northern parts of the country, to avoid public places and regularly wash their hands as Italy becomes the newest center of the epidemy. \n** The NCDC assesses that the country remains a \"low-risk\" zone for the spread of the virus.\n* [[25 February]]: Three Georgians and two Iranians are tested for the coronavirus in Tbilisi. Their results come back negative.\n\n==== First cases ====\n{{Unreferenced section|date=March 2020}}\n\n* [[26 February]]: \n** A Georgian citizen returning from Iran is diagnosed with the coronavirus at the Georgia-Azerbaijan border, representing the first COVID-19 case. [[President of Georgia|President]] [[Salome Zourabichvili]] and the Health Ministry state there is no need for panic.\n** Prime Minister Giorgi Gakharia sets up an Inter-Agency Council for Coordination Against the Coronavirus (IACC), made of representatives of every major government agency, to manage the situation. The IACC's first decision is to ban flights to Iran.\n** The Economy Ministry predicts a loss of 30 million lari per month in the tourism industry due to the coronavirus.\n* [[27 February]]: \n** The IACC instructs every Ministry to draft an action plan against the coronavirus.\n** Turkish citizens who visited coronavirus-infected countries are banned from crossing the Georgian-Turkish border.\n** 15 individuals with lung disease are taken to the town of Abastumani to be tested.\n** South Ossetian ''de facto'' authorities close down the Kartsmani crossing point in Imereti to prevent Georgians from entering the breakaway republic out of fear for the outbreak.\n** Airline Wizz Air reduces its flight frequency to Italian destinations, including a full cancellation of flights to Milan.\n* [[28 February]]: \n** A second case of COVID-19 is detected in a woman who recently travelled to Italy. \n** Russia sends out mobile sanitary brigades to help separatist Abkhazia deal with the virus, as Sokhumi refuses to collaborate with Tbilisi on the outbreak.\n* [[29 February]]: \n** A third case is diagnosed in a patient who had come in close contact with the first patient and had recently travelled to Iran.\n** The government closes schools down until March 16.\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{COVID-19}}\n\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in Georgia (country)| ]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Details of ongoing viral pandemic in Georgia}}\n{{About|cases within the country Georgia|the U.S. state Georgia|2020 coronavirus pandemic in Georgia (U.S. state)}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{EngvarB|date=March 2020}}\n{{Current disaster|event=pandemic|date=March 2020}}\n{{infobox pandemic\n| name = 2020 coronavirus pandemic in Georgia\n| map1            = COVID-19 Outbreak Cases in Georgia per regional unit (municipality).svg\n| legend1         = Map of the COVID-19 outbreak in Georgia as of 21 March 2020 per municipality.<br>(as of 24 March):<br>Red dots represent medical centers currently treating patients<br> {{legend|#e63c0d|Strict quarantine regime}}{{legend|#ff8080|Confirmed cases reported}}\n| map2            = <!--COVID-19 Outbreak Cases in Italy (Density).svg-->\n| legend2         = <!--Number of confirmed cases by province<br>(as of 24 March): {{legend|#FCEED3|1\u20139 confirmed}}{{legend|#F2A88D|10\u201399 confirmed}}{{legend|#E36654|100\u2013499 confirmed}}{{legend|#E5354B|500\u2013999 confirmed}}{{legend|#87353F|1,000\u20139,999 confirmed}}<!--{{legend|#630606|\u226510,000 confirmed}}-->\n| disease = [[Coronavirus disease 2019|COVID-19]]\n| virus_strain = [[Severe acute respiratory syndrome coronavirus 2|SARS-CoV-2]]\n| location = [[Georgia (country)|Georgia]]\n| first_case = [[Tbilisi]]\n| arrival_date = 26 February 2020 ({{age in years, months and days|2020|02|26}})\n| origin = [[Wuhan]], [[Hubei]], [[China]]\n| confirmed_cases = 162\n| suspected_cases = \n| recovery_cases = 36\n| deaths = 1\n}}\n\nThe [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]] was confirmed to have spread to [[Georgia (country)|Georgia]] when its first case was confirmed in [[Tbilisi]] on 26 February 2020.<ref name=\"georgiatoday.1\" />\n\n== Timeline ==\nAll flights from China and [[Wuhan]] to [[Tbilisi International Airport]] were cancelled until 27 January.{{update inline|date=February 2020}} The Health Ministry announced that all arriving passengers from China would be screened. Georgia also temporarily shut down all flights to Iran.<ref>{{Cite News|url=https://imedinews.ge/ge/saqartvelo/126262/tbilisis-aeroportshi-mgzavrebs-koronaviruszeamotsmeben|title=\u10d7\u10d1\u10d8\u10da\u10d8\u10e1\u10d8\u10e1 \u10d0\u10d4\u10e0\u10dd\u10de\u10dd\u10e0\u10e2\u10e8\u10d8 \u10db\u10d2\u10d6\u10d0\u10d5\u10e0\u10d4\u10d1\u10e1 \"\u10d9\u10dd\u10e0\u10dd\u10dc\u10d0\u10d5\u10d8\u10e0\u10e3\u10e1\u10d6\u10d4\" \u10d0\u10db\u10dd\u10ec\u10db\u10d4\u10d1\u10d4\u10dc|date=25 January 2020|accessdate=26 January 2020|5=|website=imedinews.ge|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200126064402/https://imedinews.ge/ge/saqartvelo/126262/tbilisis-aeroportshi-mgzavrebs-koronaviruszeamotsmeben|archive-date=26 January 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 26 February, Georgia confirmed its first COVID-19 case. A 50-year-old man, who returned to Georgia from Iran, was admitted to Infectious Diseases Hospital in [[Tbilisi]]. He came back to the Georgian border via Azerbaijan by taxi.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://imedinews.ge/ge/saqartvelo/129237/saqartveloshi-koronavirusis-pirveli-shemtkhveva-dadasturda |title=\u10e1\u10d0\u10e5\u10d0\u10e0\u10d7\u10d5\u10d4\u10da\u10dd\u10e8\u10d8 \u10d9\u10dd\u10e0\u10dd\u10dc\u10d0\u10d5\u10d8\u10e0\u10e3\u10e1\u10d8\u10e1 \u10de\u10d8\u10e0\u10d5\u10d4\u10da\u10d8 \u10e8\u10d4\u10db\u10d7\u10ee\u10d5\u10d4\u10d5\u10d0 \u10d3\u10d0\u10d3\u10d0\u10e1\u10e2\u10e3\u10e0\u10d3\u10d0 |access-date=26 February 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200228125933/https://imedinews.ge/ge/saqartvelo/129237/saqartveloshi-koronavirusis-pirveli-shemtkhveva-dadasturda |archive-date=28 February 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"georgiatoday.1\">{{Cite web|url=http://georgiatoday.ge/news/19625/First-Case-of-Coronavirus-Reported-in-Georgia- |title=First Case of Coronavirus Reported in Georgia |access-date=26 February 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200226185051/http://georgiatoday.ge/news/19625/First-Case-of-Coronavirus-Reported-in-Georgia- |archive-date=26 February 2020 |url-status=live |website=georgiatoday.ge}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://civil.ge/archives/340246|title=Georgia Confirms First Case of Coronavirus|date=2020-02-26|website=Civil.ge|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-27|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200227050210/https://civil.ge/archives/340246|archive-date=27 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://agenda.ge/en/news/2020/620|title=Georgia reports second case of coronavirus|website=Agenda.ge|access-date=2020-02-28|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200228181135/https://agenda.ge/en/news/2020/620|archive-date=28 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n{{float_box|{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic data/Georgia medical cases chart}}}}\n\nOn 28 February, Georgia confirmed that a 31-year-old Georgian woman who had travelled to Italy tested positive and was admitted to Infectious Diseases Hospital in Tbilisi.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nAn additional 29 are being kept in isolation in a Tbilisi hospital, with Georgia's Center for Disease control chief, Amiran Gamkrelidze stating there was a \u201chigh probability\u201d that some of them have the virus.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thejakartapost.com/news/2020/02/28/belarus-azerbaijan-report-first-coronavirus-cases.html|title=Belarus, Azerbaijan report first coronavirus cases|last=Post|first=The Jakarta|website=The Jakarta Post|language=en|access-date=2020-02-28|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200228161017/https://www.thejakartapost.com/news/2020/02/28/belarus-azerbaijan-report-first-coronavirus-cases.html|archive-date=28 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 5 March, five people have tested positive for the new coronavirus COVID-19 in Georgia increasing the total number of people infected in the country to nine. Head of the Georgian National Centre for Disease Control Amiran Gamkrelidze made the announcement at the recent news briefing following today. He said, all of the five people belong to the same cluster who travelled together to Italy and returned to Georgia on Sunday.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://agenda.ge/en/news/2020/691|title=Georgia confirms five new cases of coronavirus|website=Agenda.ge|accessdate=6 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 12 March, [[President of Georgia|President]] [[Salome Zourabichvili]], in a televised appearance called for calm and unity.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://imedinews.ge/ge/sazogadoeba/131294/salome-zurabishvili-koronavirustan-dakavshirebit-mimartvas-avrtselebs|title=\u10e1\u10d0\u10da\u10dd\u10db\u10d4 \u10d6\u10e3\u10e0\u10d0\u10d1\u10d8\u10e8\u10d5\u10d8\u10da\u10d8 \u10d9\u10dd\u10e0\u10dd\u10dc\u10d0\u10d5\u10d8\u10e0\u10e3\u10e1\u10d7\u10d0\u10dc \u10d3\u10d0\u10d9\u10d0\u10d5\u10e8\u10d8\u10e0\u10d4\u10d1\u10d8\u10d7 \u10db\u10d8\u10db\u10d0\u10e0\u10d7\u10d5\u10d0\u10e1 \u10d0\u10d5\u10e0\u10ea\u10d4\u10da\u10d4\u10d1\u10e1|website=imedinews.ge|accessdate=14 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nAs of 15 March, 33 cases were confirmed, 637 were held under quarantine and 54 were under hospital supervision.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://stopcov.ge/en/|title=Prevention of Coronavirus Spread in Georgia|access-date=15 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 16 March, the spokesperson of the Government of Georgia Irakli Chikovani announced special measures and recommendations. The government of Georgia banned entrance to Georgia for any foreign nationals for the next two weeks.<ref name=\"on.ge16feb\">[https://on.ge/story/52023 \u10e3\u10ea\u10ee\u10dd \u10e5\u10d5\u10d4\u10e7\u10dc\u10d8\u10e1 \u10db\u10dd\u10e5\u10d0\u10da\u10d0\u10e5\u10d4\u10d4\u10d1\u10d8\u10e1\u10d7\u10d5\u10d8\u10e1 \u10e1\u10d0\u10e5\u10d0\u10e0\u10d7\u10d5\u10d4\u10da\u10dd\u10e8\u10d8 \u10e8\u10d4\u10db\u10dd\u10e1\u10d5\u10da\u10d0 2 \u10d9\u10d5\u10d8\u10e0\u10d8\u10e1 \u10d2\u10d0\u10dc\u10db\u10d0\u10d5\u10da\u10dd\u10d1\u10d0\u10e8\u10d8 \u10d8\u10d9\u10e0\u10eb\u10d0\u10da\u10d4\u10d1\u10d0], on.ge</ref> The Coordination Council recommended all elderly citizens of Georgia to avoid mass gatherings and isolate themselves.<ref>[https://www.interpressnews.ge/ka/article/590140 \u10e1\u10d0\u10d9\u10dd\u10dd\u10e0\u10d3\u10d8\u10dc\u10d0\u10ea\u10d8\u10dd \u10e1\u10d0\u10d1\u10ed\u10dd 70 \u10ec\u10d4\u10da\u10e1 \u10d6\u10d4\u10db\u10dd\u10d7 \u10db\u10dd\u10e5\u10d0\u10da\u10d0\u10e5\u10d4\u10d4\u10d1\u10e1 \u10e0\u10d4\u10d9\u10dd\u10db\u10d4\u10dc\u10d3\u10d0\u10ea\u10d8\u10d0\u10e1 \u10d0\u10eb\u10da\u10d4\u10d5\u10e1, \u10db\u10dd\u10d4\u10e0\u10d8\u10d3\u10dd\u10dc \u10e1\u10d0\u10d6\u10dd\u10d2\u10d0\u10d3\u10dd\u10d4\u10d1\u10e0\u10d8\u10d5\u10d8 \u10d7\u10d0\u10d5\u10e8\u10d4\u10e7\u10e0\u10d8\u10e1 \u10d0\u10d3\u10d2\u10d8\u10da\u10d4\u10d1\u10e1 \u10d3\u10d0 \u201e\u10db\u10d0\u10e5\u10e1\u10d8\u10db\u10d0\u10da\u10e3\u10e0\u10d0\u10d3 \u10e8\u10d4\u10d4\u10ea\u10d0\u10d3\u10dd\u10dc \u10e1\u10d0\u10d9\u10e3\u10d7\u10d0\u10e0\u10d8 \u10d7\u10d0\u10d5\u10d8\u10e1 \u10d8\u10d6\u10dd\u10da\u10d0\u10ea\u10d8\u10d0\u10e1\u201c], ipn.ge</ref> The Government also recommends cafes, restaurants and bars to offer customers the take-away service.<ref>[https://www.interpressnews.ge/ka/article/590139-mtavroba-restornebsa-da-kape-barebs-rekomendaciit-mimartavs-mokalakeebs-ec-gatanis-servisi-shestavazon \u10db\u10d7\u10d0\u10d5\u10e0\u10dd\u10d1\u10d0 \u10e0\u10d4\u10e1\u10e2\u10dd\u10e0\u10dc\u10d4\u10d1\u10e1\u10d0 \u10d3\u10d0 \u10d9\u10d0\u10e4\u10d4-\u10d1\u10d0\u10e0\u10d4\u10d1\u10e1 \u10e0\u10d4\u10d9\u10dd\u10db\u10d4\u10dc\u10d3\u10d0\u10ea\u10d8\u10d8\u10d7 \u10db\u10d8\u10db\u10d0\u10e0\u10d7\u10d0\u10d5\u10e1, \u10db\u10dd\u10e5\u10d0\u10da\u10d0\u10e5\u10d4\u10d4\u10d1\u10e1 \u10d4.\u10ec. \u10d2\u10d0\u10e2\u10d0\u10dc\u10d8\u10e1 \u10e1\u10d4\u10e0\u10d5\u10d8\u10e1\u10d8 \u10e8\u10d4\u10e1\u10d7\u10d0\u10d5\u10d0\u10d6\u10dd\u10dc], ipn.ge</ref>  33 cases of coronavirus were confirmed in Georgia, 637 persons remain in quarantine and 54 persons are under direct medical supervision in hospitals for the 16th of March.<ref>[https://netgazeti.ge/news/434107/ \u10e1\u10d0\u10e5\u10d0\u10e0\u10d7\u10d5\u10d4\u10da\u10dd 2 \u10d9\u10d5\u10d8\u10e0\u10d8\u10d7 \u10e1\u10d0\u10d6\u10e6\u10d5\u10d0\u10e0\u10e1 \u10d9\u10d4\u10e2\u10d0\u10d5\u10e1 \u2013 \u10db\u10d7\u10d0\u10d5\u10e0\u10dd\u10d1\u10d8\u10e1 \u10d2\u10d0\u10d3\u10d0\u10ec\u10e7\u10d5\u10d4\u10e2\u10d8\u10da\u10d4\u10d1\u10d0], netgazeti.ge</ref> The government disseminated a special sms to all phones in Georgia informing population about measures and recommendations.<ref>[https://netgazeti.ge/news/434103/ \u10db\u10d7\u10d0\u10d5\u10e0\u10dd\u10d1\u10d0: \u10d0\u10e3\u10ea\u10d8\u10da\u10d4\u10d1\u10d4\u10da\u10d8 \u10e1\u10d0\u10ed\u10d8\u10e0\u10dd\u10d4\u10d1\u10d8\u10e1 \u10d2\u10d0\u10e0\u10d4\u10e8\u10d4 \u10e1\u10d0\u10ee\u10da\u10d8\u10d3\u10d0\u10dc \u10d0\u10e0 \u10d2\u10d0\u10ee\u10d5\u10d8\u10d3\u10d4\u10d7], netgazeti.ge</ref>\n\n=== Timeline ===\n\n==== Prelude ====\n\n* [[22 January]]: Amiran Gamkrelidze, head of the Georgian National Center for Disease Control, warns Georgian travellers from visiting Wuhan, the point of origin of the COVID-19 outbreak. He claims that there is a \"small, but theoretical\" chance that the virus could reach Georgia.<ref>[https://agenda.ge/en/news/2020/206 Health official: China-born virus has \u2018low but theoretical\u2019 chance of reaching Georgia], Agenda.ge</ref>\n* [[26 January]]: Georgian doctors start examining passengers arriving from China at airports for coronavirus-related symptoms.<ref>[https://agenda.ge/en/news/2020/245 Passengers inbound from China examined at Tbilisi airport], Agenda.ge</ref>\n* [[27 January]]: \n** Georgian news outlet ''Alia'' claims that some medics refuse to check airport arrivals out of a lack of proper safety guarantees. The Ministry of Health denies these allegations.<ref>[https://www.alia.ge/%e1%83%a1%e1%83%90%e1%83%a1%e1%83%ac%e1%83%a0%e1%83%90%e1%83%a4%e1%83%9d%e1%83%a1-%e1%83%94%e1%83%a5%e1%83%98%e1%83%9b%e1%83%98%e1%83%a1-%e1%83%a1%e1%83%99%e1%83%90%e1%83%9c%e1%83%93%e1%83%90%e1%83%9a/?fbclid=IwAR2butPwJoowCoxhyuuvU7Z40rar7O2fizzgNF8YGKBIjF3bhJV60IpuLqM \u10e1\u10d0\u10e1\u10ec\u10e0\u10d0\u10e4\u10dd\u10d3! \u2013 \u10e0\u10d0\u10e2\u10dd\u10db \u10d0\u10db\u10d1\u10dd\u10d1\u10d4\u10dc \u10d4\u10e5\u10d8\u10db\u10d4\u10d1\u10d8 \u10e3\u10d0\u10e0\u10e1 \u10d0\u10d4\u10e0\u10dd\u10de\u10dd\u10e0\u10e2\u10e8\u10d8 \u10d2\u10d0\u10e1\u10d5\u10da\u10d0\u10d6\u10d4?], Alia.ge</ref>\n** The National Center for Disease Control starts monitoring Chinese workers operating on the construction of a highway in Georgia.\n* [[28 January]]: \n** Georgia announces it will be evacuating its citizens from the Hubei Province of China.\n** Georgia bans the import of live animals, including turtles and ornamental fish, from China. Tbilisi claims the ban will remain in effect until the WHO declares China free from the coronavirus.\n* [[29 January]]: \n** Georgia suspends direct flights with China for two months.\n** Two Chinese sailors stationed in Batumi and showing signs of high fever start being monitored by the NCDC.\n* [[30 January]]: [[Prime Minister of Georgia|Prime Minister]] [[Giorgi Gakharia]] alleges that the country's healthcare system is ready to respond to the new coronavirus if it enters Georgia.\n* [[31 January]]: Two Chinese and two Georgian citizens, one of whom recently returned from Wuhan, are monitored by the NCDC after showing high temperatures. Their blood samples are sent to Germany after their test results come back negative for all the viruses that Georgia is capable at the moment of testing for.\n* [[1 February]]: The Georgian Foreign Ministry \"stands with\" China as the outbreak continues to expand and thanks Turkey for offering to evacuate Georgian citizens from Wuhan.\n* [[2 February]]: Turkey and France evacuate 5 Georgian citizens from the Hubei Province of China, initial center of the coronavirus outbreak.\n* [[4 February]]: The Lugar Center of the NCDC starts testing for the coronavirus after receiving reagents from Germany. It previously had to send test samples to Germany or the Netherlands for confirmation.\n* [[10 February]]: United Airports of Georgia reports a 3% year-on-year decrease in airport traffic in January. Media cites the suspension of flights with China as a potential cause.\n* [[20 February]]: A South Korean citizen with high fever tests negative for the coronavirus in Georgia.\n* [[22 February]]: 34 Georgian citizens recently evacuated from China test negative for the coronavirus while in quarantine in Imereti.\n* [[23 February]]: Georgia calls the outbreak of the coronavirus in neighboring Iran a \"serious concern\" and suspends direct flights with the Islamic Republic.\n* [[24 February]]: \n** Georgia warns its citizens visiting Italy, in particular northern parts of the country, to avoid public places and regularly wash their hands as Italy becomes the newest center of the epidemy. \n** The NCDC assesses that the country remains a \"low-risk\" zone for the spread of the virus.\n* [[25 February]]: Three Georgians and two Iranians are tested for the coronavirus in Tbilisi. Their results come back negative.\n\n==== First cases ====\n{{Unreferenced section|date=March 2020}}\n\n* [[26 February]]: \n** A Georgian citizen returning from Iran is diagnosed with the coronavirus at the Georgia-Azerbaijan border, representing the first COVID-19 case. [[President of Georgia|President]] [[Salome Zourabichvili]] and the Health Ministry state there is no need for panic.\n** Prime Minister Giorgi Gakharia sets up an Inter-Agency Council for Coordination Against the Coronavirus (IACC), made of representatives of every major government agency, to manage the situation. The IACC's first decision is to ban flights to Iran.\n** The Economy Ministry predicts a loss of 30 million lari per month in the tourism industry due to the coronavirus.\n* [[27 February]]: \n** The IACC instructs every Ministry to draft an action plan against the coronavirus.\n** Turkish citizens who visited coronavirus-infected countries are banned from crossing the Georgian-Turkish border.\n** 15 individuals with lung disease are taken to the town of Abastumani to be tested.\n** South Ossetian ''de facto'' authorities close down the Kartsmani crossing point in Imereti to prevent Georgians from entering the breakaway republic out of fear for the outbreak.\n** Airline Wizz Air reduces its flight frequency to Italian destinations, including a full cancellation of flights to Milan.\n* [[28 February]]: \n** A second case of COVID-19 is detected in a woman who recently travelled to Italy. \n** Russia sends out mobile sanitary brigades to help separatist Abkhazia deal with the virus, as Sokhumi refuses to collaborate with Tbilisi on the outbreak.\n* [[29 February]]: \n** A third case is diagnosed in a patient who had come in close contact with the first patient and had recently travelled to Iran.\n** The government closes schools down until March 16.\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{COVID-19}}\n\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in Georgia (country)| ]]\n", "name_user": "Fotoni", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2020_coronavirus_pandemic_in_Georgia_(country)"}
{"title_page": "Dinesh Lal Yadav", "text_new": "\n\n{{Use British English|date = February 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Dinesh lal yadav\n| image              = Dinesh Lal Yadav at Press Conference of Celebrity Cricket League 2016 (cropped).jpg\n| imagesize          = \n| alt                = \n| caption            = Dinesh Lal Yadav\n| birth_name         = Dinesh\n| birth_date         = {{birth date and age|df=y|1979|02|02}}\n| birth_place        = [[Ghazipur]], Uttar Pradesh, India|\n| occupation         = social, worker\n| years_active       = 2006\u2013present\n| party              = [[Bharatiya Janata Party]] {{small|(2019\u2013present)}}\n| other names        = Nirahua, Jubilee Star\n}}\n'''Dinesh Lal Yadav Nirahua'' (born 2 February 1979) also known as '''Nirahua''', is an Indian actor, [[Bhojpuri cinema|Bhojpuri]] film actor, singer, film producer,<ref>https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/topic/Nirahua-Entertainment-Pvt-Ltd.</ref><ref>https://www.moviebuff.com/nirahua-entertainment</ref> television presenter, and politician.<ref>{{cite news|title=My audience are the reason for my success \u2013 Dinesh Lal Yadav|url=http://entertainment.oneindia.in/bollywood/features/2008/dinesh-lal-yadav-interview-130208.html|date=13 February 2008}}</ref> He is among the most successful Bhojpuri actors, with successive five box office successes released in 2015.<ref>{{cite news|title=Dinesh Lal Yadav's new record |url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/bhojpuri/movies/news/Dinesh-Lal-Yadavs-new-record/articleshow/49890847.cms |date=23 November 2015 |newspaper=[[The Times of India]]}}</ref> Dinesh Lal Yadav was a contestant on ''[[Bigg Boss 6]]'' in 2012.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rediff.com/movies/slide-show/slide-show-1-nobody-is-big-or-small-in-bigg-boss-tv/20121015.htm|title=Nobody is big or small in Bigg Boss. Everybody is equal}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://indiatoday.intoday.in/story/nirahua-evicted-from-bigg-boss-6/1/237436.html|title=Hope Bigg Boss benefits me: Nirahua}}</ref>\n\nHe hails from famous Birha family of Ghazipur but spent most of his childhood days in '' Belghoria'' area of [[Kolkata]] where his father used to work in a factory. He completed his education in the same suburbs of [[Kolkata]]. Famous Birha singer Vijay Lal Yadav known as \"Birha Samrat\" and lyrics writer Pyare Lal Yadav (Kaviji) who has penned most of '' Nirahua's'' songs both films and albums, are his first cousins.\n\n==Career==\nHe started his career with the Bhojpuri movie ''Chalat Musafir Moh Liyo Re'' as a supporting actor with [[Kalpana Patowary]] and Sunil Chhaila Bihari.\n\nFirst time in 2008, he appeared in ''Nirahua Rikshawala'' as a lead actor. ''Nirahua Rikshwala'' was a blockbuster in [[Bhojpuri]] box office. After which Nirahua never looked back. He has given many successful films in his career such as ''[[Nirahua Hindustani]], [[Patna Se Pakistan]], [[Nirahua Hindustani 2]], [[Bam Bam Bol Raha Hai Kashi]]''. He is also known as \"Jubilee Star\". His last released [[Nirahua Hindustani 3]] was also a huge hit in Bhojpuri Box Office.\n\nIn 2012, he acted alongside [[Amitabh Bachhan]] in the Bhojpuri film Ganga Devi.\n\nIn 2016, he received Uttar Pradesh's highest civilian award \"Yash Bharti Samman Award\" by the Uttar Pradesh Government for this contribution in Bhojpuri films.\n\n==Political career==\nNirahua joined BJP in [[Lucknow]] on 27 March 2019 in presence of Uttar Pradesh chief minister [[Yogi Adityanath]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.ndtv.com/india-news/bhojpuri-actor-dinesh-lal-yadav-nirhua-joins-bjp-2013612?&tb_cb=1|title=Bhojpuri Actor Dinesh Lal Yadav Joins BJP|date=27 March 2019|publisher=NDTV|access-date=27 March 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://abpnews.abplive.in/bollywood/lok-sabha-election-2019bhojpuri-stars-ravi-kishan-and-dinesh-lal-yadav-joins-bjp-1096095|title=\u0932\u094b\u0915\u0938\u092d\u093e \u091a\u0941\u0928\u093e\u0935 2019: \u091a\u0941\u0928\u093e\u0935\u0940 \u0905\u0916\u093e\u0921\u093c\u0947 \u092e\u0947\u0902 \u0915\u0942\u0926\u0947 \u0928\u093f\u0930\u0939\u0941\u0906 \u0914\u0930 \u0930\u0935\u093f \u0915\u093f\u0936\u0928, \u091a\u0941\u0928\u093e\u0935\u094b\u0902 \u092e\u0947\u0902 \u091a\u0922\u093c\u0947\u0917\u093e \u092d\u094b\u091c\u092a\u0941\u0930\u0940 \u0930\u0902\u0917|date=27 March 2019|work=[[ABP News]]|access-date=27 March 2019}}</ref> On 3 April 2019 he got [[Lok Sabha|Loksabha]] ticket by [[Bharatiya Janata Party|Bhartiya Janata Party]] from [[Azamgarh (Lok Sabha constituency)]], he contested against [[Akhilesh Yadav]] [[List of Chief Ministers of Uttar Pradesh|(former chief minister of Uttar Pradesh]]).<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://m.jagran.com/politics/national-bjp-releases-16th-list-of-6-candidates-dinesh-lal-yadav-to-contest-from-azamgarh-against-akhilesh-yadav-19098939.html|title=\u092d\u093e\u091c\u092a\u093e \u0928\u0947 \u091c\u093e\u0930\u0940 \u0915\u0940 \u0909\u092e\u094d\u200d\u092e\u0940\u0926\u0935\u093e\u0930\u094b\u0902 \u0915\u0940 16\u0935\u0940\u0902 \u0932\u093f\u0938\u094d\u200d\u091f, \u0905\u0916\u093f\u0932\u0947\u0936 \u0915\u0947 \u0916\u093f\u0932\u093e\u092b \u0924\u093e\u0932 \u0920\u094b\u0915\u0947\u0902\u0917\u0947 \u0926\u093f\u0928\u0947\u0936 \u0932\u093e\u0932 \u092f\u093e\u0926\u0935 \u0909\u0930\u094d\u092b \u0928\u093f\u0930\u0939\u0941\u0906|date=3 April 2019|work=Jagran|access-date=7 April 2019|language=Hindi}}</ref> \n\nIn a TV interview when he was asked what will he do if he loses the 2019 General election, he replied 'One who can defeat me hasn't yet taken birth in this world'. This comment sparked political controversy. However he lost the election to [[Akhilesh Yadav]] by a margin of {{formatnum:259874}} votes.\n\n==Filmography==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+Key\n| style=\"background:#ffc;\"| {{dagger|alt=Films that have not yet been released}}\n| Denotes films that have not yet been released\n|}\n{| class=\"wi