ilm Awards 2018: Check out the list of winners|work=Zee News | date=23 July 2018}}</ref>\n|-\n|| [[International Bhojpuri Film Awards]] show London\n| Jublee Star Award\n| 2017\n|\n| {{won}}\n|<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.amarujala.com/photo-gallery/uttar-pradesh/varanasi/international-bhojpuri-film-award-ceremony-held-at-ondon?pageId=7|title=\u0932\u0902\u0926\u0928 \u092e\u0947\u0902 \u092d\u094b\u091c\u092a\u0941\u0930\u0940 \u092b\u093f\u0932\u094d\u092e \u0905\u0935\u093e\u0930\u094d\u0921 \u0938\u092e\u093e\u0930\u094b\u0939 \u0938\u0902\u092a\u0928\u094d\u0928, \u091c\u093e\u0928\u093f\u090f \u0915\u093f\u0938\u0947 \u092e\u093f\u0932\u093e \u0915\u094c\u0928 \u0938\u093e \u0905\u0935\u093e\u0930\u094d\u0921|newspaper=Amarujala| date=1 August 2018}}</ref>\n|-\n|| [[International Bhojpuri Film Awards]] show [[Dubai]]\n| Best Actor\n| 2016\n| ''[[Patna Se Pakistan]]''\n| {{won}}\n|<ref name=\"International Bhojpuri Film Awards\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.bhojpurixp.com/ibfa-awards-winners-list-2016/ |title=winners list}}</ref>\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{IMDb name|5815769}}\n*[https://hindi.movieskata.com/2019/07/nirahua-ke-bhojpuri-film.html Nirahau ( Dinesh lal yadav) all bhojpuri Bhojpuri Film List \u2013 Hindi Movies kata] \n\n{{commons category}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Yadav, Dinesh Lal}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Male actors in Bhojpuri cinema]]\n[[Category:1979 births]]\n[[Category:Bigg Boss contestants]]\n[[Category:People from Ghazipur]]\n[[Category:Indian actor-politicians]]\n", "name_user": "Jaywardhan009", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dinesh_Lal_Yadav"}
{"title_page": "Romani people in Bulgaria", "text_new": "{{short description|Constitute Europe's densest Romani minority}}\n{{distinguish|Romanians in Bulgaria}}\n{{Infobox ethnic group\n|group = Romani people in Bulgaria\n| native_name = <small>\u0446\u0438\u0433\u0430\u043d\u0438/\u0440\u043e\u043c\u0438 \u0432 \u0411\u044a\u043b\u0433\u0430\u0440\u0438\u044f</small><br/><small>Romane ando Bulgariya</small>\n| population = 325,343 (2011 Census; 4.4%)<ref name=Census2011final>{{cite web|url=http://www.nsi.bg/census2011/PDOCS2/Census2011final_en.pdf |title=2011 POPULATION CENSUS \u2013 MAIN RESULTS |website=Nsi.bg |accessdate=2016-05-21}}</ref>{{br}}{{br}}{{br}}[[European Commission]]'s average estimate: 750,000<ref name=eu1>{{cite web |title=Roma integration in Bulgaria |url=https://ec.europa.eu/info/policies/justice-and-fundamental-rights/combatting-discrimination/roma-and-eu/roma-integration-eu-country/roma-integration-bulgaria_en |website=European Commission - European Commission |language=en|date=2016-12-13 }}</ref><ref name=eu2>{{cite web |title=COMMUNICATION FROM THE COMMISSION TO THE EUROPEAN PARLIAMENT, THE COUNCIL, THE EUROPEAN ECONOMIC AND SOCIAL COMMITTEE AND THE COMMITTEE OF THE REGIONS |url=https://eur-lex.europa.eu/legal-content/EN/TXT/PDF/?uri=CELEX:52011DC0173&from=EN |publisher=EUROPEAN COMMISSION|page=15|date=April 2011|location=Brussels}}</ref> (last updated 14/09/2010)<ref>{{cite web|format=PDF|url= http://rm.coe.int/CoERMPublicCommonSearchServices/DisplayDCTMContent?documentId=0900001680088ea9|title=Roma and Travellers Team. TOOLS AND TEXTS OF REFERENCE. Estimates on Roma population in European countries|postscript= Council of Europe Roma and Travellers Division}}</ref><br />unofficial estimates: 800,000<ref>{{cite book |last1=Silverman |first1=Carol |title=Romani Routes: Cultural Politics and Balkan Music in Diaspora |date=2011 |publisher=Oxford University Press |isbn=9780199913350 |url=https://books.google.bg/books?id=LrPEBgAAQBAJ&pg=PT49&lpg=PT49#v=onepage&q&f=false }}</ref>\n|popplace= nationwide, rural and urban\n|rels = {{plainlist|\n* 2011 census in Bulgaria on those identified as Romani:<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nccedi.government.bg/print.php?category=92&id=2249&print=yes|title=\u041d\u0430\u0446\u0438\u043e\u043d\u0430\u043b\u0435\u043d \u0441\u044a\u0432\u0435\u0442 \u0437\u0430 \u0441\u044a\u0442\u0440\u0443\u0434\u043d\u0438\u0447\u0435\u0441\u0442\u0432\u043e \u043f\u043e \u0435\u0442\u043d\u0438\u0447\u0435\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0442\u0435 \u0438 \u0438\u043d\u0442\u0435\u0433\u0440\u0430\u0446\u0438\u043e\u043d\u043d\u0438\u0442\u0435 \u0432\u044a\u043f\u0440\u043e\u0441\u0438|website=Nccedi.government.bg|accessdate=2016-05-21|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160113062116/http://www.nccedi.government.bg/print.php?category=92&id=2249&print=yes|archivedate=13 January 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref><br />[[Irreligion|Unaffiliated]] (over 50%)\n*[[Bulgarian Orthodox Church|Bulgarian Orthodox]] (26%)\n*[[Islam]] (13%)\n*[[Protestantism]] (7%)\n}}\n|langs = {{plainlist|\n*[[Romani language|Romani]] (84%)\n*[[Bulgarian language|Bulgarian]] (7%)\n*[[Turkish language|Turkish]] (7%)<br />(by mother tongue; 2011 census)\n}}\n|related =\n}}\n{{Romani people}}\n\n[[File:Roma-sofia.JPG|right|thumb|150px|Romani wedding in Sofia, 1936]]\n[[File:Gypsy--Cart.jpg|thumb|150px|A Romani in wagon ([[Dolna Banya]])]]\n[[File:GypsyPartof-Filipovtsi.jpg|right|thumb|150px|The Romani ghetto in [[Filipovtsi]], [[Sofia]]]]\n[[File:NadezhdaSliven.jpg|right|thumb|150px|Roma people in Sliven]]\n[[File:\u0413\u0440\u0443\u043f\u0430 \"\u0420\u043e\u043c\u0441\u043a\u0438 \u0440\u0438\u0442\u043c\u0438\" - \u041f\u0440\u0430\u0437\u043d\u0438\u043a \u043d\u0430 \u0420\u043e\u0437\u0430\u0442\u0430.jpg|right|thumb|150px|Roma dancers]]\n \n'''[[Romani people]]''' ({{lang-bg|\u0446\u0438\u0433\u0430\u043d\u0438}} {{IPA-bg|tsi\u0261\u0250ni|}}, {{lang|bg|\u0440\u043e\u043c\u0438}} {{IPA-bg|r\u0254mi|}}){{fix|text=stress?}} '''in [[Bulgaria]]''' constitute Europe's densest Romani minority. The Romani people in Bulgaria \"speak Bulgarian, Turkish or Romani, depending on the region and their religious affiliations.\"\n<ref name=\"diaspora\">{{cite web|title=Can Romas be part of Indian diaspora?|publisher=khaleejtimes.com|url=http://www.khaleejtimes.com/international/india/can-romas-be-part-of-indian-diaspora|date=29 February 2016|accessdate=4 March 2016}}</ref>\n\nAccording to the latest census in 2011, the number of the Romani is 325,343, constituting 4.4% of the total population, in which only one ethnic group could be opted as an answer and 10% of the total population did not respond to the question on ethnic group. In a conclusive report of the census sent to [[Eurostat]], the authors of the census (the [[National Statistical Institute (Bulgaria)|National Statistical Institute of Bulgaria]]) identified the census results on ethnicity as a \"gross manipulation\".<ref>{{cite book |title=\u041a\u0440\u0438\u0442\u0438\u0447\u0435\u043d \u0434\u043e\u043a\u043b\u0430\u0434 \u043e\u0442\u043d\u043e\u0441\u043d\u043e \u041f\u0440\u0435\u0431\u0440\u043e\u044f\u0432\u0430\u043d\u0435\u0442\u043e \u043d\u0430 \u043d\u0430\u0441\u0435\u043b\u0435\u043d\u0438\u0435\u0442\u043e \u0438 \u0436\u0438\u043b\u0438\u0449\u043d\u0438\u044f \u0444\u043e\u043d\u0434, \u043f\u0440\u043e\u0432\u0435\u0434\u0435\u043d\u043e \u043a\u044a\u043c 1 \u0444\u0435\u0432\u0440\u0443\u0430\u0440\u0438 2011 \u0433\u043e\u0434\u0438\u043d\u0430 |url=http://www.nsi.bg/bg/content/12037/basic-page/%D0%BA%D1%80%D0%B8%D1%82%D0%B8%D1%87%D0%B5%D0%BD-%D0%B4%D0%BE%D0%BA%D0%BB%D0%B0%D0%B4-%D0%BE%D1%82%D0%BD%D0%BE%D1%81%D0%BD%D0%BE-%D0%BF%D1%80%D0%B5%D0%B1%D1%80%D0%BE%D1%8F%D0%B2%D0%B0%D0%BD%D0%B5%D1%82%D0%BE-%D0%BD%D0%B0-%D0%BD%D0%B0%D1%81%D0%B5%D0%BB%D0%B5%D0%BD%D0%B8%D0%B5%D1%82%D0%BE-%D0%B8-%D0%B6%D0%B8%D0%BB%D0%B8%D1%89%D0%BD%D0%B8%D1%8F-%D1%84%D0%BE%D0%BD%D0%B4}}</ref> The former head of the [[National Statistical Institute (Bulgaria)|National Statistical Institute of Bulgaria]], [[Reneta Indzhova]] claims to have been fired by the Bulgarian Prime Minister in 2014 for attempting to check the actual number of the Romani and implied that neither the census did enumerate the Romani, nor its statistics did provide the \"real data\".<ref>{{cite web |title=\u0411\u0438\u0432\u0448 \u043f\u0440\u0435\u043c\u0438\u0435\u0440 \u0431\u0435\u0437 \u043f\u0435\u043d\u0441\u0438\u044f. \u041a\u0430\u043a \u0436\u0438\u0432\u0435\u0435 \u0420\u0435\u043d\u0435\u0442\u0430 \u0418\u043d\u0434\u0436\u043e\u0432\u0430? |url=https://www.bnt.bg/bg/a/bivsh-premier-bez-pensiya-kak-zhivee-reneta-indzhova |website=\u0411\u041d\u0422 |language=bg}}</ref> Unlike other censuses under [[Eurostat]], which require the ethnic identification to be verified by a [[family tree]], in the Bulgarian census the ethnic identification is completely up to the voluntarily identification of the enumerated and not up to any further investigation by the enumerators.<ref>{{cite web |last1=PhD |first1=N.I.Todorov |title=The Portal of Pleven, Bulgaria - \u041f\u0440\u043e\u0444. \u041f\u0435\u0442\u044a\u0440 \u0418\u0432\u0430\u043d\u043e\u0432: \u0415\u0442\u043d\u0438\u0447\u0435\u0441\u043a\u0438 \u0434\u0435\u0444\u043e\u0440\u043c\u0430\u0446\u0438\u0438, \u043d\u0440\u0430\u0432\u0441\u0442\u0432\u0430\u043d\u0430 \u0434\u0435\u0433\u0440\u0430\u0434\u0430\u0446\u0438\u044f \u0438 \u0434\u0435\u043c\u043e\u0433\u0440\u0430\u0444\u0441\u043a\u0438 \u0441\u0440\u0438\u0432 |url=http://www.plevenonline.com/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=2132&Itemid=7 |website=www.plevenonline.com}}</ref>\n\nThe previous 2001 census recorded 370,908 Romani (4.7% of the population). The preceding 1992 census recorded 313,396 Romani (3.7% of the population), while a secret backstage 1992 census ordered by the [[Ministry of Interior (Bulgaria)|Ministry of Interior]] recorded a figure of 550,000 Romani (6.5% of the population); the Ministry of Interior ordered at least two other secret censuses to enumerate the Romani in denial, the one in 1980 recorded 523,519 Romani, while the one in 1989 recorded that the number of the Romani was 576,927 (6.5% of the population) and that over half of the Romani identified as Turks.<ref name=\"NUMBER OF ROMA\">{{cite book |last1=Ilieva |first1=Nadezhda |title=NUMBER OF ROMA ETHNIC GROUP IN BULGARIA FROM THE LIBERATION TO THE BEGINNING OF THE 21ST CENTURY (BASED ON REGULAR CENSUSES) (Part 1) |date=2012 |location=Bulgarian Academy of Sciences |page=75 |url=http://geoproblems.eu/wp-content/uploads/2016/01/2012_34/5_ilieva.pdf}}</ref> The majority of the estimated 200,000-400,000 Muslim Romani tend to identify themselves as ethnic [[Turks in Bulgaria|Turks]],<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://www.novinite.com/articles/130230/WikiLeaks%3A+Islam+and+Islamic+Extremism+in+Bulgaria |title=WikiLeaks: Islam and Islamic Extremism in Bulgaria - Novinite.com - Sofia News Agency |website=Novinite.com |date=2011-07-14 |accessdate=2016-05-21}}</ref> some deny their origin, or identify as Bulgarians.\n\nThe demographic collapse in Bulgaria affects only ethnic groups other than the Romani.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Roberts |first1=Lance W. |last2=Ferguson |first2=Barry |last3=B\u00f6s |first3=Mathias |title=Multicultural Variations: Social Incorporation in Europe and North America |url=https://books.google.bg/books?id=qfQB7mTcArIC&pg=PA243 |publisher=McGill-Queen's Press - MQUP |language=en |date=1 February 2013|isbn=9780773589056 }}</ref>\nAccording to data of the [[European Commission]], to which [[Eurostat]] belongs, the Romani in Bulgaria number 750,000 and they constitute 10.33% of the population.<ref name=eu1/><ref name=eu2/> An [[Bulgarian Academy of Sciences and Arts|NGO]] estimates that the number of the Romani in Bulgaria is twice as this high and their population grows by 35,000 a year.<ref name=dnes>{{cite web |url=https://dnes.dir.bg/obshtestvo/akademik-d-r-petar-ivanov-balgariya-se-obezbalgaryava-i-se-tsiganizira-topim-se-s-9-dushi-na-chas|title=\u0410\u043a\u0430\u0434\u0435\u043c\u0438\u043a \u0434-\u0440 \u041f\u0435\u0442\u044a\u0440 \u0418\u0432\u0430\u043d\u043e\u0432: \u0411\u044a\u043b\u0433\u0430\u0440\u0438\u044f \u0441\u0435 \u043e\u0431\u0435\u0437\u0431\u044a\u043b\u0433\u0430\u0440\u044f\u0432\u0430, \u0442\u043e\u043f\u0438\u043c \u0441\u0435 \u0441 9 \u0434\u0443\u0448\u0438 \u043d\u0430 \u0447\u0430\u0441|publisher=dir.bg}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=\u0410\u043a\u0430\u0434. \u041f\u0435\u0442\u044a\u0440 \u0418\u0432\u0430\u043d\u043e\u0432: \u0426\u0438\u0433\u0430\u043d\u0438\u0442\u0435 \u0443 \u043d\u0430\u0441 \u0441\u0430 1,5 \u043c\u043b\u043d. \u0434\u0443\u0448\u0438 \u0438 \u0433\u043b\u0430\u0432\u043e\u043b\u043e\u043c\u043d\u043e \u0441\u0435 \u0443\u0432\u0435\u043b\u0438\u0447\u0430\u0432\u0430\u0442 |url=http://bultimes.bg/akad-petur-ivanov-tsiganite-u-nas-sa-1-5-mln-dushi-i-glavolomno-se-uvelichavat/ |website=Bulgarian Times |language=bg-BG |date=16 August 2017}}</ref>\n\n== Overview ==\nIn Bulgaria, Romani are most commonly referred to as ''[[Tsigani]]'' (\u0446\u0438\u0433\u0430\u043d\u0438, pronounced {{IPA-bg|tsi\u0261\u0259ni|}}), an [[exonym]] that some Romani resent and others embrace. The form of the [[endonym]] ''Roma'' in [[Bulgarian language|Bulgarian]] is ''romi'' (\u0440\u043e\u043c\u0438). They are generally younger, according to the 2011 census they make up 10.2% of the population aged up to 9 years, on a note 14.9% of the total age group being non-respondents.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://censusresults.nsi.bg/Census/Reports/2/2/R7.aspx |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2012-06-13 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/68OJXNJMI?url=http://censusresults.nsi.bg/Census/Reports/2/2/R7.aspx |archivedate=13 June 2012 |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nsi.bg/bg/content/3078/\u043d\u0430\u0441\u0435\u043b\u0435\u043d\u0438\u0435-\u043f\u043e-\u043e\u0431\u043b\u0430\u0441\u0442\u0438-\u043e\u0431\u0449\u0438\u043d\u0438-\u043d\u0430\u0441\u0435\u043b\u0435\u043d\u0438-\u043c\u0435\u0441\u0442\u0430-\u0438-\u0432\u044a\u0437\u0440\u0430\u0441\u0442-\u043a\u044a\u043c-01022011-\u0433|title=Population by districts, municipalities, settlements and age as of 01.02.2011|website=Nsi.bg|accessdate=2017-08-24}}</ref>\n\nIn Bulgaria Roma are discriminated: 59% to 80% of non-Roma have negative feelings towards Roma.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=lw-Byail0EkC&pg=PA12&dq=ethnic+bulgarians+percent#v=onepage&q=ethnic%20bulgarians%20percent&f=false |title=Romani Routes: Cultural Politics and Balkan Music in Diaspora |author=Carol Silverman |page=12 |date=2012-05-24 |accessdate=2016-05-21|isbn=9780195300949 }}</ref>\nThey are emancipated social group, having higher crime, unemployment, birth, death and poverty rates, and not many of them attend school. Though most live in poverty, the Romani are represented in [[Bulgarian mafia]] and rich Romani crime bosses deal with drug trade and prostitution. Though most of them are officially unemployed, they have a high rate of child sex workers. Roma constitute the majority of prison population according to self-identification of inmates, with 7000 prisoners (70%) out of 10,000 in total.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.24chasa.bg/Article.asp?ArticleId=4583604 |title=\u0421\u0430\u043c\u043e 10 000 \u0432 \u0437\u0430\u0442\u0432\u043e\u0440\u0430, 7000 \u043e\u0442 \u0442\u044f\u0445 \u0441\u0430 \u0446\u0438\u0433\u0430\u043d\u0438 |website=24chasa.bg |date= |accessdate=2016-05-21}}</ref> According to 2002 data, the poverty rate among Romani is 61.8%, in contrast to a rate of 5.6% among Bulgarians.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=HP7eBMn6aGUC&pg=PT253&dq=bulgarians+turks+poverty+rate#v=onepage&q=bulgarians%20turks%20poverty%20rate&f=false |title=World Economic and Social Survey 2003: Trends and Policies in the World Economy - United Nations |accessdate=2016-05-21|isbn=9789211091434 |last1=Nations |first1=United |year=2003 }}</ref> In 1997, 84% of Bulgarian Romani lived under the poverty line, compared with 32% of ethnic Bulgarians.<ref>The Roma in Central and Eastern Europe: Avoiding the Dependency Trap, pp. 31, 39.</ref> In 1994, the poverty rate of Romani was estimated at 71.4%, compared with 15% for Bulgarians.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=O_tXHTK2kQUC&pg=PA47&dq=ethnic+bulgarians+constitute#v=onepage&q=ethnic%20bulgarians%20constitute&f=false |title=Poverty, Ethnicity, and Gender in Eastern Europe During the Market Transition |author1=Rebecca Jean Emigh |author2=Iv\u00e1n Szel\u00e9nyi |page=47 |accessdate=2016-05-21|isbn=9780275968816 |year=2001 }}</ref> The [[unemployment]] rate of non-Romani in Bulgaria was 25%, while of the Romani it was 65% in 2008, for instance in neighbouring Romania and Hungary the Romani had much lower unemployment rates - 14% and 21% respectively.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Revenga |first1=Ana |last2=Ringold |first2=Dena |last3=Tracy |first3=William Mart\u00edn |title=Poverty and Ethnicity: A Cross-country Study of Roma Poverty in Central Europe |date=2002 |publisher=World Bank Publications |isbn=9780821353394 |url=https://books.google.bg/books?id=3T4zvJ-KUaMC&pg=PA29 |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last1=Silverman |first1=Carol |title=Romani Routes: Cultural Politics and Balkan Music in Diaspora |date=2011 |publisher=Oxford University Press |isbn=9780199913350 |url=https://books.google.bg/books?id=LrPEBgAAQBAJ&pg=PT50 |language=en}}</ref> In 2016 only 23% of the Romani in Bulgaria are employed.<ref>{{cite web |title=EU agency study: Situation of Bulgarian Roma is appalling |url=https://sofiaglobe.com/2016/11/29/e-u-agency-study-results-the-situation-of-bulgarian-roma-is-appalling/ |website=The Sofia Globe |date=29 November 2016}}</ref> The unemployed enjoy more financial aid than other citizens, especially for children, which may have prompted the higher birth rates of the Romani.{{Citation needed|reason=Where is this stated? What's the evidence?|date=September 2019}} \n\nIn 2011 the share of Romani with [[university degree]] reached 0.3%, while 6.9% have [[secondary education]]; the same share was 22.8%/47.6% for Bulgarians.<ref>{{cite book|title=Changing Inequalities and Societal Impacts in Rich Countries |url=https://books.google.com/?id=MdfQAgAAQBAJ&pg=PA157&dq=bulgarians+turks+education+level#v=onepage&q=bulgarians%20turks%20education%20level&f=false|isbn=9780199687428|last1=Salverda|first1=Wiemer|last2=Checchi|first2=Daniele|last3=Marx|first3=Ive|last4=McKnight|first4=Abigail|year=2014}}</ref>\n\nThe Turks are more negative towards the Romani than the Bulgarians, with 30-50% rejecting various interactions and friendship with Romani. Although only 25% of Romani parents object to their children to be married with a Bulgarian and a Turk, only 4% of the Bulgarians and 6% of the Turks would marry a Romani person.<ref>{{cite web|title=Gallup|url=http://www.gallup-international.bg/bg/%D0%9F%D1%83%D0%B1%D0%BB%D0%B8%D0%BA%D0%B0%D1%86%D0%B8%D0%B8/2015/227-Hypotheses-on-Attitudes-Towards-the-Roma}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=\u0414\u0432\u0435 \u0442\u0440\u0435\u0442\u0438 \u043e\u0442 \u0431\u044a\u043b\u0433\u0430\u0440\u0438\u0442\u0435 \u043f\u0440\u0438\u0435\u043c\u0430\u0442 \u0435\u0442\u043d\u0438\u0447\u0435\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0442\u043e \u0440\u0430\u0437\u0434\u0435\u043b\u0435\u043d\u0438\u0435 \u0437\u0430 \u043d\u043e\u0440\u043c\u0430\u043b\u043d\u043e - Mediapool.bg|url=http://www.mediapool.bg/dve-treti-ot-balgarite-priemat-etnicheskoto-razdelenie-za-normalno-news134799.html|website=Mediapool.bg}}</ref> Romani are avoided by the majority traditionally, especially for marriage, however, there are ethnically mixed people with Gypsy and Bulgarian parents who are called \u0436\u043e\u0440\u0435\u0432\u0446\u0438 \"''zhorevtsi''\" (from the common name [[George (given name)|George]]).\n\nBulgaria participates in the [[Decade of Roma Inclusion]], an international initiative to improve the socio-economic status and social inclusion of Roma, with eight other governments committing themselves to \"work toward eliminating discrimination and closing the unacceptable gaps between Roma and the rest of society\".<ref>{{cite web\n| year = 2005\n| url = http://www.romadecade.org/itentcms/www/roma/index.php?content=77\n| title = Declaration of the Decade of Roma Inclusion 2005-2015\n| publisher = Decade of Roma Inclusion 2005-2015\n| accessdate = 2007-04-20}}</ref> The rights of the Romani people in the country are also represented by political parties and cultural organizations, most notably the [[Civil Union \"Roma\"]]. Noted Roma from Bulgaria include musicians [[Azis]], [[Sofi Marinova]] and [[Ivo Papazov]], surgeon Aleksandar Chirkov, politicians Toma Tomov and Tsvetelin Kanchev, footballer [[Marian Ognyanov]], and 1988 Olympic boxing champion [[Ismail Mustafov]].\n\n==History==\n===Origin===\nThe Romani people originate from [[North India|Northern]] [[India]],{{sfn|Hancock|2002 |p= [https://books.google.com/?id=MG0ahVw-kdwC&lpg=PP1&pg=PR20  xx] | ps =: \u2018While a nine century removal from India has diluted Indian biological connection to the extent that for some Romanian groups, it may be hardly representative today, Sarren (1976:72) concluded that we still remain together, genetically, Asian rather than European\u2019}}<ref name=\"IsabelMendizabal\">{{cite journal|first=Isabel|last=Mendizabal|title=Reconstructing the Population History of European Romani from Genome-wide Data|journal=Current Biology|date=6 December 2012|doi=10.1016/j.cub.2012.10.039|volume=22|issue=24|pages=2342\u20132349|pmid=23219723}}</ref><ref name=\"Comas\">{{cite news|author=Sindya N. Bhanoo|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2012/12/11/science/genomic-study-traces-roma-to-northern-india.html?_r=0|title=Genomic Study Traces Roma to Northern India|work=New York Times|date=11 December 2012}}</ref><ref>''Current Biology''.</ref><ref name=\"google1\">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=AS61CgAAQBAJ&pg=PA50&dq=Roma+Rajastan+Penjab#v=snippet&q=Roma%20Rajasthan%20Punjab&f=false |title=Flamenco on the Global Stage: Historical, Critical and Theoretical Perspectives |author1=K. Meira Goldberg |author2=Ninotchka Devorah Bennahum |author3=Michelle Heffner Hayes |page=50 |date= 2015-10-06|accessdate=2016-05-21|isbn=9780786494705 }}</ref><ref name=\"google2\">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=gyiTOcnb2yYC&pg=PA147&dq=Roma+Rajastan+Penjab#v=onepage&q=Roma%20Rajastan%20Penjab&f=false |title=World Music: Africa, Europe and the Middle East |author1=Simon Broughton |author2=Mark Ellingham |author3=Richard Trillo |page=147 |accessdate=2016-05-21|isbn=9781858286358 |year=1999 }}</ref> presumably from the northwestern Indian states [[Rajasthan]]<ref name=\"google1\"/><ref name=\"google2\"/> and [[Punjab, India|Punjab]].<ref name=\"google1\"/>\n\nThe linguistic evidence has indisputably shown that roots of Romani language lie in India: the language has grammatical characteristics of Indian languages and shares with them a big part of the basic lexicon, for example, body parts or daily routines.<ref name=\"mluvnice\">{{Citation | last1 = \u0160ebkov\u00e1 | first1 = Hana | last2 = \u017dlnayov\u00e1 | first2 = Edita | year = 1998 | url = http://rss.archives.ceu.hu/archive/00001112/01/118.pdf | title = N\u00e1stin mluvnice slovensk\u00e9 rom\u0161tiny (pro pedagogick\u00e9 \u00fa\u010dely) | place = \u00dast\u00ed nad Labem | publisher = Pedagogick\u00e1 fakulta Univerzity J. E. Purkyn\u011b v \u00dast\u00ed nad Labem | page = 4 | isbn = 978-80-7044-205-0 | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20160304024041/http://rss.archives.ceu.hu/archive/00001112/01/118.pdf | archivedate = 4 March 2016 | df = dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nMore exactly, Romani shares the basic lexicon with [[Hindi]] and [[Punjabi language|Punjabi]]. It shares many phonetic features with [[Marwari (language)|Marwari]], while its grammar is closest to [[Bengali language|Bengali]].<ref name=\"hub1995\">{{cite journal|first=Milena|last=H\u00fcbschmannov\u00e1|title=Roma\u0148i \u010dhib \u2013 rom\u0161tina: N\u011bkolik z\u00e1kladn\u00edch informac\u00ed o romsk\u00e9m jazyku|journal=Bulletin Muzea Romsk\u00e9 Kultury|issue=4/1995|year= 1995 |place=Brno|quote=Zat\u00edmco romsk\u00e1 lexika je bli\u017e\u0161\u00ed hind\u0161tin\u011b, marv\u00e1r\u0161tin\u011b, pand\u017e\u00e1b\u0161tin\u011b atd., v gramatick\u00e9 sf\u00e9\u0159e nach\u00e1z\u00edme mnoho shod s v\u00fdchodoindick\u00fdm jazykem, s beng\u00e1l\u0161tinou.}}</ref>\n\nGenetic findings in 2012 suggest the Romani originated in northwestern India and migrated as a group.<ref name=\"IsabelMendizabal\"/><ref name=\"Comas\"/><ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.livescience.com/40652-facts-about-roma-romani-gypsies.html|title=5 Intriguing Facts About the Roma|work=Live Science}}</ref>\nAccording to a genetic study in 2012, the ancestors of present [[Scheduled Castes and Scheduled Tribes]] populations of [[North India|northern]] [[India]], traditionally referred to collectively as the [[\u1e0coma]], are the likely ancestral populations of the modern European Roma.<ref>{{Citation | last1 = Rai | first1 = N | last2 = Chaubey | first2 = G | last3 = Tamang | first3 = R | last4 = Pathak | first4 = AK | last5 = Singh | first5 = VK | year = 2012 | title = The Phylogeography of Y-Chromosome Haplogroup H1a1a-M82 Reveals the Likely Indian Origin of the European Romani Populations | journal = PLoS ONE | volume = 7 | number = 11 | page = e48477 | doi = 10.1371/journal.pone.0048477 | pmid=23209554 | pmc=3509117}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2016, during the International Roma Conference, the [[Minister of External Affairs (India)|Indian Minister of External Affairs]] stated that the people of the Roma community were children of India. The conference ended with a recommendation to the [[Government of India]] to recognize the Roma community spread across 30 countries as a part of the [[Indian diaspora]].<ref name=\"diaspora\"/>\n\n===Migration to Bulgaria===\n[[File:Movimiento gitano.jpg|right|thumb|300px|The migration of the Romani people through the [[Middle East]] and [[North Africa]] to Europe. The key shows the century of arrival in that area, e.g., ''S.XII'' is the 12th century]]\nThe Romani people emigrated from [[North India|Northern]] [[India]],<ref name=\"google1\"/><ref name=\"google2\"/> presumably from the northwestern Indian states of [[Rajasthan]]<ref name=\"google1\"/><ref name=\"google2\"/> and [[Punjab, India|Punjab]],<ref name=\"google1\"/> possibly as early as 600 A.D. They emigrated to the Middle East and then reached the European continent.<ref name=\"books.google.ca\">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=fQ8vWih-rqwC&pg=PA189&lpg=PA189&dq=800,+000+roma+in+bulgaria+including+turkish+descent#v=onepage&q=800%2C%20000%20roma%20in%20bulgaria%20including%20turkish%20descent&f=false |title=Bulgaria (Other Places Travel Guide) |author1=Leslie Strnadel |author2=Patrick Erdley |page=189 |website=Books.google.ca |accessdate=2016-05-21|isbn=9780982261996 |year=2012 }}</ref> Moreover, \"the Roma (the name is the plural form of the word \u201cRom\u201d) moved from India at the beginning of the 12th century, reached Europe in the 14th century and Central Europe in the 15th century.\"<ref name=\"europa2\">{{cite web|url=http://ec.europa.eu/languages/policy/language-policy/documents/euromosaic-bulgaria_en.pdf |title=Bulgaria : Introduction : 1/37 |website=Ec.europa.eu |accessdate=2016-05-21}}</ref> The language of the Romani people is called Romani [roma\u0148i \u010dhib] or Romany. It is an [[Indo-Aryan languages|Indic]] (or [[Indo-Aryan languages|Indo-Aryan]]) language \u2014 like [[Sanskrit]], [[Hindi]], and [[Bengali language|Bengali]] \u2014 which belongs to the [[Indo-Iranian languages|Indo-Iranian]] branch of the Indo-European family. The language retains much of the Indic morphology, phonology and lexicon, while its syntax has been heavily influenced by contact with other languages.\n\nBulgarian ethnologists Elena Marushiakova and Veselin Popov assert that no direct evidence indicates when precisely the Romani first appeared in Bulgaria. While they mention that other Bulgarian and international scholars have associated the 1387 [[Medieval Bulgarian royal charters|Charter of Rila]] term ''Agoupovi Kleti'' with the Romani, they hold that the term refers to seasonal lodgings for mountain herdsmen. Instead, they delimit the mass settlement of Romani in Bulgarian territory between the 13th and 14th centuries, supporting this time frame with 13th- and 14th-century documents referring to Romani presence in the surrounding Balkan states.<ref>Marushiakova et al., ''Gypsies in the Ottoman Empire: a contribution to the history of the Balkans'', p. 19</ref> According to Bulgarian sociologist Ilona Tomova, Ottoman fiscal reports between the 15th and 17th centuries indirectly indicate Romani settlement in Bulgaria since the 13th century, as most registered Romani possessed [[Slavic languages|Slavonic]] names and were Christians.<ref name=\"tomova\">Tomova, ''Ethnic Dimensions of poverty in Bulgaria'', p. 15</ref>\n<blockquote>\"Although the largest Roma migration wave to the Bulgarian lands seems to have occurred in the 13th and 14th centuries, many Roma arrived with the Ottoman troops, accompanying army craftsmen and complementary military units.\"</blockquote>\n\nIn addition, during the 14th and 15th centuries, Muslim Romani arrived in Bulgaria with the [[Ottoman Empire|Ottoman]] rule, serving as auxiliaries, craftsmen, musicians and other professions.<ref name=\"tomova\"/><ref>Marushiakova et al., ''Gypsies in the Ottoman Empire: a contribution to the history of the Balkans'', p. 26</ref> Unlike the Ottoman Empire's other subjects in the [[Millet (Ottoman Empire)|millet]] system, Romani were governed based on their ethnicity, not their religious affiliation.<ref name=\"celik5\">Celik, ''Exploring Marginality in the Ottoman Empire: Gypsies or People of Malice (Ehl-i Fesad) as Viewed by the Ottomans Authors'', p. 5</ref> Ottoman tax records first mention Romani in the [[Nikopol, Bulgaria|Nikopol]] region, where 3.5% of the registered households were Romani. Under [[Mehmed II]]\u2019s reign, all Romani \u2014 Christian and Muslim \u2014 paid a poll-tax that was otherwise imposed only on non-Muslims.<ref>Marushiakova et al., ''Gypsies in the Ottoman Empire: a contribution to the history of the Balkans'', p. 27</ref>\n\nDuring the 16th century, [[Suleiman the Magnificent|Suleiman I]] enacted laws to prohibit the mingling of Muslim and Christian Romani and to administer taxes collected from the Romani: the 1530 ''Gypsies in the [[Rumelia]] Region Act'' and a 1541 law for the Romani [[sanjak|sancak]].<ref name=\"tomova\"/><ref>Marushiakova et al. [https://www.webcitation.org/query?url=http://www.geocities.com/~Patrin/bulgaria-hstry.htm&date=2009-10-26+00:36:53 \u201cA History of the Roma in Bulgaria\u201d]. Patrin Web Journal. Retrieved on 2009-03-01.</ref> [[Muslim Roma]]ni were taxed less than Christian Romani,<ref name=\"celik5\"/> yet they were taxed more than other Muslims for not adhering to Islamic laws and customs.<ref>Barany, ''The East European gypsies: regime change, marginality, and ethnopolitics'', p. 85</ref> Ottoman imperial assembly registers from 1558-1569 characterize the Romani as ''ehl-i fesad'' (people of malice), charging them with crimes such as prostitution, murder, theft, vagrancy and counterfeiting.<ref>Celik, ''Exploring Marginality in the Ottoman Empire: Gypsies or People of Malice (Ehl-i Fesad) as Viewed by the Ottomans Authors'', p. 20</ref>\n\n==Groups==\n[[File:BGRoma Language.png|thumb|Mother tongue with largest population of the Romani according to the 1946 census]]\n[[File:\u0420\u043e\u043c\u0440\u0435\u043b.png|thumb|Religion with largest population of the Romani according to the 1946 census before most converted to Christianity]]\nRoma in Bulgaria are not a unified community in culture and lifestyle. The most widespread group of the Romani in the country are the ''yerlii'' or the 'local Roma', who are in turn divided into Bulgarian Gypsies (''daskane roma'') and Turkish Gypsies (''horahane roma''). The former are mostly Christian ([[Eastern Orthodox]] and [[Protestant]]), while the latter are [[Muslim]]. Many of the Muslim Romani or the so-called Turkish Gypsies are usually well integrated in the ethnic [[Turks in Bulgaria|Turkish society in Bulgaria]]. Many possess Turkish ethnic identity and speak Turkish in addition to [[Romani language|Romani]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=QgTP2aKBO_0 |title=Discrimination Against Roma Muslims of Europe |publisher=YouTube |date=2010-03-04 |accessdate=2016-05-21}}</ref><ref name=\"Archived copy\">{{cite web|url=http://ec.europa.eu/languages/euromosaic/bg1_en.htm |title=Education and Training |accessdate=13 November 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120221065932/http://ec.europa.eu/languages/euromosaic/bg1_en.htm |archivedate=21 February 2012 }}</ref><ref name=\"europa2\"/> Moreover, between 50% and 75% of Romani are Muslims and more than 30 Romani dialects are reportedly used in the country. Muslim Romani can be divided into several linguistic groups: for example the Xoraxane Romani, who speak only Romani (although they know Turkish or Bulgarian) and identify themselves as Romani; Romani whose language is a mix between Romani and Turkish; Romani who use only Turkish (rarely Bulgarian and Romani); and Romani who can only speak Turkish, identifying themselves as either Romani or Turkish.<ref name=\"Archived copy\"/><ref name=\"europa2\"/>\n\nA subgroup of the Bulgarian Gypsies in southern Bulgaria, the ''Asparuhovi b\u00e2lgari'' ('Asparuh Bulgarians') \u2014 that is known also as ''stari b\u00e2lgari'' ('Old Bulgarians'), ''sivi g\u00e2l\u00e2bi'' ('Grey Doves', 'Grey Pigeons'), or ''demirdzhii'' \u2014 self-identify as the descendants of blacksmiths for Khan [[Asparukh of Bulgaria|Asparuh]]'s army.<ref>{{cite journal\n| url = http://balkanologie.revues.org/index1102.html\n|last=Slavkova\n|first=Magdalena\n| title = 'Being Gypsy in Europe. The Case of Bulgarian Roma Workers in Spain', Balkanologie\n|journal=Balkanologie. Revue d'\u00c9tudes Pluridisciplinaires\n| volume = X, \u2116 1\u20132\n|issue=Vol. XI, n\u00b0 1\u20132\n| date = December 2008\n| accessdate = 2009-02-24\n}}</ref><ref>{{cite book\n|author=Marushiakova, E., Popov, V.\n|editor=Acton, T.\n|title='Myth as Process', Scholarship and the Gypsy Struggle. Commitment in Romani Studies\n|year=2000\n|publisher=University of Hertfordshire Press\n|location=Hatfield\n|page=90\n|url=http://212.72.210.78/sr-www/files/Virtual%20library/Myth.pdf\n}}</ref><ref name=\"Pamporov\">{{cite book\n|last=Pamporov\n|first=Alexei\n|title=\u0420\u043e\u043c\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0442\u043e \u0432\u0441\u0435\u043a\u0438\u0434\u043d\u0435\u0432\u0438\u0435 \u0432 \u0411\u044a\u043b\u0433\u0430\u0440\u0438\u044f (Romani Daily Life in Bulgaria)\n|url=http://212.72.210.78/sr-www/files/Virtual%20library/Myth.pdf\n|accessdate=2009-02-24\n|year=2006\n|publisher=\u041c\u0435\u0436\u0434\u0443\u043d\u0430\u0440\u043e\u0434\u0435\u043d \u0446\u0435\u043d\u0442\u044a\u0440 \u0437\u0430 \u0438\u0437\u0441\u043b\u0435\u0434\u0432\u0430\u043d\u0435 \u043d\u0430 \u043c\u0430\u043b\u0446\u0438\u043d\u0441\u0442\u0432\u0430\u0442\u0430 \u0438 \u043a\u0443\u043b\u0442\u0443\u0440\u043d\u0438\u0442\u0435 \u0432\u0437\u0430\u0438\u043c\u043e\u0434\u0435\u0439\u0441\u0442\u0432\u0438\u044f\n|location=Sofia\n|language=Bulgarian\n|isbn=978-954-8872-63-8\n|pages=23\u20134, 62\u20133\n}}</ref> Some deny any connection with the Romani and most do not speak Romani.<ref name=\"Pamporov\"/>\n\nOther Romani groups include the conservative wandering ''[[Kalderash]]'' (sometimes referred to by the exonym ''Serbian Gypsies'') that are Eastern Orthodox and the ''[[Rudari]]'' (or ''Ludari'') who speak a dialect of [[Romanian language|Romanian]] and are known as ''Vlax Gypsies''. They are further subdivided into three groups by their traditional craft: the ''[[Ursari]]'' or ''Mechkari'' ('bear trainers'), the ''Lingurari'' or ''Kopanari'' ('carpenters', primarily associated with wooden bowls) and the ''[[L\u0103utari|Lautari]]'' ('musicians'). They migrated from [[Wallachia]] to present-day Bulgaria after 1856, the year of their liberation from [[Slavery in Romania|slavery]].\n\n==Demographics==\n[[File:Bulgaria roma 2001.PNG|right|thumb|250px|Romani minority in Bulgaria (census 2001)]]\n[[File:Bulgaria roma 2001 (average).PNG|right|thumb|250px|Romani minority in Bulgaria (census 2001)]]\n[[File:BGRoma.png|thumb|Distribution of the Romani in Bulgaria according to the 2001 census]]\n[[File:Bulgaria Ethnic composition Roma census 2011.svg|thumb|250px|Distribution of the Roma ethnic groups by municipalities in Bulgaria according to the 2011 census (represented as percentage of the municipality population)]]\n[[File:Bulgaria ethnic map.svg|thumb|Distribution of ethnic groups according to the 2011 census]]\nAccording to the 2011 census of the population of Bulgaria, there are 325,343 Gypsies in Bulgaria,<ref name=Census2011final/> or 4.4 percent. 180,266 of these are urban residents and 145,077 rural.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://censusresults.nsi.bg/Census/Reports/1/2/R7.aspx |format=PDF |title=Census Results 2011 |website=Censusresults.nsi.bg |accessdate=2016-05-21}}</ref>\n\nThe CIA Factbook claimed that 10% of the population is from unknown ethnic group, citing the 2011 census of the population of Bulgaria.\nIn 1992 of 5202 settlements there were registered Romani in 2095.\n\n22% of the Romani live in northeast, whereas settlements with prevailing Romani are located mostly in northeastern Bulgaria - mostly in [[Dobruja]]. According to the 1910 census, although in Bulgarian [[Dobruja]] there were settlements mostly populated even by [[Germans]] and [[Russians]], there wasn't a single settlement with Romani plurality there and also on the 1930 Romanian census of the same region.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://historymaps.ro/?tag=harta-etnica-cadrilater|title=harta etnica cadrilater \u2013 History Maps|website=Historymaps.ro|accessdate=15 December 2017}}</ref>\n\nWhile most of the Roma, 66%, are young children and adults up to 29 years old, the same group constitutes 37% among ethnic Bulgarians, while 5% of Roma are 60 years and over, Bulgarians are 22%.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=WRL1yhvtYVwC&pg=PA77&dq=ethnic+bulgarians+constitute#v=onepage&q=ethnic%20bulgarians%20constitute&f=false |title=Democratisation and the Prevention of Violent Conflict: Lessons Learned from ... |author=Jenny Engstr\u00f6m |page=77 |accessdate=2016-05-21|isbn=9780754674344 |year=2009 }}</ref>\n\nFrom the 1992 census to the 2001 census, the number of Romani in the country has increased by 57,512, or 18.4%. The Romani were only 2.8% in 1910 and 2.0% in 1920.<ref>{{cite web| url = http://balkans21.org/2002_1/euro1.html#7| title = Assoc. Prof. Dr. Kiril Kertikov, Europeisation or \"tsiganisation\" of Bulgaria. Institute of Sociology, Bulgarian Academy of Sciences.| publisher = In: Balkans'21, vol. 1, 2002, ISSN 1311-9583| language = Bulgarian| accessdate = 2007-08-03}}</ref>\n\nWhile the Romani are present in all [[provinces of Bulgaria]], their highest percentages are in [[Montana Province]] (12.5%) and [[Sliven Province]] (12.3%) and their smallest percentage is in [[Smolyan Province]], where they number 686<ref name=\"Ethnos\">{{cite web\n| year = 2011\n| url = http://censusresults.nsi.bg/Census/Reports/2/2/R7.aspx\n| title = \u041f\u0420\u0415\u0411\u0420\u041e\u042f\u0412\u0410\u041d\u0415 2011\n| publisher = National Statistical Institute\n| language = Bulgarian\n| accessdate = 2006-06-18\n}}</ref> \u2014 about 0.05% of the population.\n\n[[Varbitsa (town)|Varbitsa]] is possibly the only urban settlement where the Romani are the most numerous group. The largest Romani quarters are [[Stolipinovo]] in [[Plovdiv]] and [[Fakulteta]] in [[Sofia]]. The number of places where Romani constitute more than 50% of the population has doubled from the 1992 to the 2001 census.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! [[Provinces of Bulgaria|Province]]\n! Romani population (2011 census)\n! %\n|-\n| [[Blagoevgrad Province]] || 9,739 || 3.43%\n|-\n| [[Burgas Province]] || 18,424 || 4.97%\n|-\n| [[Dobrich Province]] || 15,323 || 8.81%\n|-\n| [[Gabrovo Province]] || 1,305 || 1.13%\n|-\n| [[Haskovo Province]] || 15,889 || 6.99%\n|-\n| [[Kardzhali Province]] || 1,296 || 0.99%\n|-\n| [[Kyustendil Province]] || 8,305 || 6.36%\n|-\n| [[Lovech Province]] || 5,705 || 4.38%\n|-\n| [[Montana Province]] || 18,228 || 12.71%\n|-\n| [[Pazardzhik Province]] || 20,350 || 8.27%\n|-\n| [[Pernik Province]] || 3,560 || 2.84%\n|-\n| [[Pleven Province]] || 9,961 || 4.15%\n|-\n| [[Plovdiv Province]] || 30,202 || 4.87%\n|-\n| [[Razgrad Province]] || 5,719 || 5.00%\n|-\n| [[Ruse Province]] || 8,615 || 3.98%\n|-\n| [[Shumen Province]] || 13,847 || 8.24%\n|-\n| [[Silistra Province]] || 5,697 || 5.11%\n|-\n| [[Sliven Province]] || 20,478 || 11.82%\n|-\n| [[Smolyan Province]] || 448 || 0.47%\n|-\n| [[Sofia City Province]] || 18,284 || 1.55%\n|-\n| [[Sofia Province]] || 17,079 || 7.40%\n|-\n| [[Stara Zagora Province]] || 24,018 || 7.80%\n|-\n| [[Targovishte Province]] || 7,767 || 7.27%\n|-\n| [[Varna Province]] || 13,432 || 3.16%\n|-\n| [[Veliko Tarnovo Province]] || 3,875 || 1.66%\n|-\n| [[Vidin Province]] || 7,282 || 7.66%\n|-\n| [[Vratsa Province]] || 10,082 || 6.18%\n|-\n| [[Yambol Province]] || 10,433 || 8.48%\n|-\n| '''Total'''<ref>{{cite web|author=WebDesign Ltd. www.webdesign-bg.eu |url=http://www.nsi.bg/census2011/pageen2.php?p2=179&sp2=209 |title=Population |website=Nsi.bg |date= |accessdate=2016-05-21}}</ref> || '''325,343''' || '''4.87 %'''<ref>The 2011 percentage of the ethnic groups is calculated only from those who answered the optional question on ethnicity (6,680,980 in total) and does not include around 700,000 people who did not answer the question.</ref>\n|}\n\n=== Age structure ===\n\nAlthough Roma constitute only 4.4 percent of the Bulgarian population, they constitute around 12 percent of all children aged between 0 and 9 years old according to the 2011 census.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://censusresults.nsi.bg/Census/Reports/2/2/R7.aspx |title=Format ref|website=censusresults.nsi.bg}}</ref> In some municipalities, like [[Valchedram Municipality|Valchedram]] in northwestern Bulgaria,<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.strategy.bg/FileHandler.ashx?fileId=3572|title= Data |website=strategy.bg}}</ref> more than the half of all children belong to the Roma ethnicity.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" width=\"400px\"\n!colspan=19 | Roma population by age group and share of total Bulgarian population as of 2011\n|-\n| '''Ethnic group''' || Total || 0 \u2013 9 || 10 \u2013 19 || 20 \u2013 29 || 30 \u2013 39 || 40 \u2013 49 || 50 \u2013 59 || 60 \u2013 69 || 70 \u2013 79 || 80+\n|-\n| '''Roma''' || '''325.343''' || '''67.568''' || '''59.511''' || '''59.442''' || '''49.572''' || '''37.723''' || '''28.411''' || '''15.833''' || '''6.031''' || '''1.252'''\n|-\n| ''Percentage of Bulgarian population'' || ''4.9'' || ''12.0'' || ''9.7'' || ''6.8'' || ''5.1'' || ''4.1'' || ''3.0'' || ''1.8'' || ''1.0'' || ''0.4''\n|}\n\n==Problems of exclusion and discrimination==\nIn a [[United Nations Development Programme|UNDP]]/[[International Labour Organization|ILO]] survey, Bulgarian Romani identified unemployment, economic hardship and discrimination in access to employment as major problems.\n\nThe Council of Europe body ECRI stated in its June 2003 third report on Bulgaria that Romani encounter \"serious difficulties in many spheres of life\", elaborating that:\n\n<blockquote>\"The main problems stem from the fact that the Roma districts are turning into ghettos. [...] Most Roma neighbourhoods consist of slums, precariously built without planning permission on land that often belongs to the municipalities [...]. As the Bulgarian authorities have not taken steps to address the situation, the people living in these districts have no access to basic public services, whether health care, public transport, waste collection or sanitation.\"<ref name=autogenerated1>{{cite web\n| year = 2003\n| url = http://hudoc.ecri.coe.int/XMLEcri/ENGLISH/Cycle_03/03_CbC_eng/BGR-CbC-III-2004-2-ENG.pdf\n| title = Third report on Bulgaria\n| publisher = Council of Europe - ECRI\n| accessdate = 2009-02-22\n}}</ref></blockquote>\n\nTo which the Bulgarian government answered officially in the same document:\n\n<blockquote>ECRI has correctly observed that members of the Roma community encounter \u201cserious difficulties\u201d \u201cin many spheres of life\u201d. The rest of this paragraph, however, regrettably contains sweeping, grossly inaccurate generalizations ... Due to various objective and subjective factors, many (but by no means all!) members of the Roma community found it particularly difficult to adapt to the new realities of the market economy. \u201c\u2026Romani mahala-dwellers are still captives of the past, holding onto and behaving according to preconceptions about the socialist welfare state that clash with the modern realities of a market economy and privatisation.\u201d (Skopje Report, p.6)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.per-usa.org/reports/Roma-Skopje.pdf |title=Archived copy |accessdate=20 September 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070710184636/http://www.per-usa.org/reports/Roma-Skopje.pdf |archivedate=10 July 2007 }}</ref>\n\nMore concretely, the allegation that the people living in these districts \u201chave no access to basic public services\u201d is largely inaccurate. Certain difficulties (though not remotely on the scale suggested) do exist in this regard, and the authorities are taking concrete measures to address them (see above). However, as the Advisor on Roma and Sinti issues at the OSCE, N. Gheorghe remarked during the Skopje meeting: \u201c\u2026many of the Roma confuse public services with rights to which they are entitled and which are guaranteed by the welfare state\u201d (Skopje Report, p.16). ...\n\nConcerning the issue of the electricity supply it should be noted that dwellers of such neighbourhoods sometimes refuse to pay their electricity bills. This attitude could at least in part be explained by the fact that \u201c\u2026Romani mahala-dwellers believe they have rights as citizens to electricity and other services, and that the state has an obligation to provide and to a large extent to subsidize them\u201d (Skopje Report, p. 7). In these circumstances electricity suppliers may find themselves with no other option but to \u201csometimes cut off\u201d the electricity supply in order to incite the consumers to commence honouring their debts. Such cut-offs are part of standard practice and the ethnic origin of the consumers is irrelevant in these cases.\n\nWith respect to welfare benefits, which allegedly \u201cin some cases, moreover, Roma do not receive\u201d while \u201cthey are entitled\u201d to them, it should be underscored that Bulgaria\u2019s social welfare legislation sets uniform objective criteria for access to welfare benefits for all citizens, irrespective of their ethnic origin (furthermore, any discrimination, including on ethnic grounds is expressly prohibited by law). The question of who is entitled or not entitled to welfare benefits is determined by the relevant services on the basis of a means test. Every single decision of these services must be (and is) in written form and clearly motivated. If a claimant is not satisfied with a decision, he/she is entitled to appeal it before the regional welfare office. Consequently, this allegation of ECRI is also erroneous.\"<ref name=autogenerated1 /></blockquote>\n\nA monitoring report by the [[Open Society Institute]] found that Romani children and teenagers are less likely to enroll in primary and secondary schools than the majority population and less likely to complete their education if they do. Between 60% and 77% of Romani children enroll in primary education (ages 6\u201315), compared to 90-94% of ethnic Bulgarians. Only 6%-12% of Romani teenagers enroll in secondary education (ages 16\u201319). The drop-out rate is significant, but hard to measure, as many are formally enrolled but rarely attend classes.<ref>{{cite web|year=2007 |url=http://www.eumap.org/topics/minority/reports/roma_education/reports/national/bulgaria/romeduc_bulgaria.pdf |title=Equal access to quality education for Roma, Bulgaria |pages=32\u201334 |publisher=Open Society Institute - EU Monitoring and Advocacy Program (EUMAP) |accessdate=2007-04-20 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090227083217/http://www.eumap.org/topics/minority/reports/roma_education/reports/national/bulgaria/romeduc_bulgaria.pdf |archivedate=27 February 2009 }}</ref>\n\nThe report also indicates that Romani children and teenagers attend de facto segregated \"Roma schools\" in majority-Romani neighbourhoods and villages. These \"Roma schools\" offer inferior quality education; many are in bad physical condition and lack necessary facilities such as computers. As a result, Romani literacy rates, already below those for ethnic Bulgarians, are much lower still for Romani who have attended segregated schools.<ref>Equal access to quality education for Roma, Bulgaria, pp. 18-20.</ref>\n\nThe official position of the Bulgarian government to such segregation is:\n\n<blockquote>\"There had never been a policy of \"segregation\" of Roma children in the national education system. The fact that in some neighbourhoods in certain towns particular schools were attended predominantly by pupils of Roma origin was an [[unintended consequence]] of the administrative division of the school system. According to the rules valid for all children irrespective of their ethnic origin, admittance to any public school was linked administratively to the domicile of the family. In neighbourhoods where the population was predominantly of Roma origin, this system produced schools, attended predominantly by pupils of Roma origin. It is precisely this situation that the authorities are taking special measures to rectify. Therefore, the word \u201csegregation\" with respect to Roma children is inaccurate.\"<ref name=autogenerated1/></blockquote>\n\nRomani children are often sent to special schools for children with intellectual disabilities or boarding schools for children with \"deviant behavior\" (so-called \"delinquent schools\"). According to reports of the [[Bulgarian Helsinki Committee]] (BHC), Romani made up half the number of students in schools for children with intellectual disabilities and about two-thirds of the students of the boarding schools, where the BHC found a variety of human rights abuses, including physical violence. In both sets of special schools, the quality of teaching is very poor and essential things such as desks, textbooks and teaching materials are inadequate or altogether lacking.<ref>{{cite book | last = Bulgarian Helsinki Committee | title = \u041f\u043e\u043c\u043e\u0449\u043d\u0438\u0442\u0435 \u0443\u0447\u0438\u043b\u0438\u0449\u0430 \u0432 \u0411\u044a\u043b\u0433\u0430\u0440\u0438\u044f (Remedial Schools in Bulgaria) | year = 2002 | isbn = 978-954-9738-14-8 }}{{cite book | last = Bulgarian Helsinki Committee | title = \u0421\u043e\u0446\u0438\u0430\u043b\u043d\u043e-\u043f\u0435\u0434\u0430\u0433\u043e\u0433\u0438\u0447\u0435\u0441\u043a\u0438 \u0438 \u0432\u044a\u0437\u043f\u0438\u0442\u0430\u0442\u0435\u043b\u043d\u0438 \u0443\u0447\u0438\u043b\u0438\u0449\u0430-\u0438\u043d\u0442\u0435\u0440\u043d\u0430\u0442\u0438 (Social-Pedagogical Boarding Schools and Correctional Boarding Schools) | year = 2001 | isbn = 978-954-9738-03-2 | pages = 391\u2013392 }}{{cite book | last = Bulgarian Helsinki Committee | title = \u0412 \u0438\u043c\u0435\u0442\u043e \u043d\u0430 \u0438\u043d\u0441\u0442\u0438\u0442\u0443\u0446\u0438\u044f\u0442\u0430: \u043f\u043e\u043f\u0440\u0430\u0432\u0438\u0442\u0435\u043b\u043d\u0438\u0442\u0435 \u0443\u0447\u0438\u043b\u0438\u0449\u0430 \u0432 \u0411\u044a\u043b\u0433\u0430\u0440\u0438\u044f (In the Name of the Institution: Schools for Delinquent Children in Bulgaria) | year = 2005 | isbn = 978-954-9738-21-6 }}</ref>\n\nOn two occasions, the European Committee of Social Rights has found violations of the [[European Social Charter]] in situations with Bulgaria's Romani population: in 2006, concerning right to housing,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.coe.int/t/dghl/monitoring/socialcharter/Complaints/CC31Merits_en.pdf |title=La Charte sociale europ\u00e9enne |website=Coe.int |date= |accessdate=2016-05-21}}</ref> and in 2008, concerning right to health<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.coe.int/t/dghl/monitoring/socialcharter/Complaints/CC46Merits_en.pdf |title=La Charte sociale europ\u00e9enne |website=Coe.int |date= |accessdate=2016-05-21}}</ref> \u2014 in both cases on complaints from the [[European Roma Rights Centre]].\n\n===Political representation===\nAccording to a report of POLITEA, \"For the most of the 1990s the only representation the Romani got was through the mainstream political parties. This was a very limited form of representation in which one or two Romani had a symbolic presence in Parliament during each term.\" The Bulgarian Constitution does not allow political parties based on ethnic, religious, or racist principles or ideology. However, \"Twenty one Roma political organizations were founded between 1997 and 2003 in Bulgaria [...]\".<ref name=autogenerated2>{{cite web\n |year        = 2005\n |url         = http://www.politeia.net/themes/citizenship_and_participation/the_political_representation_of_the_roma_minority_in_bulgaria_1990_2005\n |title       = The Political Representation of the Roma Minority in Bulgaria: (1990-2005)\n |publisher   = POLITEIA - Participation for Citizenship and Democracy in Europe\n |accessdate  = 2007-07-20\n |url-status     = dead\n |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20120420200504/http://www.politeia.net/Themes/citizenship_and_participation/the_political_representation_of_the_roma_minority_in_bulgaria_1990_2005\n |archivedate = 20 April 2012\n |df          = dmy-all\n}}</ref>\n\nIn the [[Bulgarian parliamentary election, 2005|2005 Bulgarian parliamentary election]], three Romani parties took part: [[Euroroma]], [[Movement for an Equal Public Model]] (as part of a coalition led by the [[Union of Democratic Forces (Bulgaria)|Union of Democratic Forces]]) and the Civil Union \"Roma\" (as part of a coalition led by the [[Bulgarian Socialist Party]]).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.2005izbori.org/results/index.html |title=Archived copy |accessdate=18 January 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110510063201/http://www.2005izbori.org/results/index.html |archivedate=10 May 2011 }}</ref>\nCurrently, the [[Movement for Rights and Freedoms]] represents<ref>{{cite web|url=https://surface.syr.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=1020&context=rel|title=Selected Muslim Historical Sites and Monuments in Bulgaria|publisher=Syracuse University Surface|website=surface.syr.edu}}</ref> Muslim Romani. The party relies on the biggest share of Romani people, 44%<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.trud.bg/Article.asp?ArticleId=4351106|title=\u041f\u0440\u043e\u0443\u0447\u0432\u0430\u043d\u0435 \u043d\u0430 \u0410\u043b\u0444\u0430 \u0420\u0438\u0441\u044a\u0440\u0447: 44% \u043e\u0442 \u0440\u043e\u043c\u0438\u0442\u0435 \u0441\u0430 \u043f\u043e\u0434\u043a\u0440\u0435\u043f\u0438\u043b\u0438 \u0414\u041f\u0421|website=Trud.bg|accessdate=2016-05-21|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304040117/http://www.trud.bg/Article.asp?ArticleId=4351106|archivedate=4 March 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref> of the total Romani vote, including non-Muslims.\n\nRomani people are considered second-class citizens by some Bulgarians.{{Sfn|Library of Congress|2006|p=6}} Romani integration programmes funded by the European Union have had mixed success.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.eubusiness.com/news-eu/bulgaria-politics.arz|title=Bulgarian Roma snub new EU plan for gypsy integration|publisher=EUbusiness|date=21 June 2011|accessdate=21 June 2012}}</ref>\n\n=== Public opinion ===\nThe 2019 [[Pew Research Center|Pew Research poll]] found that 68% of Bulgarians held unfavorable views of Roma.<ref>{{cite news |title=European Public Opinion Three Decades After the Fall of Communism \u2014 6. Minority groups |url=https://www.pewresearch.org/global/2019/10/14/minority-groups/ |work=Pew Research Center |date=14 October 2019}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[NGO Roma Together]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n===Sources===\n* {{cite book\n | last = Giordano\n | first = Christian\n | authorlink =\n |author2=Andrea Boscoboinik, Dobrinka Kostova, Milena Benovska-Sabkova, Annabel Chanteraud\n | year = 2003\n | title = Roma's Identities in Southeast Europe: Bulgaria\n | publisher = Ethnobarometer\n | location = Rome\n | url = http://www.ethnobarometer.org/pagine/bulgaria.pdf\n | isbn = 978-88-88235-03-5\n}}\n* {{cite book\n | last = Marushiakova\n | first = Elena\n | authorlink =\n |author2=Veselin Popov \n | year = 2001\n | title = Gypsies in the Ottoman Empire: a contribution to the history of the Balkans\n | publisher = Univ of Hertfordshire Press\n | location =\n | url =\n | isbn = 978-1-902806-02-0\n}}\n*{{cite book\n  | last = Marushiakova\n  | first = Elena\n  | authorlink =\n  |author2=Popov, Vesselin\n | title = Gypsies (Roma) in Bulgaria\n  | publisher = Peter Lang Verlag\n  | date = 1997\n | isbn = 978-0820432168}}\n* {{cite web\n | last = Slavkova\n | first = Magdalena\n |author2=Yeris Erolova\n | year = 2005\n | title = Study of the educational adjustment of the Roma population of Nova Zagora municipality\n | publisher = IMIR\n | language = Bulgarian\n | url = http://www.ncedi.government.bg/IMIR.htm\n}}\n* {{Cite journal\n | last = Tomova\n | first = Ilona\n | year = 1998\n | url = http://siteresources.worldbank.org/EXTGLDEVLEARN/Resources/IlonaTomova.pdf\n | title = This report is one of the studies commissioned for the social assessment of Bulgaria by the Social Development Team Europe and Central Asia Region\n | publisher = The World Bank\n | location =\n | page = 63\n | postscript = <!--None-->\n}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.nsi.bg/census2011/PDOCS2/Census2011final_en.pdf The 2011 census of the population of the Republic of Bulgaria]\n* [http://kolotoc.sk/en#/home The largest archive of gypsy music on the Internet - 100,000 gypsy songs]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20060821022409/http://www.studiiromani.org/ Studii Romani Specialized Library with Archive]\n* [http://www.cega.bg CEGA (\u0421\u0415\u0413\u0410) Foundation]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20080917180009/http://www.osaarchivum.org/db/fa/205-4-20-1.htm Bulgarian Subject Files - Social Issues: Minorities: Gypsys] Open Society Archives, Budapest\n* [http://www.romatogether.org/ Bulgarian Roma Grassroot NGO Roma Together]\n\n{{Ethnic groups in Bulgaria}}\n{{Romani diaspora}}\n{{Portal bar|Bulgaria}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2011}}\n\n[[Category:Ethnic groups in Bulgaria]]\n[[Category:Bulgarian people of Romani descent|*]]\n[[Category:Romani in Bulgaria| ]]\n[[Category:Articles with permanently dead external links]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Constitute Europe's densest Romani minority}}\n{{distinguish|Romanians in Bulgaria}}\n{{Infobox ethnic group\n|group = Romani people in Bulgaria\n| native_name = <small>\u0446\u0438\u0433\u0430\u043d\u0438/\u0440\u043e\u043c\u0438 \u0432 \u0411\u044a\u043b\u0433\u0430\u0440\u0438\u044f</small><br/><small>Romane ando Bulgariya</small>\n| population = 325,343 (2011 Census; 4.4%)<ref name=Census2011final>{{cite web|url=http://www.nsi.bg/census2011/PDOCS2/Census2011final_en.pdf |title=2011 POPULATION CENSUS \u2013 MAIN RESULTS |website=Nsi.bg |accessdate=2016-05-21}}</ref>{{br}}{{br}}{{br}}[[European Commission]]'s average estimate: 750,000<ref name=eu1>{{cite web |title=Roma integration in Bulgaria |url=https://ec.europa.eu/info/policies/justice-and-fundamental-rights/combatting-discrimination/roma-and-eu/roma-integration-eu-country/roma-integration-bulgaria_en |website=European Commission - European Commission |language=en|date=2016-12-13 }}</ref><ref name=eu2>{{cite web |title=COMMUNICATION FROM THE COMMISSION TO THE EUROPEAN PARLIAMENT, THE COUNCIL, THE EUROPEAN ECONOMIC AND SOCIAL COMMITTEE AND THE COMMITTEE OF THE REGIONS |url=https://eur-lex.europa.eu/legal-content/EN/TXT/PDF/?uri=CELEX:52011DC0173&from=EN |publisher=EUROPEAN COMMISSION|page=15|date=April 2011|location=Brussels}}</ref> (last updated 14/09/2010)<ref>{{cite web|format=PDF|url= http://rm.coe.int/CoERMPublicCommonSearchServices/DisplayDCTMContent?documentId=0900001680088ea9|title=Roma and Travellers Team. TOOLS AND TEXTS OF REFERENCE. Estimates on Roma population in European countries|postscript= Council of Europe Roma and Travellers Division}}</ref><br />unofficial estimates: 800,000<ref>{{cite book |last1=Silverman |first1=Carol |title=Romani Routes: Cultural Politics and Balkan Music in Diaspora |date=2011 |publisher=Oxford University Press |isbn=9780199913350 |url=https://books.google.bg/books?id=LrPEBgAAQBAJ&pg=PT49&lpg=PT49#v=onepage&q&f=false }}</ref>\n|popplace= nationwide, rural and urban\n|rels = {{plainlist|\n* 2011 census in Bulgaria on those identified as Romani:<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nccedi.government.bg/print.php?category=92&id=2249&print=yes|title=\u041d\u0430\u0446\u0438\u043e\u043d\u0430\u043b\u0435\u043d \u0441\u044a\u0432\u0435\u0442 \u0437\u0430 \u0441\u044a\u0442\u0440\u0443\u0434\u043d\u0438\u0447\u0435\u0441\u0442\u0432\u043e \u043f\u043e \u0435\u0442\u043d\u0438\u0447\u0435\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0442\u0435 \u0438 \u0438\u043d\u0442\u0435\u0433\u0440\u0430\u0446\u0438\u043e\u043d\u043d\u0438\u0442\u0435 \u0432\u044a\u043f\u0440\u043e\u0441\u0438|website=Nccedi.government.bg|accessdate=2016-05-21|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160113062116/http://www.nccedi.government.bg/print.php?category=92&id=2249&print=yes|archivedate=13 January 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref><br />[[Irreligion|Unaffiliated]] (over 50%)\n*[[Bulgarian Orthodox Church|Bulgarian Orthodox]] (26%)\n*[[Islam]] (13%)\n*[[Protestantism]] (7%)\n}}\n|langs = {{plainlist|\n*[[Romani language|Romani]] (84%)\n*[[Bulgarian language|Bulgarian]] (7%)\n*[[Turkish language|Turkish]] (7%)<br />(by mother tongue; 2011 census)\n}}\n|related =\n}}\n{{Romani people}}\n\n[[File:Roma-sofia.JPG|right|thumb|150px|Romani wedding in Sofia, 1936]]\n[[File:Gypsy--Cart.jpg|thumb|150px|A Romani in wagon ([[Dolna Banya]])]]\n[[File:GypsyPartof-Filipovtsi.jpg|right|thumb|150px|The Romani ghetto in [[Filipovtsi]], [[Sofia]]]]\n[[File:NadezhdaSliven.jpg|right|thumb|150px|Roma people in Sliven]]\n[[File:\u0413\u0440\u0443\u043f\u0430 \"\u0420\u043e\u043c\u0441\u043a\u0438 \u0440\u0438\u0442\u043c\u0438\" - \u041f\u0440\u0430\u0437\u043d\u0438\u043a \u043d\u0430 \u0420\u043e\u0437\u0430\u0442\u0430.jpg|right|thumb|150px|Roma dancers]]\n \n'''[[Romani people]]''' ({{lang-bg|\u0446\u0438\u0433\u0430\u043d\u0438}} {{IPA-bg|tsi\u0261\u0250ni|}}, {{lang|bg|\u0440\u043e\u043c\u0438}} {{IPA-bg|r\u0254mi|}}){{fix|text=stress?}} '''in [[Bulgaria]]''' constitute Europe's densest Romani minority. The Romani people in Bulgaria \"speak Bulgarian, Turkish or Romani, depending on the region and their religious affiliations.\"\n<ref name=\"diaspora\">{{cite web|title=Can Romas be part of Indian diaspora?|publisher=khaleejtimes.com|url=http://www.khaleejtimes.com/international/india/can-romas-be-part-of-indian-diaspora|date=29 February 2016|accessdate=4 March 2016}}</ref>\n\nAccording to the latest census in 2011, the number of the Romani is 325,343, constituting 4.4% of the total population, in which only one ethnic group could be opted as an answer and 10% of the total population did not respond to the question on ethnic group. In a conclusive report of the census sent to [[Eurostat]], the authors of the census (the [[National Statistical Institute (Bulgaria)|National Statistical Institute of Bulgaria]]) identified the census results on ethnicity as a \"gross manipulation\".<ref>{{cite book |title=\u041a\u0440\u0438\u0442\u0438\u0447\u0435\u043d \u0434\u043e\u043a\u043b\u0430\u0434 \u043e\u0442\u043d\u043e\u0441\u043d\u043e \u041f\u0440\u0435\u0431\u0440\u043e\u044f\u0432\u0430\u043d\u0435\u0442\u043e \u043d\u0430 \u043d\u0430\u0441\u0435\u043b\u0435\u043d\u0438\u0435\u0442\u043e \u0438 \u0436\u0438\u043b\u0438\u0449\u043d\u0438\u044f \u0444\u043e\u043d\u0434, \u043f\u0440\u043e\u0432\u0435\u0434\u0435\u043d\u043e \u043a\u044a\u043c 1 \u0444\u0435\u0432\u0440\u0443\u0430\u0440\u0438 2011 \u0433\u043e\u0434\u0438\u043d\u0430 |url=http://www.nsi.bg/bg/content/12037/basic-page/%D0%BA%D1%80%D0%B8%D1%82%D0%B8%D1%87%D0%B5%D0%BD-%D0%B4%D0%BE%D0%BA%D0%BB%D0%B0%D0%B4-%D0%BE%D1%82%D0%BD%D0%BE%D1%81%D0%BD%D0%BE-%D0%BF%D1%80%D0%B5%D0%B1%D1%80%D0%BE%D1%8F%D0%B2%D0%B0%D0%BD%D0%B5%D1%82%D0%BE-%D0%BD%D0%B0-%D0%BD%D0%B0%D1%81%D0%B5%D0%BB%D0%B5%D0%BD%D0%B8%D0%B5%D1%82%D0%BE-%D0%B8-%D0%B6%D0%B8%D0%BB%D0%B8%D1%89%D0%BD%D0%B8%D1%8F-%D1%84%D0%BE%D0%BD%D0%B4}}</ref> The former head of the [[National Statistical Institute (Bulgaria)|National Statistical Institute of Bulgaria]], [[Reneta Indzhova]] claims to have been fired by the Bulgarian Prime Minister in 2014 for attempting to check the actual number of the Romani and implied that neither the census did enumerate the Romani, nor its statistics did provide the \"real data\".<ref>{{cite web |title=\u0411\u0438\u0432\u0448 \u043f\u0440\u0435\u043c\u0438\u0435\u0440 \u0431\u0435\u0437 \u043f\u0435\u043d\u0441\u0438\u044f. \u041a\u0430\u043a \u0436\u0438\u0432\u0435\u0435 \u0420\u0435\u043d\u0435\u0442\u0430 \u0418\u043d\u0434\u0436\u043e\u0432\u0430? |url=https://www.bnt.bg/bg/a/bivsh-premier-bez-pensiya-kak-zhivee-reneta-indzhova |website=\u0411\u041d\u0422 |language=bg}}</ref> Unlike other censuses under [[Eurostat]], which require the ethnic identification to be verified by a [[family tree]], in the Bulgarian census the ethnic identification is completely up to the voluntarily identification of the enumerated and not up to any further investigation by the enumerators.<ref>{{cite web |last1=PhD |first1=N.I.Todorov |title=The Portal of Pleven, Bulgaria - \u041f\u0440\u043e\u0444. \u041f\u0435\u0442\u044a\u0440 \u0418\u0432\u0430\u043d\u043e\u0432: \u0415\u0442\u043d\u0438\u0447\u0435\u0441\u043a\u0438 \u0434\u0435\u0444\u043e\u0440\u043c\u0430\u0446\u0438\u0438, \u043d\u0440\u0430\u0432\u0441\u0442\u0432\u0430\u043d\u0430 \u0434\u0435\u0433\u0440\u0430\u0434\u0430\u0446\u0438\u044f \u0438 \u0434\u0435\u043c\u043e\u0433\u0440\u0430\u0444\u0441\u043a\u0438 \u0441\u0440\u0438\u0432 |url=http://www.plevenonline.com/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=2132&Itemid=7 |website=www.plevenonline.com}}</ref>\n\nThe previous 2001 census recorded 370,908 Romani (4.7% of the population). The preceding 1992 census recorded 313,396 Romani (3.7% of the population), while a secret backstage 1992 census ordered by the [[Ministry of Interior (Bulgaria)|Ministry of Interior]] recorded a figure of 550,000 Romani (6.5% of the population); the Ministry of Interior ordered at least two other secret censuses to enumerate the Romani in denial, the one in 1980 recorded 523,519 Romani, while the one in 1989 recorded that the number of the Romani was 576,927 (6.5% of the population) and that over half of the Romani identified as Turks.<ref name=\"NUMBER OF ROMA\">{{cite book |last1=Ilieva |first1=Nadezhda |title=NUMBER OF ROMA ETHNIC GROUP IN BULGARIA FROM THE LIBERATION TO THE BEGINNING OF THE 21ST CENTURY (BASED ON REGULAR CENSUSES) (Part 1) |date=2012 |location=Bulgarian Academy of Sciences |page=75 |url=http://geoproblems.eu/wp-content/uploads/2016/01/2012_34/5_ilieva.pdf}}</ref> The majority of the estimated 200,000-400,000 Muslim Romani tend to identify themselves as ethnic [[Turks in Bulgaria|Turks]],<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://www.novinite.com/articles/130230/WikiLeaks%3A+Islam+and+Islamic+Extremism+in+Bulgaria |title=WikiLeaks: Islam and Islamic Extremism in Bulgaria - Novinite.com - Sofia News Agency |website=Novinite.com |date=2011-07-14 |accessdate=2016-05-21}}</ref> some deny their origin, or identify as Bulgarians.\n\nThe demographic collapse in Bulgaria affects only ethnic groups other than the Romani.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Roberts |first1=Lance W. |last2=Ferguson |first2=Barry |last3=B\u00f6s |first3=Mathias |title=Multicultural Variations: Social Incorporation in Europe and North America |url=https://books.google.bg/books?id=qfQB7mTcArIC&pg=PA243 |publisher=McGill-Queen's Press - MQUP |language=en |date=1 February 2013|isbn=9780773589056 }}</ref>\nAccording to data of the [[European Commission]], to which [[Eurostat]] belongs, the Romani in Bulgaria number 750,000 and they constitute 10.33% of the population.<ref name=eu1/><ref name=eu2/> An [[Bulgarian Academy of Sciences and Arts|NGO]] estimates that the number of the Romani in Bulgaria is twice as this high and their population grows by 35,000 a year.<ref name=dnes>{{cite web |url=https://dnes.dir.bg/obshtestvo/akademik-d-r-petar-ivanov-balgariya-se-obezbalgaryava-i-se-tsiganizira-topim-se-s-9-dushi-na-chas|title=\u0410\u043a\u0430\u0434\u0435\u043c\u0438\u043a \u0434-\u0440 \u041f\u0435\u0442\u044a\u0440 \u0418\u0432\u0430\u043d\u043e\u0432: \u0411\u044a\u043b\u0433\u0430\u0440\u0438\u044f \u0441\u0435 \u043e\u0431\u0435\u0437\u0431\u044a\u043b\u0433\u0430\u0440\u044f\u0432\u0430, \u0442\u043e\u043f\u0438\u043c \u0441\u0435 \u0441 9 \u0434\u0443\u0448\u0438 \u043d\u0430 \u0447\u0430\u0441|publisher=dir.bg}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=\u0410\u043a\u0430\u0434. \u041f\u0435\u0442\u044a\u0440 \u0418\u0432\u0430\u043d\u043e\u0432: \u0426\u0438\u0433\u0430\u043d\u0438\u0442\u0435 \u0443 \u043d\u0430\u0441 \u0441\u0430 1,5 \u043c\u043b\u043d. \u0434\u0443\u0448\u0438 \u0438 \u0433\u043b\u0430\u0432\u043e\u043b\u043e\u043c\u043d\u043e \u0441\u0435 \u0443\u0432\u0435\u043b\u0438\u0447\u0430\u0432\u0430\u0442 |url=http://bultimes.bg/akad-petur-ivanov-tsiganite-u-nas-sa-1-5-mln-dushi-i-glavolomno-se-uvelichavat/ |website=Bulgarian Times |language=bg-BG |date=16 August 2017}}</ref>\n\n== Overview ==\nIn Bulgaria, Romani are most commonly referred to as ''[[Tsigani]]'' (\u0446\u0438\u0433\u0430\u043d\u0438, pronounced {{IPA-bg|tsi\u0261\u0259ni|}}), an [[exonym]] that some Romani resent and others embrace. The form of the [[endonym]] ''Roma'' in [[Bulgarian language|Bulgarian]] is ''romi'' (\u0440\u043e\u043c\u0438). They are generally younger, according to the 2011 census they make up 10.2% of the population aged up to 9 years, on a note 14.9% of the total age group being non-respondents.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://censusresults.nsi.bg/Census/Reports/2/2/R7.aspx |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2012-06-13 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/68OJXNJMI?url=http://censusresults.nsi.bg/Census/Reports/2/2/R7.aspx |archivedate=13 June 2012 |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nsi.bg/bg/content/3078/\u043d\u0430\u0441\u0435\u043b\u0435\u043d\u0438\u0435-\u043f\u043e-\u043e\u0431\u043b\u0430\u0441\u0442\u0438-\u043e\u0431\u0449\u0438\u043d\u0438-\u043d\u0430\u0441\u0435\u043b\u0435\u043d\u0438-\u043c\u0435\u0441\u0442\u0430-\u0438-\u0432\u044a\u0437\u0440\u0430\u0441\u0442-\u043a\u044a\u043c-01022011-\u0433|title=Population by districts, municipalities, settlements and age as of 01.02.2011|website=Nsi.bg|accessdate=2017-08-24}}</ref>\n\nIn Bulgaria Roma are discriminated: 59% to 80% of non-Roma have negative feelings towards Roma.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=lw-Byail0EkC&pg=PA12&dq=ethnic+bulgarians+percent#v=onepage&q=ethnic%20bulgarians%20percent&f=false |title=Romani Routes: Cultural Politics and Balkan Music in Diaspora |author=Carol Silverman |page=12 |date=2012-05-24 |accessdate=2016-05-21|isbn=9780195300949 }}</ref>\nThey are emancipated social group, having higher crime, unemployment, birth, death and poverty rates, and not many of them attend school. Though most live in poverty, the Romani are represented in [[Bulgarian mafia]] and rich Romani crime bosses deal with drug trade and prostitution. Though most of them are officially unemployed, they have a high rate of child sex workers. Roma constitute the majority of prison population according to self-identification of inmates, with 7000 prisoners (70%) out of 10,000 in total.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.24chasa.bg/Article.asp?ArticleId=4583604 |title=\u0421\u0430\u043c\u043e 10 000 \u0432 \u0437\u0430\u0442\u0432\u043e\u0440\u0430, 7000 \u043e\u0442 \u0442\u044f\u0445 \u0441\u0430 \u0446\u0438\u0433\u0430\u043d\u0438 |website=24chasa.bg |date= |accessdate=2016-05-21}}</ref> According to 2002 data, the poverty rate among Romani is 61.8%, in contrast to a rate of 5.6% among Bulgarians.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=HP7eBMn6aGUC&pg=PT253&dq=bulgarians+turks+poverty+rate#v=onepage&q=bulgarians%20turks%20poverty%20rate&f=false |title=World Economic and Social Survey 2003: Trends and Policies in the World Economy - United Nations |accessdate=2016-05-21|isbn=9789211091434 |last1=Nations |first1=United |year=2003 }}</ref> In 1997, 84% of Bulgarian Romani lived under the poverty line, compared with 32% of ethnic Bulgarians.<ref>The Roma in Central and Eastern Europe: Avoiding the Dependency Trap, pp. 31, 39.</ref> In 1994, the poverty rate of Romani was estimated at 71.4%, compared with 15% for Bulgarians.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=O_tXHTK2kQUC&pg=PA47&dq=ethnic+bulgarians+constitute#v=onepage&q=ethnic%20bulgarians%20constitute&f=false |title=Poverty, Ethnicity, and Gender in Eastern Europe During the Market Transition |author1=Rebecca Jean Emigh |author2=Iv\u00e1n Szel\u00e9nyi |page=47 |accessdate=2016-05-21|isbn=9780275968816 |year=2001 }}</ref> The [[unemployment]] rate of non-Romani in Bulgaria was 25%, while of the Romani it was 65% in 2008, for instance in neighbouring Romania and Hungary the Romani had much lower unemployment rates - 14% and 21% respectively.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Revenga |first1=Ana |last2=Ringold |first2=Dena |last3=Tracy |first3=William Mart\u00edn |title=Poverty and Ethnicity: A Cross-country Study of Roma Poverty in Central Europe |date=2002 |publisher=World Bank Publications |isbn=9780821353394 |url=https://books.google.bg/books?id=3T4zvJ-KUaMC&pg=PA29 |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last1=Silverman |first1=Carol |title=Romani Routes: Cultural Politics and Balkan Music in Diaspora |date=2011 |publisher=Oxford University Press |isbn=9780199913350 |url=https://books.google.bg/books?id=LrPEBgAAQBAJ&pg=PT50 |language=en}}</ref> In 2016 only 23% of the Romani in Bulgaria are employed.<ref>{{cite web |title=EU agency study: Situation of Bulgarian Roma is appalling |url=https://sofiaglobe.com/2016/11/29/e-u-agency-study-results-the-situation-of-bulgarian-roma-is-appalling/ |website=The Sofia Globe |date=29 November 2016}}</ref> The unemployed enjoy more financial aid than other citizens, especially for children, which may have prompted the higher birth rates of the Romani.{{Citation needed|reason=Where is this stated? What's the evidence?|date=September 2019}} \n\nIn 2011 the share of Romani with [[university degree]] reached 0.3%, while 6.9% have [[secondary education]]; the same share was 22.8%/47.6% for Bulgarians.<ref>{{cite book|title=Changing Inequalities and Societal Impacts in Rich Countries |url=https://books.google.com/?id=MdfQAgAAQBAJ&pg=PA157&dq=bulgarians+turks+education+level#v=onepage&q=bulgarians%20turks%20education%20level&f=false|isbn=9780199687428|last1=Salverda|first1=Wiemer|last2=Checchi|first2=Daniele|last3=Marx|first3=Ive|last4=McKnight|first4=Abigail|year=2014}}</ref>\n\nThe Turks are more negative towards the Romani than the Bulgarians, with 30-50% rejecting various interactions and friendship with Romani. Although only 25% of Romani parents object to their children to be married with a Bulgarian and a Turk, only 4% of the Bulgarians and 6% of the Turks would marry a Romani person.<ref>{{cite web|title=Gallup|url=http://www.gallup-international.bg/bg/%D0%9F%D1%83%D0%B1%D0%BB%D0%B8%D0%BA%D0%B0%D1%86%D0%B8%D0%B8/2015/227-Hypotheses-on-Attitudes-Towards-the-Roma}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=\u0414\u0432\u0435 \u0442\u0440\u0435\u0442\u0438 \u043e\u0442 \u0431\u044a\u043b\u0433\u0430\u0440\u0438\u0442\u0435 \u043f\u0440\u0438\u0435\u043c\u0430\u0442 \u0435\u0442\u043d\u0438\u0447\u0435\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0442\u043e \u0440\u0430\u0437\u0434\u0435\u043b\u0435\u043d\u0438\u0435 \u0437\u0430 \u043d\u043e\u0440\u043c\u0430\u043b\u043d\u043e - Mediapool.bg|url=http://www.mediapool.bg/dve-treti-ot-balgarite-priemat-etnicheskoto-razdelenie-za-normalno-news134799.html|website=Mediapool.bg}}</ref> Romani are avoided by the majority traditionally, especially for marriage, however, there are ethnically mixed people with Gypsy and Bulgarian parents who are called \u0436\u043e\u0440\u0435\u0432\u0446\u0438 \"''zhorevtsi''\" (from the common name [[George (given name)|George]]).\n\nBulgaria participates in the [[Decade of Roma Inclusion]], an international initiative to improve the socio-economic status and social inclusion of Roma, with eight other governments committing themselves to \"work toward eliminating discrimination and closing the unacceptable gaps between Roma and the rest of society\".<ref>{{cite web\n| year = 2005\n| url = http://www.romadecade.org/itentcms/www/roma/index.php?content=77\n| title = Declaration of the Decade of Roma Inclusion 2005-2015\n| publisher = Decade of Roma Inclusion 2005-2015\n| accessdate = 2007-04-20}}</ref> The rights of the Romani people in the country are also represented by political parties and cultural organizations, most notably the [[Civil Union \"Roma\"]]. Noted Roma from Bulgaria include musicians [[Azis]], [[Sofi Marinova]] and [[Ivo Papazov]], surgeon Aleksandar Chirkov, politicians Toma Tomov and Tsvetelin Kanchev, footballer [[Marian Ognyanov]], and 1988 Olympic boxing champion [[Ismail Mustafov]].\n\n==History==\n===Origin===\nThe Romani people originate from [[North India|Northern]] [[India]],{{sfn|Hancock|2002 |p= [https://books.google.com/?id=MG0ahVw-kdwC&lpg=PP1&pg=PR20  xx] | ps =: \u2018While a nine century removal from India has diluted Indian biological connection to the extent that for some Romanian groups, it may be hardly representative today, Sarren (1976:72) concluded that we still remain together, genetically, Asian rather than European\u2019}}<ref name=\"IsabelMendizabal\">{{cite journal|first=Isabel|last=Mendizabal|title=Reconstructing the Population History of European Romani from Genome-wide Data|journal=Current Biology|date=6 December 2012|doi=10.1016/j.cub.2012.10.039|volume=22|issue=24|pages=2342\u20132349|pmid=23219723}}</ref><ref name=\"Comas\">{{cite news|author=Sindya N. Bhanoo|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2012/12/11/science/genomic-study-traces-roma-to-northern-india.html?_r=0|title=Genomic Study Traces Roma to Northern India|work=New York Times|date=11 December 2012}}</ref><ref>''Current Biology''.</ref><ref name=\"google1\">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=AS61CgAAQBAJ&pg=PA50&dq=Roma+Rajastan+Penjab#v=snippet&q=Roma%20Rajasthan%20Punjab&f=false |title=Flamenco on the Global Stage: Historical, Critical and Theoretical Perspectives |author1=K. Meira Goldberg |author2=Ninotchka Devorah Bennahum |author3=Michelle Heffner Hayes |page=50 |date= 2015-10-06|accessdate=2016-05-21|isbn=9780786494705 }}</ref><ref name=\"google2\">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=gyiTOcnb2yYC&pg=PA147&dq=Roma+Rajastan+Penjab#v=onepage&q=Roma%20Rajastan%20Penjab&f=false |title=World Music: Africa, Europe and the Middle East |author1=Simon Broughton |author2=Mark Ellingham |author3=Richard Trillo |page=147 |accessdate=2016-05-21|isbn=9781858286358 |year=1999 }}</ref> presumably from the northwestern Indian states [[Rajasthan]]<ref name=\"google1\"/><ref name=\"google2\"/> and [[Punjab, India|Punjab]].<ref name=\"google1\"/>\n\nThe linguistic evidence has indisputably shown that roots of Romani language lie in India: the language has grammatical characteristics of Indian languages and shares with them a big part of the basic lexicon, for example, body parts or daily routines.<ref name=\"mluvnice\">{{Citation | last1 = \u0160ebkov\u00e1 | first1 = Hana | last2 = \u017dlnayov\u00e1 | first2 = Edita | year = 1998 | url = http://rss.archives.ceu.hu/archive/00001112/01/118.pdf | title = N\u00e1stin mluvnice slovensk\u00e9 rom\u0161tiny (pro pedagogick\u00e9 \u00fa\u010dely) | place = \u00dast\u00ed nad Labem | publisher = Pedagogick\u00e1 fakulta Univerzity J. E. Purkyn\u011b v \u00dast\u00ed nad Labem | page = 4 | isbn = 978-80-7044-205-0 | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20160304024041/http://rss.archives.ceu.hu/archive/00001112/01/118.pdf | archivedate = 4 March 2016 | df = dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nMore exactly, Romani shares the basic lexicon with [[Hindi]] and [[Punjabi language|Punjabi]]. It shares many phonetic features with [[Marwari (language)|Marwari]], while its grammar is closest to [[Bengali language|Bengali]].<ref name=\"hub1995\">{{cite journal|first=Milena|last=H\u00fcbschmannov\u00e1|title=Roma\u0148i \u010dhib \u2013 rom\u0161tina: N\u011bkolik z\u00e1kladn\u00edch informac\u00ed o romsk\u00e9m jazyku|journal=Bulletin Muzea Romsk\u00e9 Kultury|issue=4/1995|year= 1995 |place=Brno|quote=Zat\u00edmco romsk\u00e1 lexika je bli\u017e\u0161\u00ed hind\u0161tin\u011b, marv\u00e1r\u0161tin\u011b, pand\u017e\u00e1b\u0161tin\u011b atd., v gramatick\u00e9 sf\u00e9\u0159e nach\u00e1z\u00edme mnoho shod s v\u00fdchodoindick\u00fdm jazykem, s beng\u00e1l\u0161tinou.}}</ref>\n\nGenetic findings in 2012 suggest the Romani originated in northwestern India and migrated as a group.<ref name=\"IsabelMendizabal\"/><ref name=\"Comas\"/><ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.livescience.com/40652-facts-about-roma-romani-gypsies.html|title=5 Intriguing Facts About the Roma|work=Live Science}}</ref>\nAccording to a genetic study in 2012, the ancestors of present [[Scheduled Castes and Scheduled Tribes]] populations of [[North India|northern]] [[India]], traditionally referred to collectively as the [[\u1e0coma]], are the likely ancestral populations of the modern European Roma.<ref>{{Citation | last1 = Rai | first1 = N | last2 = Chaubey | first2 = G | last3 = Tamang | first3 = R | last4 = Pathak | first4 = AK | last5 = Singh | first5 = VK | year = 2012 | title = The Phylogeography of Y-Chromosome Haplogroup H1a1a-M82 Reveals the Likely Indian Origin of the European Romani Populations | journal = PLoS ONE | volume = 7 | number = 11 | page = e48477 | doi = 10.1371/journal.pone.0048477 | pmid=23209554 | pmc=3509117}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2016, during the International Roma Conference, the [[Minister of External Affairs (India)|Indian Minister of External Affairs]] stated that the people of the Roma community were children of India. The conference ended with a recommendation to the [[Government of India]] to recognize the Roma community spread across 30 countries as a part of the [[Indian diaspora]].<ref name=\"diaspora\"/>\n\n===Migration to Bulgaria===\n[[File:Movimiento gitano.jpg|right|thumb|300px|The migration of the Romani people through the [[Middle East]] and [[North Africa]] to Europe. The key shows the century of arrival in that area, e.g., ''S.XII'' is the 12th century]]\nThe Romani people emigrated from [[North India|Northern]] [[India]],<ref name=\"google1\"/><ref name=\"google2\"/> presumably from the northwestern Indian states of [[Rajasthan]]<ref name=\"google1\"/><ref name=\"google2\"/> and [[Punjab, India|Punjab]],<ref name=\"google1\"/> possibly as early as 600 A.D. They emigrated to the Middle East and then reached the European continent.<ref name=\"books.google.ca\">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=fQ8vWih-rqwC&pg=PA189&lpg=PA189&dq=800,+000+roma+in+bulgaria+including+turkish+descent#v=onepage&q=800%2C%20000%20roma%20in%20bulgaria%20including%20turkish%20descent&f=false |title=Bulgaria (Other Places Travel Guide) |author1=Leslie Strnadel |author2=Patrick Erdley |page=189 |website=Books.google.ca |accessdate=2016-05-21|isbn=9780982261996 |year=2012 }}</ref> Moreover, \"the Roma (the name is the plural form of the word \u201cRom\u201d) moved from India at the beginning of the 12th century, reached Europe in the 14th century and Central Europe in the 15th century.\"<ref name=\"europa2\">{{cite web|url=http://ec.europa.eu/languages/policy/language-policy/documents/euromosaic-bulgaria_en.pdf |title=Bulgaria : Introduction : 1/37 |website=Ec.europa.eu |accessdate=2016-05-21}}</ref> The language of the Romani people is called Romani [roma\u0148i \u010dhib] or Romany. It is an [[Indo-Aryan languages|Indic]] (or [[Indo-Aryan languages|Indo-Aryan]]) language \u2014 like [[Sanskrit]], [[Hindi]], and [[Bengali language|Bengali]] \u2014 which belongs to the [[Indo-Iranian languages|Indo-Iranian]] branch of the Indo-European family. The language retains much of the Indic morphology, phonology and lexicon, while its syntax has been heavily influenced by contact with other languages.\n\nBulgarian ethnologists Elena Marushiakova and Veselin Popov assert that no direct evidence indicates when precisely the Romani first appeared in Bulgaria. While they mention that other Bulgarian and international scholars have associated the 1387 [[Medieval Bulgarian royal charters|Charter of Rila]] term ''Agoupovi Kleti'' with the Romani, they hold that the term refers to seasonal lodgings for mountain herdsmen. Instead, they delimit the mass settlement of Romani in Bulgarian territory between the 13th and 14th centuries, supporting this time frame with 13th- and 14th-century documents referring to Romani presence in the surrounding Balkan states.<ref>Marushiakova et al., ''Gypsies in the Ottoman Empire: a contribution to the history of the Balkans'', p. 19</ref> According to Bulgarian sociologist Ilona Tomova, Ottoman fiscal reports between the 15th and 17th centuries indirectly indicate Romani settlement in Bulgaria since the 13th century, as most registered Romani possessed [[Slavic languages|Slavonic]] names and were Christians.<ref name=\"tomova\">Tomova, ''Ethnic Dimensions of poverty in Bulgaria'', p. 15</ref>\n<blockquote>\"Although the largest Roma migration wave to the Bulgarian lands seems to have occurred in the 13th and 14th centuries, many Roma arrived with the Ottoman troops, accompanying army craftsmen and complementary military units.\"</blockquote>\n\nIn addition, during the 14th and 15th centuries, Muslim Romani arrived in Bulgaria with the [[Ottoman Empire|Ottoman]] rule, serving as auxiliaries, craftsmen, musicians and other professions.<ref name=\"tomova\"/><ref>Marushiakova et al., ''Gypsies in the Ottoman Empire: a contribution to the history of the Balkans'', p. 26</ref> Unlike the Ottoman Empire's other subjects in the [[Millet (Ottoman Empire)|millet]] system, Romani were governed based on their ethnicity, not their religious affiliation.<ref name=\"celik5\">Celik, ''Exploring Marginality in the Ottoman Empire: Gypsies or People of Malice (Ehl-i Fesad) as Viewed by the Ottomans Authors'', p. 5</ref> Ottoman tax records first mention Romani in the [[Nikopol, Bulgaria|Nikopol]] region, where 3.5% of the registered households were Romani. Under [[Mehmed II]]\u2019s reign, all Romani \u2014 Christian and Muslim \u2014 paid a poll-tax that was otherwise imposed only on non-Muslims.<ref>Marushiakova et al., ''Gypsies in the Ottoman Empire: a contribution to the history of the Balkans'', p. 27</ref>\n\nDuring the 16th century, [[Suleiman the Magnificent|Suleiman I]] enacted laws to prohibit the mingling of Muslim and Christian Romani and to administer taxes collected from the Romani: the 1530 ''Gypsies in the [[Rumelia]] Region Act'' and a 1541 law for the Romani [[sanjak|sancak]].<ref name=\"tomova\"/><ref>Marushiakova et al. [https://www.webcitation.org/query?url=http://www.geocities.com/~Patrin/bulgaria-hstry.htm&date=2009-10-26+00:36:53 \u201cA History of the Roma in Bulgaria\u201d]. Patrin Web Journal. Retrieved on 2009-03-01.</ref> [[Muslim Roma]]ni were taxed less than Christian Romani,<ref name=\"celik5\"/> yet they were taxed more than other Muslims for not adhering to Islamic laws and customs.<ref>Barany, ''The East European gypsies: regime change, marginality, and ethnopolitics'', p. 85</ref> Ottoman imperial assembly registers from 1558-1569 characterize the Romani as ''ehl-i fesad'' (people of malice), charging them with crimes such as prostitution, murder, theft, vagrancy and counterfeiting.<ref>Celik, ''Exploring Marginality in the Ottoman Empire: Gypsies or People of Malice (Ehl-i Fesad) as Viewed by the Ottomans Authors'', p. 20</ref>\n\n==Groups==\n[[File:BGRoma Language.png|thumb|Mother tongue with largest population of the Romani according to the 1946 census]]\n[[File:\u0420\u043e\u043c\u0440\u0435\u043b.png|thumb|Religion with largest population of the Romani according to the 1946 census before most converted to Christianity]]\nRoma in Bulgaria are not a unified community in culture and lifestyle. The most widespread group of the Romani in the country are the ''yerlii'' or the 'local Roma', who are in turn divided into Bulgarian Gypsies (''daskane roma'') and Turkish Gypsies (''horahane roma''). The former are mostly Christian ([[Eastern Orthodox]] and [[Protestant]]), while the latter are [[Muslim]]. Many of the Muslim Romani or the so-called Turkish Gypsies are usually well integrated in the ethnic [[Turks in Bulgaria|Turkish society in Bulgaria]]. Many possess Turkish ethnic identity and speak Turkish in addition to [[Romani language|Romani]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=QgTP2aKBO_0 |title=Discrimination Against Roma Muslims of Europe |publisher=YouTube |date=2010-03-04 |accessdate=2016-05-21}}</ref><ref name=\"Archived copy\">{{cite web|url=http://ec.europa.eu/languages/euromosaic/bg1_en.htm |title=Education and Training |accessdate=13 November 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120221065932/http://ec.europa.eu/languages/euromosaic/bg1_en.htm |archivedate=21 February 2012 }}</ref><ref name=\"europa2\"/> Moreover, between 50% and 75% of Romani are Muslims and more than 30 Romani dialects are reportedly used in the country. Muslim Romani can be divided into several linguistic groups: for example the Xoraxane Romani, who speak only Romani (although they know Turkish or Bulgarian) and identify themselves as Romani; Romani whose language is a mix between Romani and Turkish; Romani who use only Turkish (rarely Bulgarian and Romani); and Romani who can only speak Turkish, identifying themselves as either Romani or Turkish.<ref name=\"Archived copy\"/><ref name=\"europa2\"/>\n\nA subgroup of the Bulgarian Gypsies in southern Bulgaria, the ''Asparuhovi b\u00e2lgari'' ('Asparuh Bulgarians') \u2014 that is known also as ''stari b\u00e2lgari'' ('Old Bulgarians'), ''sivi g\u00e2l\u00e2bi'' ('Grey Doves', 'Grey Pigeons'), or ''demirdzhii'' \u2014 self-identify as the descendants of blacksmiths for Khan [[Asparukh of Bulgaria|Asparuh]]'s army.<ref>{{cite journal\n| url = http://balkanologie.revues.org/index1102.html\n|last=Slavkova\n|first=Magdalena\n| title = 'Being Gypsy in Europe. The Case of Bulgarian Roma Workers in Spain', Balkanologie\n|journal=Balkanologie. Revue d'\u00c9tudes Pluridisciplinaires\n| volume = X, \u2116 1\u20132\n|issue=Vol. XI, n\u00b0 1\u20132\n| date = December 2008\n| accessdate = 2009-02-24\n}}</ref><ref>{{cite book\n|author=Marushiakova, E., Popov, V.\n|editor=Acton, T.\n|title='Myth as Process', Scholarship and the Gypsy Struggle. Commitment in Romani Studies\n|year=2000\n|publisher=University of Hertfordshire Press\n|location=Hatfield\n|page=90\n|url=http://212.72.210.78/sr-www/files/Virtual%20library/Myth.pdf\n}}</ref><ref name=\"Pamporov\">{{cite book\n|last=Pamporov\n|first=Alexei\n|title=\u0420\u043e\u043c\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0442\u043e \u0432\u0441\u0435\u043a\u0438\u0434\u043d\u0435\u0432\u0438\u0435 \u0432 \u0411\u044a\u043b\u0433\u0430\u0440\u0438\u044f (Romani Daily Life in Bulgaria)\n|url=http://212.72.210.78/sr-www/files/Virtual%20library/Myth.pdf\n|accessdate=2009-02-24\n|year=2006\n|publisher=\u041c\u0435\u0436\u0434\u0443\u043d\u0430\u0440\u043e\u0434\u0435\u043d \u0446\u0435\u043d\u0442\u044a\u0440 \u0437\u0430 \u0438\u0437\u0441\u043b\u0435\u0434\u0432\u0430\u043d\u0435 \u043d\u0430 \u043c\u0430\u043b\u0446\u0438\u043d\u0441\u0442\u0432\u0430\u0442\u0430 \u0438 \u043a\u0443\u043b\u0442\u0443\u0440\u043d\u0438\u0442\u0435 \u0432\u0437\u0430\u0438\u043c\u043e\u0434\u0435\u0439\u0441\u0442\u0432\u0438\u044f\n|location=Sofia\n|language=Bulgarian\n|isbn=978-954-8872-63-8\n|pages=23\u20134, 62\u20133\n}}</ref> Some deny any connection with the Romani and most do not speak Romani.<ref name=\"Pamporov\"/>\n\nOther Romani groups include the conservative wandering ''[[Kalderash]]'' (sometimes referred to by the exonym ''Serbian Gypsies'') that are Eastern Orthodox and the ''[[Rudari]]'' (or ''Ludari'') who speak a dialect of [[Romanian language|Romanian]] and are known as ''Vlax Gypsies''. They are further subdivided into three groups by their traditional craft: the ''[[Ursari]]'' or ''Mechkari'' ('bear trainers'), the ''Lingurari'' or ''Kopanari'' ('carpenters', primarily associated with wooden bowls) and the ''[[L\u0103utari|Lautari]]'' ('musicians'). They migrated from [[Wallachia]] to present-day Bulgaria after 1856, the year of their liberation from [[Slavery in Romania|slavery]].\n\n==Demographics==\n[[File:Bulgaria roma 2001.PNG|right|thumb|250px|Romani minority in Bulgaria (census 2001)]]\n[[File:Bulgaria roma 2001 (average).PNG|right|thumb|250px|Romani minority in Bulgaria (census 2001)]]\n[[File:BGRoma.png|thumb|Distribution of the Romani in Bulgaria according to the 2001 census]]\n[[File:Bulgaria Ethnic composition Roma census 2011.svg|thumb|250px|Distribution of the Roma ethnic groups by municipalities in Bulgaria according to the 2011 census (represented as percentage of the municipality population)]]\n[[File:Bulgaria ethnic map.svg|thumb|Distribution of ethnic groups according to the 2011 census]]\nAccording to the 2011 census of the population of Bulgaria, there are 325,343 Gypsies in Bulgaria,<ref name=Census2011final/> or 4.4 percent. 180,266 of these are urban residents and 145,077 rural.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://censusresults.nsi.bg/Census/Reports/1/2/R7.aspx |format=PDF |title=Census Results 2011 |website=Censusresults.nsi.bg |accessdate=2016-05-21}}</ref>\n\nThe CIA Factbook claimed that 10% of the population is from unknown ethnic group, citing the 2011 census of the population of Bulgaria.\nIn 1992 of 5202 settlements there were registered Romani in 2095.\n\n22% of the Romani live in northeast, whereas settlements with prevailing Romani are located mostly in northeastern Bulgaria - mostly in [[Dobruja]]. According to the 1910 census, although in Bulgarian [[Dobruja]] there were settlements mostly populated even by [[Germans]] and [[Russians]], there wasn't a single settlement with Romani plurality there and also on the 1930 Romanian census of the same region.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://historymaps.ro/?tag=harta-etnica-cadrilater|title=harta etnica cadrilater \u2013 History Maps|website=Historymaps.ro|accessdate=15 December 2017}}</ref>\n\nWhile most of the Roma, 66%, are young children and adults up to 29 years old, the same group constitutes 37% among ethnic Bulgarians, while 5% of Roma are 60 years and over, Bulgarians are 22%.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=WRL1yhvtYVwC&pg=PA77&dq=ethnic+bulgarians+constitute#v=onepage&q=ethnic%20bulgarians%20constitute&f=false |title=Democratisation and the Prevention of Violent Conflict: Lessons Learned from ... |author=Jenny Engstr\u00f6m |page=77 |accessdate=2016-05-21|isbn=9780754674344 |year=2009 }}</ref>\n\nFrom the 1992 census to the 2001 census, the number of Romani in the country has increased by 57,512, or 18.4%. The Romani were only 2.8% in 1910 and 2.0% in 1920.<ref>{{cite web| url = http://balkans21.org/2002_1/euro1.html#7| title = Assoc. Prof. Dr. Kiril Kertikov, Europeisation or \"tsiganisation\" of Bulgaria. Institute of Sociology, Bulgarian Academy of Sciences.| publisher = In: Balkans'21, vol. 1, 2002, ISSN 1311-9583| language = Bulgarian| accessdate = 2007-08-03}}</ref>\n\nWhile the Romani are present in all [[provinces of Bulgaria]], their highest percentages are in [[Montana Province]] (12.5%) and [[Sliven Province]] (12.3%) and their smallest percentage is in [[Smolyan Province]], where they number 686<ref name=\"Ethnos\">{{cite web\n| year = 2011\n| url = http://censusresults.nsi.bg/Census/Reports/2/2/R7.aspx\n| title = \u041f\u0420\u0415\u0411\u0420\u041e\u042f\u0412\u0410\u041d\u0415 2011\n| publisher = National Statistical Institute\n| language = Bulgarian\n| accessdate = 2006-06-18\n}}</ref> \u2014 about 0.05% of the population.\n\n[[Varbitsa (town)|Varbitsa]] is possibly the only urban settlement where the Romani are the most numerous group. The largest Romani quarters are [[Stolipinovo]] in [[Plovdiv]] and [[Fakulteta]] in [[Sofia]]. The number of places where Romani constitute more than 50% of the population has doubled from the 1992 to the 2001 census.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! [[Provinces of Bulgaria|Province]]\n! Romani population (2011 census)\n! %\n|-\n| [[Blagoevgrad Province]] || 9,739 || 3.43%\n|-\n| [[Burgas Province]] || 18,424 || 4.97%\n|-\n| [[Dobrich Province]] || 15,323 || 8.81%\n|-\n| [[Gabrovo Province]] || 1,305 || 1.13%\n|-\n| [[Haskovo Province]] || 15,889 || 6.99%\n|-\n| [[Kardzhali Province]] || 1,296 || 0.99%\n|-\n| [[Kyustendil Province]] || 8,305 || 6.36%\n|-\n| [[Lovech Province]] || 5,705 || 4.38%\n|-\n| [[Montana Province]] || 18,228 || 12.71%\n|-\n| [[Pazardzhik Province]] || 20,350 || 8.27%\n|-\n| [[Pernik Province]] || 3,560 || 2.84%\n|-\n| [[Pleven Province]] || 9,961 || 4.15%\n|-\n| [[Plovdiv Province]] || 30,202 || 4.87%\n|-\n| [[Razgrad Province]] || 5,719 || 5.00%\n|-\n| [[Ruse Province]] || 8,615 || 3.98%\n|-\n| [[Shumen Province]] || 13,847 || 8.24%\n|-\n| [[Silistra Province]] || 5,697 || 5.11%\n|-\n| [[Sliven Province]] || 20,478 || 11.82%\n|-\n| [[Smolyan Province]] || 448 || 0.47%\n|-\n| [[Sofia City Province]] || 18,284 || 1.55%\n|-\n| [[Sofia Province]] || 17,079 || 7.40%\n|-\n| [[Stara Zagora Province]] || 24,018 || 7.80%\n|-\n| [[Targovishte Province]] || 7,767 || 7.27%\n|-\n| [[Varna Province]] || 13,432 || 3.16%\n|-\n| [[Veliko Tarnovo Province]] || 3,875 || 1.66%\n|-\n| [[Vidin Province]] || 7,282 || 7.66%\n|-\n| [[Vratsa Province]] || 10,082 || 6.18%\n|-\n| [[Yambol Province]] || 10,433 || 8.48%\n|-\n| '''Total'''<ref>{{cite web|author=WebDesign Ltd. www.webdesign-bg.eu |url=http://www.nsi.bg/census2011/pageen2.php?p2=179&sp2=209 |title=Population |website=Nsi.bg |date= |accessdate=2016-05-21}}</ref> || '''325,343''' || '''4.87 %'''<ref>The 2011 percentage of the ethnic groups is calculated only from those who answered the optional question on ethnicity (6,680,980 in total) and does not include around 700,000 people who did not answer the question.</ref>\n|}\n\n=== Age structure ===\n\nAlthough Roma constitute only 4.4 percent of the Bulgarian population, they constitute around 12 percent of all children aged between 0 and 9 years old according to the 2011 census.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://censusresults.nsi.bg/Census/Reports/2/2/R7.aspx |title=Format ref|website=censusresults.nsi.bg}}</ref> In some municipalities, like [[Valchedram Municipality|Valchedram]] in northwestern Bulgaria,<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.strategy.bg/FileHandler.ashx?fileId=3572|title= Data |website=strategy.bg}}</ref> more than the half of all children belong to the Roma ethnicity.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" width=\"400px\"\n!colspan=19 | Roma population by age group and share of total Bulgarian population as of 2011\n|-\n| '''Ethnic group''' || Total || 0 \u2013 9 || 10 \u2013 19 || 20 \u2013 29 || 30 \u2013 39 || 40 \u2013 49 || 50 \u2013 59 || 60 \u2013 69 || 70 \u2013 79 || 80+\n|-\n| '''Roma''' || '''325.343''' || '''67.568''' || '''59.511''' || '''59.442''' || '''49.572''' || '''37.723''' || '''28.411''' || '''15.833''' || '''6.031''' || '''1.252'''\n|-\n| ''Percentage of Bulgarian population'' || ''4.9'' || ''12.0'' || ''9.7'' || ''6.8'' || ''5.1'' || ''4.1'' || ''3.0'' || ''1.8'' || ''1.0'' || ''0.4''\n|}\n\n==Problems of exclusion and discrimination==\nIn a [[United Nations Development Programme|UNDP]]/[[International Labour Organization|ILO]] survey, Bulgarian Romani identified unemployment, economic hardship and discrimination in access to employment as major problems.\n\nThe Council of Europe body ECRI stated in its June 2003 third report on Bulgaria that Romani encounter \"serious difficulties in many spheres of life\", elaborating that:\n\n<blockquote>\"The main problems stem from the fact that the Roma districts are turning into ghettos. [...] Most Roma neighbourhoods consist of slums, precariously built without planning permission on land that often belongs to the municipalities [...]. As the Bulgarian authorities have not taken steps to address the situation, the people living in these districts have no access to basic public services, whether health care, public transport, waste collection or sanitation.\"<ref name=autogenerated1>{{cite web\n| year = 2003\n| url = http://hudoc.ecri.coe.int/XMLEcri/ENGLISH/Cycle_03/03_CbC_eng/BGR-CbC-III-2004-2-ENG.pdf\n| title = Third report on Bulgaria\n| publisher = Council of Europe - ECRI\n| accessdate = 2009-02-22\n}}</ref></blockquote>\n\nTo which the Bulgarian government answered officially in the same document:\n\n<blockquote>ECRI has correctly observed that members of the Roma community encounter \u201cserious difficulties\u201d \u201cin many spheres of life\u201d. The rest of this paragraph, however, regrettably contains sweeping, grossly inaccurate generalizations ... Due to various objective and subjective factors, many (but by no means all!) members of the Roma community found it particularly difficult to adapt to the new realities of the market economy. \u201c\u2026Romani mahala-dwellers are still captives of the past, holding onto and behaving according to preconceptions about the socialist welfare state that clash with the modern realities of a market economy and privatisation.\u201d (Skopje Report, p.6)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.per-usa.org/reports/Roma-Skopje.pdf |title=Archived copy |accessdate=20 September 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070710184636/http://www.per-usa.org/reports/Roma-Skopje.pdf |archivedate=10 July 2007 }}</ref>\n\nMore concretely, the allegation that the people living in these districts \u201chave no access to basic public services\u201d is largely inaccurate. Certain difficulties (though not remotely on the scale suggested) do exist in this regard, and the authorities are taking concrete measures to address them (see above). However, as the Advisor on Roma and Sinti issues at the OSCE, N. Gheorghe remarked during the Skopje meeting: \u201c\u2026many of the Roma confuse public services with rights to which they are entitled and which are guaranteed by the welfare state\u201d (Skopje Report, p.16). ...\n\nConcerning the issue of the electricity supply it should be noted that dwellers of such neighbourhoods sometimes refuse to pay their electricity bills. This attitude could at least in part be explained by the fact that \u201c\u2026Romani mahala-dwellers believe they have rights as citizens to electricity and other services, and that the state has an obligation to provide and to a large extent to subsidize them\u201d (Skopje Report, p. 7). In these circumstances electricity suppliers may find themselves with no other option but to \u201csometimes cut off\u201d the electricity supply in order to incite the consumers to commence honouring their debts. Such cut-offs are part of standard practice and the ethnic origin of the consumers is irrelevant in these cases.\n\nWith respect to welfare benefits, which allegedly \u201cin some cases, moreover, Roma do not receive\u201d while \u201cthey are entitled\u201d to them, it should be underscored that Bulgaria\u2019s social welfare legislation sets uniform objective criteria for access to welfare benefits for all citizens, irrespective of their ethnic origin (furthermore, any discrimination, including on ethnic grounds is expressly prohibited by law). The question of who is entitled or not entitled to welfare benefits is determined by the relevant services on the basis of a means test. Every single decision of these services must be (and is) in written form and clearly motivated. If a claimant is not satisfied with a decision, he/she is entitled to appeal it before the regional welfare office. Consequently, this allegation of ECRI is also erroneous.\"<ref name=autogenerated1 /></blockquote>\n\nA monitoring report by the [[Open Society Institute]] found that Romani children and teenagers are less likely to enroll in primary and secondary schools than the majority population and less likely to complete their education if they do. Between 60% and 77% of Romani children enroll in primary education (ages 6\u201315), compared to 90-94% of ethnic Bulgarians. Only 6%-12% of Romani teenagers enroll in secondary education (ages 16\u201319). The drop-out rate is significant, but hard to measure, as many are formally enrolled but rarely attend classes.<ref>{{cite web|year=2007 |url=http://www.eumap.org/topics/minority/reports/roma_education/reports/national/bulgaria/romeduc_bulgaria.pdf |title=Equal access to quality education for Roma, Bulgaria |pages=32\u201334 |publisher=Open Society Institute - EU Monitoring and Advocacy Program (EUMAP) |accessdate=2007-04-20 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090227083217/http://www.eumap.org/topics/minority/reports/roma_education/reports/national/bulgaria/romeduc_bulgaria.pdf |archivedate=27 February 2009 }}</ref>\n\nThe report also indicates that Romani children and teenagers attend de facto segregated \"Roma schools\" in majority-Romani neighbourhoods and villages. These \"Roma schools\" offer inferior quality education; many are in bad physical condition and lack necessary facilities such as computers. As a result, Romani literacy rates, already below those for ethnic Bulgarians, are much lower still for Romani who have attended segregated schools.<ref>Equal access to quality education for Roma, Bulgaria, pp. 18-20.</ref>\n\nThe official position of the Bulgarian government to such segregation is:\n\n<blockquote>\"There had never been a policy of \"segregation\" of Roma children in the national education system. The fact that in some neighbourhoods in certain towns particular schools were attended predominantly by pupils of Roma origin was an [[unintended consequence]] of the administrative division of the school system. According to the rules valid for all children irrespective of their ethnic origin, admittance to any public school was linked administratively to the domicile of the family. In neighbourhoods where the population was predominantly of Roma origin, this system produced schools, attended predominantly by pupils of Roma origin. It is precisely this situation that the authorities are taking special measures to rectify. Therefore, the word \u201csegregation\" with respect to Roma children is inaccurate.\"<ref name=autogenerated1/></blockquote>\n\nRomani children are often sent to special schools for children with intellectual disabilities or boarding schools for children with \"deviant behavior\" (so-called \"delinquent schools\"). According to reports of the [[Bulgarian Helsinki Committee]] (BHC), Romani made up half the number of students in schools for children with intellectual disabilities and about two-thirds of the students of the boarding schools, where the BHC found a variety of human rights abuses, including physical violence. In both sets of special schools, the quality of teaching is very poor and essential things such as desks, textbooks and teaching materials are inadequate or altogether lacking.<ref>{{cite book | last = Bulgarian Helsinki Committee | title = \u041f\u043e\u043c\u043e\u0449\u043d\u0438\u0442\u0435 \u0443\u0447\u0438\u043b\u0438\u0449\u0430 \u0432 \u0411\u044a\u043b\u0433\u0430\u0440\u0438\u044f (Remedial Schools in Bulgaria) | year = 2002 | isbn = 978-954-9738-14-8 }}{{cite book | last = Bulgarian Helsinki Committee | title = \u0421\u043e\u0446\u0438\u0430\u043b\u043d\u043e-\u043f\u0435\u0434\u0430\u0433\u043e\u0433\u0438\u0447\u0435\u0441\u043a\u0438 \u0438 \u0432\u044a\u0437\u043f\u0438\u0442\u0430\u0442\u0435\u043b\u043d\u0438 \u0443\u0447\u0438\u043b\u0438\u0449\u0430-\u0438\u043d\u0442\u0435\u0440\u043d\u0430\u0442\u0438 (Social-Pedagogical Boarding Schools and Correctional Boarding Schools) | year = 2001 | isbn = 978-954-9738-03-2 | pages = 391\u2013392 }}{{cite book | last = Bulgarian Helsinki Committee | title = \u0412 \u0438\u043c\u0435\u0442\u043e \u043d\u0430 \u0438\u043d\u0441\u0442\u0438\u0442\u0443\u0446\u0438\u044f\u0442\u0430: \u043f\u043e\u043f\u0440\u0430\u0432\u0438\u0442\u0435\u043b\u043d\u0438\u0442\u0435 \u0443\u0447\u0438\u043b\u0438\u0449\u0430 \u0432 \u0411\u044a\u043b\u0433\u0430\u0440\u0438\u044f (In the Name of the Institution: Schools for Delinquent Children in Bulgaria) | year = 2005 | isbn = 978-954-9738-21-6 }}</ref>\n\nOn two occasions, the European Committee of Social Rights has found violations of the [[European Social Charter]] in situations with Bulgaria's Romani population: in 2006, concerning right to housing,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.coe.int/t/dghl/monitoring/socialcharter/Complaints/CC31Merits_en.pdf |title=La Charte sociale europ\u00e9enne |website=Coe.int |date= |accessdate=2016-05-21}}</ref> and in 2008, concerning right to health<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.coe.int/t/dghl/monitoring/socialcharter/Complaints/CC46Merits_en.pdf |title=La Charte sociale europ\u00e9enne |website=Coe.int |date= |accessdate=2016-05-21}}</ref> \u2014 in both cases on complaints from the [[European Roma Rights Centre]].\n\n===Political representation===\nAccording to a report of POLITEA, \"For the most of the 1990s the only representation the Romani got was through the mainstream political parties. This was a very limited form of representation in which one or two Romani had a symbolic presence in Parliament during each term.\" The Bulgarian Constitution does not allow political parties based on ethnic, religious, or racist principles or ideology. However, \"Twenty one Roma political organizations were founded between 1997 and 2003 in Bulgaria [...]\".<ref name=autogenerated2>{{cite web\n |year        = 2005\n |url         = http://www.politeia.net/themes/citizenship_and_participation/the_political_representation_of_the_roma_minority_in_bulgaria_1990_2005\n |title       = The Political Representation of the Roma Minority in Bulgaria: (1990-2005)\n |publisher   = POLITEIA - Participation for Citizenship and Democracy in Europe\n |accessdate  = 2007-07-20\n |url-status     = dead\n |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20120420200504/http://www.politeia.net/Themes/citizenship_and_participation/the_political_representation_of_the_roma_minority_in_bulgaria_1990_2005\n |archivedate = 20 April 2012\n |df          = dmy-all\n}}</ref>\n\nIn the [[Bulgarian parliamentary election, 2005|2005 Bulgarian parliamentary election]], three Romani parties took part: [[Euroroma]], [[Movement for an Equal Public Model]] (as part of a coalition led by the [[Union of Democratic Forces (Bulgaria)|Union of Democratic Forces]]) and the Civil Union \"Roma\" (as part of a coalition led by the [[Bulgarian Socialist Party]]).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.2005izbori.org/results/index.html |title=Archived copy |accessdate=18 January 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110510063201/http://www.2005izbori.org/results/index.html |archivedate=10 May 2011 }}</ref>\nCurrently, the [[Movement for Rights and Freedoms]] represents<ref>{{cite web|url=https://surface.syr.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=1020&context=rel|title=Selected Muslim Historical Sites and Monuments in Bulgaria|publisher=Syracuse University Surface|website=surface.syr.edu}}</ref> Muslim Romani. The party relies on the biggest share of Romani people, 44%<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.trud.bg/Article.asp?ArticleId=4351106|title=\u041f\u0440\u043e\u0443\u0447\u0432\u0430\u043d\u0435 \u043d\u0430 \u0410\u043b\u0444\u0430 \u0420\u0438\u0441\u044a\u0440\u0447: 44% \u043e\u0442 \u0440\u043e\u043c\u0438\u0442\u0435 \u0441\u0430 \u043f\u043e\u0434\u043a\u0440\u0435\u043f\u0438\u043b\u0438 \u0414\u041f\u0421|website=Trud.bg|accessdate=2016-05-21|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304040117/http://www.trud.bg/Article.asp?ArticleId=4351106|archivedate=4 March 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref> of the total Romani vote, including non-Muslims.\n\nRomani people are considered second-class citizens by some Bulgarians.{{Sfn|Library of Congress|2006|p=6}} Romani integration programmes funded by the European Union have had mixed success.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.eubusiness.com/news-eu/bulgaria-politics.arz|title=Bulgarian Roma snub new EU plan for gypsy integration|publisher=EUbusiness|date=21 June 2011|accessdate=21 June 2012}}</ref>\n\n=== Public opinion ===\nThe 2019 [[Pew Research Center|Pew Research poll]] poll found that 68% of Bulgarians held unfavorable views of Roma.<ref>{{cite news |title=European Public Opinion Three Decades After the Fall of Communism \u2014 6. Minority groups |url=https://www.pewresearch.org/global/2019/10/14/minority-groups/ |work=Pew Research Center |date=14 October 2019}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[NGO Roma Together]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n===Sources===\n* {{cite book\n | last = Giordano\n | first = Christian\n | authorlink =\n |author2=Andrea Boscoboinik, Dobrinka Kostova, Milena Benovska-Sabkova, Annabel Chanteraud\n | year = 2003\n | title = Roma's Identities in Southeast Europe: Bulgaria\n | publisher = Ethnobarometer\n | location = Rome\n | url = http://www.ethnobarometer.org/pagine/bulgaria.pdf\n | isbn = 978-88-88235-03-5\n}}\n* {{cite book\n | last = Marushiakova\n | first = Elena\n | authorlink =\n |author2=Veselin Popov \n | year = 2001\n | title = Gypsies in the Ottoman Empire: a contribution to the history of the Balkans\n | publisher = Univ of Hertfordshire Press\n | location =\n | url =\n | isbn = 978-1-902806-02-0\n}}\n*{{cite book\n  | last = Marushiakova\n  | first = Elena\n  | authorlink =\n  |author2=Popov, Vesselin\n | title = Gypsies (Roma) in Bulgaria\n  | publisher = Peter Lang Verlag\n  | date = 1997\n | isbn = 978-0820432168}}\n* {{cite web\n | last = Slavkova\n | first = Magdalena\n |author2=Yeris Erolova\n | year = 2005\n | title = Study of the educational adjustment of the Roma population of Nova Zagora municipality\n | publisher = IMIR\n | language = Bulgarian\n | url = http://www.ncedi.government.bg/IMIR.htm\n}}\n* {{Cite journal\n | last = Tomova\n | first = Ilona\n | year = 1998\n | url = http://siteresources.worldbank.org/EXTGLDEVLEARN/Resources/IlonaTomova.pdf\n | title = This report is on